<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Additive properties (mass, volume, moles) sum directly when substances mix; non-additive properties (concentration, density, temperature) require weighted averaging or calculation
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For concentration mixing: calculate total solute (sum of all components), calculate total volume, then divide
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Weighted average formula for concentrations: C_final = (V₁C₁ + V₂C₂)/(V₁ + V₂), works for equal or different volumes
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Dilution equation C₁V₁ = C₂V₂ applies when adding pure solvent; solute amount stays constant while volume increases
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Final concentration must be between starting concentrations (or at one extreme if one component dominates)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For thermal mixing of same substance: T_final = (m₁T₁ + m₂T₂)/(m₁ + m₂), final temperature between starting values
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Heat exchange principle: heat lost by hot substance equals heat gained by cold substance at equilibrium
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Substances with higher (mass × specific heat) dominate final temperature in thermal mixing
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For sequential mixing, calculate result after each step; for multiple components, track total solute from all sources
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Always verify reasonableness: final value should be within expected range based on components and their proportions
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T18:09:19.214163+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (c4c5f2f4-110d-472e-b55f-423393fe7f9a, 5d8200a8-51f5-4c9e-9def-89ae511e3544, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Understanding <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">lines and coordinate geometry</strong> is essential for ACT Math success. These concepts appear in approximately 6-8 questions on every ACT test. Whether finding slope, writing equations of lines, or calculating distance and midpoint, mastering these skills will significantly boost your score.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">Key Concepts</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">This section covers the essential concepts you need to master for Topic 2.3 - Lines & Coordinate Geometry. Each concept is explained clearly with ACT-style examples.</p>

<p style="height: 1px; margin: 0; padding: 0;"></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; visibility: hidden; height: 0; margin: 0; padding: 0; overflow: hidden;">.</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">Key Takeaways</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Master the fundamental concepts for this topic
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Practice with ACT-style problems
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Apply test-taking strategies
  </li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-16T01:07:57.807204+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (f70cb875-b8c7-4077-9844-7ceb2c0a5f59, 632bb4f7-5118-49ec-819b-b3cf20a91a4b, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Science
Topic: Multiple Figures Questions
Lesson Key: multiple-figures
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Multiple figures questions require you to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">synthesize information</strong> from two or more different figures, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">compare data across tables and graphs</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">identify relationships between variables</strong> shown in separate visualizations, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">integrate data from multiple sources</strong> to answer complex questions. Unlike single-figure questions that test your ability to read one graph or table, multiple figures questions assess your capacity to navigate between different representations, track variables across formats, combine numerical data with visual trends, and draw conclusions that require information from more than one source. This lesson teaches you systematic approaches for handling questions that reference multiple figures, explains how to efficiently move between figures without losing track of information, provides strategies for identifying which figures contain the data you need, and shows you how to organize multi-figure information to answer questions accurately and quickly.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Recognizing and Approaching Multiple Figures Questions
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Multiple figures questions</strong> explicitly or implicitly require data from <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">two or more separate figures</strong>. These questions test your ability to integrate information across different data presentations and understand relationships between variables shown separately.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Identifying Multiple Figures Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Multiple figures questions can be <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">explicitly stated</strong> or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">implicitly required</strong>. Explicit questions include clear references: "Based on Figures 1 and 2, which statement is correct?", "According to Table 1 and Graph 1, at which temperature...", or "Using data from both Figure 1 and Figure 3...". These questions tell you directly that you need multiple sources. Implicit questions require multiple figures even though they don''t explicitly say so: "At what pH was oxygen concentration highest?" might seem like a single-figure question, but if pH data is in Table 1 and oxygen concentration is in Figure 2, you need both. To identify implicit multiple-figure questions: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read the question carefully</strong> and identify what variables or data points are mentioned. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check which figures contain each piece of information</strong>. If different variables are in different figures, you''ll need both. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for connecting variables</strong> that appear in multiple figures—these are often the key to linking data across sources. Understanding whether a question requires one or multiple figures prevents you from wasting time searching for data that doesn''t exist in a single source.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Two-Pass Reading Strategy for Complex Passages
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When a passage contains <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">three or more figures</strong>, use a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">two-pass reading strategy</strong> to build mental organization: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Pass 1 (Initial overview, 30-45 seconds):</strong> (1) Read the passage introduction to understand the general experiment or topic. (2) Quickly note how many figures there are and what type each is (table, line graph, bar graph, diagram, etc.). (3) For each figure, read only the title and axis labels to understand what variables are shown. (4) Identify any connecting variables that appear in multiple figures (for example, "temperature" might be shown in both Figure 1 and Figure 2). <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Pass 2 (Question-driven detail reading):</strong> (5) Read each question and identify which figure(s) it requires. (6) Return to those specific figures and examine them in detail only when needed to answer the question. This two-pass strategy prevents information overload. Rather than trying to memorize all data from all figures upfront, you build a mental map of where information lives, then retrieve it on-demand. This is much more efficient than studying every figure in detail before seeing the questions, and it prevents confusion between similar data in different figures.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Creating a Mental Map of Figure Organization
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
As you examine multiple figures, build a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">mental map</strong> of what information each figure contains. This mental organization helps you quickly locate needed data during questions. To build your map: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Associate each figure with its primary variables</strong>. For example: "Figure 1 = temperature vs. pressure", "Figure 2 = temperature vs. volume", "Table 1 = gas composition". (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Note which variables appear in multiple places</strong>. If temperature appears in both Figure 1 and Figure 2, you know temperature is a connecting variable that links these figures. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify the independent variable (x-axis) for each figure</strong>. This helps you understand what''s being manipulated versus what''s being measured. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Recognize the format of each figure</strong>—tables are good for exact values, line graphs show trends, scatter plots show relationships. This mental organization means that when you encounter a question like "At what temperature was volume highest?", you immediately think "temperature and volume = Figure 2" rather than randomly searching through all figures.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Understanding Common Multi-Figure Relationships
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
ACT Science passages use multiple figures in <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">predictable patterns</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Different experiments or trials</strong>: Figure 1 shows Experiment 1 results, Figure 2 shows Experiment 2 results, etc. Questions ask you to compare across experiments. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Same variables, different formats</strong>: Table 1 shows numerical data, Figure 1 graphs the same data visually. Questions test whether you can use whichever format is more helpful. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Linked variables</strong>: Figure 1 shows how X affects Y, Figure 2 shows how Y affects Z. Questions ask about the relationship between X and Z (requiring you to connect through Y). (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Different conditions</strong>: Figure 1 shows data at pH 5, Figure 2 shows data at pH 7. Questions ask you to compare results under different conditions. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Complementary information</strong>: Table 1 provides initial conditions, Figure 1 shows results. Both are needed to answer questions about how changes in initial conditions affect outcomes. Recognizing these patterns helps you anticipate what types of questions might be asked and how figures will work together.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Building a Mental Map</strong><br><br>
<strong>Passage contains:</strong><br>
- Figure 1: Line graph, x-axis = time (0-60 min), y-axis = temperature (0-100°C)<br>
- Figure 2: Line graph, x-axis = time (0-60 min), y-axis = pressure (0-5 atm)<br>
- Table 1: Shows gas composition (% nitrogen, % oxygen, % CO₂) at time 0, 30, and 60 min<br><br>
<strong>Mental Map:</strong><br>
- "Time" appears in all three → connecting variable<br>
- Figure 1 = temperature over time<br>
- Figure 2 = pressure over time<br>
- Table 1 = gas composition at specific times<br>
- If question asks about temperature AND pressure → need both Figures 1 and 2<br>
- If question asks about composition at a certain temperature → need Table 1 (for composition) and Figure 1 (to find when that temperature occurred)<br><br>
This map allows instant navigation to the right data source(s).
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Strategies for Navigating Between Multiple Figures
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Efficient navigation</strong> between figures is critical for speed and accuracy. Without a systematic approach, you can waste significant time flipping back and forth, lose track of which data came from which figure, or miss connections between sources.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Question-First Navigation Method
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
For multiple figures questions, always use a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">question-first approach</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read the question completely</strong> before looking at any figures. Understand exactly what''s being asked. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify which variables or data the question mentions</strong>. For example, if the question asks "At what pH was enzyme activity highest?", you need pH and enzyme activity. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Determine which figure(s) contain those variables</strong> using your mental map. If pH is in Table 1 and enzyme activity is in Figure 2, you need both. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Go to the first figure</strong> and extract the needed information. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Go to the second figure</strong> and extract its information. (6) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Synthesize the data</strong> from both sources to answer the question. This method prevents you from randomly looking through figures hoping to stumble upon the answer. Instead, you purposefully navigate to exactly what you need.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Connecting Variables as Bridges
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Connecting variables</strong> that appear in multiple figures serve as <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">bridges</strong> for integrating data. The most common connecting variable is the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">independent variable</strong> (often time, temperature, concentration, etc.) that appears on the x-axis of multiple graphs or as a column in multiple tables. To use connecting variables: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Find the value of the connecting variable</strong> specified in the question or that satisfies the condition you''re looking for. For example, if the question asks about "temperature = 50°C", locate 50°C. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">In the first figure</strong>, find what happens at that connecting variable value. At 50°C in Figure 1, pressure = 2 atm. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use that same connecting variable value in the second figure</strong>. At 50°C in Figure 2, volume = 45 mL. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Now you have data from both figures at the same condition</strong>, allowing you to compare or combine them. The connecting variable ensures you''re comparing apples to apples—data from the same experimental conditions, time points, or parameter values.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Sticky Note Tracking Method for Complex Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
For particularly complex multiple-figure questions, use a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">tracking system</strong> to avoid losing track of information: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">As you extract data from the first figure, jot down the value</strong> in the margin next to that figure or on scratch paper. For example, write "50°C → P = 2 atm". (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Move to the second figure</strong> and find the corresponding data. Write "50°C → V = 45 mL". (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If a third figure is needed</strong>, continue the same process. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Now you have all the data in one place</strong> (your notes) and can answer the question without needing to flip back and forth repeatedly. This method is especially valuable for questions like "At which temperature were BOTH pressure greater than 2 atm AND volume less than 50 mL?" where you need to check multiple conditions across multiple figures. Writing down intermediate findings prevents you from forgetting what you found in the first figure by the time you check the second.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Efficient Physical Navigation on the Test Page
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Physical navigation</strong> on paper matters for efficiency: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">When figures are on different pages</strong>, use one finger to hold your place on one page while flipping to the other, or fold the test booklet so both pages are visible simultaneously. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read figure labels carefully each time you switch</strong> to ensure you''re looking at the right figure. It''s easy to confuse Figure 2 with Figure 3 when switching rapidly. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use a finger or pencil to track your position</strong> on each figure—point to the exact data point you''re reading to prevent losing your place. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Minimize the number of switches</strong>. If you need to check four conditions across two figures, extract all four values from Figure 1 first (writing them down), then extract all four from Figure 2, rather than switching back and forth four separate times. These physical strategies might seem minor, but they can save 10-15 seconds per question, which adds up significantly over a full passage.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Using a Connecting Variable</strong><br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> "At what time were both temperature greater than 60°C AND pressure less than 3 atm?"<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Identify needed data → temperature and pressure<br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Identify sources → Figure 1 (temperature vs time), Figure 2 (pressure vs time)<br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Identify connecting variable → time (appears in both)<br><br>
<strong>Method:</strong><br>
- Check answer choices: 10 min, 20 min, 30 min, 40 min<br>
- For each time option, check BOTH figures:<br>
  - At t=10: Figure 1 → T=50°C (NO, need >60°C) → Eliminate<br>
  - At t=20: Figure 1 → T=65°C (YES), Figure 2 → P=4 atm (NO, need <3 atm) → Eliminate<br>
  - At t=30: Figure 1 → T=70°C (YES), Figure 2 → P=2.5 atm (YES) → This works!<br>
  - At t=40: Check if needed, but t=30 already satisfies both conditions<br><br>
<strong>Answer:</strong> 30 min<br><br>
The connecting variable (time) allowed systematic checking across both figures.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Common Types of Multiple Figures Questions
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Multiple figures questions fall into <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">predictable categories</strong>. Understanding these common question types helps you recognize what approach to use and what kind of information synthesis is required.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Type 1: Direct Comparison Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Direct comparison questions</strong> ask you to compare values or trends from different figures: "Was temperature higher in Experiment 1 or Experiment 2 at time = 30 min?", "In which trial was reaction rate fastest?", or "Which figure shows the greatest increase in pressure?" To answer these: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify the comparison criterion</strong>—what specifically are you comparing? (temperature, rate of change, maximum value, etc.). (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Extract the relevant value from each figure</strong>. If comparing at t=30 min, find the value at t=30 in Figure 1, then in Figure 2. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Make the comparison</strong>. Which is higher? Lower? Faster? (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Select the answer</strong> that matches your comparison. These questions test your ability to locate equivalent data points across different sources and make simple comparisons. The key is ensuring you''re comparing the same conditions—if comparing at t=30 min, make sure you''re looking at t=30 in all relevant figures.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Type 2: Condition-Matching Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Condition-matching questions</strong> ask you to find when multiple conditions are simultaneously satisfied: "At what temperature were BOTH pH greater than 6 AND enzyme activity greater than 50%?", or "Which trial had a concentration less than 0.5 M AND a reaction time greater than 40 seconds?" To solve these: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify all conditions that must be met</strong>. Break down "BOTH X and Y" into two separate requirements. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check answer choices systematically</strong>. For each option, verify whether it satisfies ALL conditions. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use elimination</strong>. If an option fails even one condition, eliminate it immediately and move to the next. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">The correct answer must satisfy every condition</strong>. These questions require careful tracking because you might find that Option A satisfies condition 1 but not condition 2, while Option B satisfies condition 2 but not condition 1—you need to find the option that works for both.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Type 3: Chained Relationship Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Chained relationship questions</strong> require you to trace through multiple figures to connect variables: "Based on the figures, how does increasing pressure affect volume?" when Figure 1 shows temperature vs. pressure and Figure 2 shows temperature vs. volume (requiring you to connect through temperature). To handle these: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify the chain</strong>. What''s the starting variable, intermediate variable, and ending variable? (Pressure → Temperature → Volume). (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Trace the first relationship</strong>. In Figure 1, as pressure increases, what happens to temperature? (Temperature increases). (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Trace the second relationship</strong>. In Figure 2, as temperature increases, what happens to volume? (Volume increases). (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Chain them together</strong>. Pressure increases → Temperature increases → Volume increases. Therefore, increasing pressure increases volume (through the intermediate effect on temperature). These questions test your understanding of how multiple variables interact across different experimental setups or conditions.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Type 4: Data Integration Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Data integration questions</strong> require you to combine numerical values from multiple figures to calculate or determine something new: "If temperature was 50°C and pressure was 2 atm, what was the density according to Table 1?" when Figure 1 provides temperature-pressure relationships and Table 1 provides density at various temperature-pressure combinations. To solve these: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Extract each piece of needed data</strong> from its respective figure. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Combine the data according to the question''s requirements</strong>. This might involve looking up a combination of conditions, calculating a ratio, or finding where multiple values intersect. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check that your integrated answer makes sense</strong>. If combining data from temperature and pressure to get density, does the density value seem reasonable given the conditions? These questions often involve using one figure to determine a value, then using that value to look up information in another figure, requiring two-step navigation.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Question Types in Action</strong><br><br>
<strong>Type 1 (Direct Comparison):</strong><br>
Question: "At t=20 min, was temperature higher in Trial 1 or Trial 2?"<br>
Method: Check Figure 1 (Trial 1) at t=20 → T=45°C; Check Figure 2 (Trial 2) at t=20 → T=60°C<br>
Answer: Trial 2<br><br>
<strong>Type 2 (Condition-Matching):</strong><br>
Question: "At what time were both temperature > 50°C AND pressure < 2.5 atm?"<br>
Method: Check each time in answer choices against both conditions in both figures<br>
Answer: The time where BOTH conditions are true<br><br>
<strong>Type 3 (Chained Relationship):</strong><br>
Question: "How does increasing pH affect oxygen production?"<br>
Figure 1 shows: pH vs enzyme activity (pH↑ → activity↑)<br>
Figure 2 shows: enzyme activity vs oxygen production (activity↑ → O₂↑)<br>
Chain: pH↑ → activity↑ → O₂↑<br>
Answer: Increasing pH increases oxygen production<br><br>
<strong>Type 4 (Data Integration):</strong><br>
Question: "At pH 6, what was the ratio of enzyme A activity to enzyme B activity?"<br>
Figure 1: At pH 6, enzyme A activity = 40 units<br>
Figure 2: At pH 6, enzyme B activity = 20 units<br>
Integration: 40/20 = 2<br>
Answer: 2:1 ratio
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Advanced Strategies and Common Pitfalls
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Advanced strategies</strong> for multiple figures questions involve recognizing patterns, avoiding common errors, and maximizing efficiency when dealing with complex data relationships.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Strategy: Using Answer Choices to Guide Figure Selection
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Sometimes <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">answer choices reveal which figures you need</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check what units or variables appear in answer choices</strong>. If answers are in units of "mL", you know you need the figure that shows volume in mL. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look at the range of answer values</strong>. If answers range from 20-50, find the figure whose scale includes these values. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Notice if answers refer to specific conditions</strong> ("Trial 1", "Experiment 2", "pH 6", etc.), which tells you exactly which figure or subset of data to examine. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use elimination strategically</strong>. If you can''t find a value that matches an answer choice in any figure, that answer is likely wrong and can be eliminated. This strategic use of answer choices prevents you from wasting time examining irrelevant figures or sections of data.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Pitfall #1: Confusing Similar Figures or Variables
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When passages contain <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">similar-looking figures</strong> (multiple line graphs with similar shapes, or multiple tables with similar layouts), it''s easy to confuse them and pull data from the wrong source. To prevent this: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Always verify the figure label</strong> before extracting data. Read "Figure 1" or "Figure 2" explicitly each time. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check axis labels or column headers</strong> to confirm you''re reading the right variable. If you need "enzyme A" but you''re looking at "enzyme B" data, you''ll get the wrong answer. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use distinct mental labels</strong> for each figure based on content, not just number. Think "the temperature graph" versus "the pressure graph" rather than just "Figure 1" and "Figure 2". (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">When switching between figures, re-orient yourself</strong> each time by quickly re-reading the title or axes. This pitfall is particularly common under time pressure when you''re rushing between sources.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Pitfall #2: Missing the Connecting Variable
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Sometimes students <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">fail to recognize the connecting variable</strong> that links multiple figures, leading to incorrect data matching. For example, if Figure 1 shows trials labeled A, B, C and Figure 2 shows trials labeled 1, 2, 3, you need to find the passage text or table that explains which letter corresponds to which number. To avoid this: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read all figure captions and notes carefully</strong> for information about how figures relate. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for common variables in axes, column headers, or labels</strong>. If both figures show "temperature", that''s likely your connecting variable. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check the passage introduction</strong> for explanations of how experiments or trials are organized. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Ensure you''re matching conditions correctly</strong>. If comparing Trial A in Figure 1 to Trial 2 in Figure 2, verify these are actually the same trial or are meant to be compared. Missing or misidentifying the connecting variable causes you to compare data from incompatible conditions.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Pitfall #3: Forgetting to Check All Conditions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
For condition-matching questions with <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">multiple requirements</strong>, students sometimes find an option that satisfies one condition and select it without checking the other conditions. To avoid this: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Write down all conditions explicitly</strong> before starting. If the question asks for "temperature > 50°C AND pressure < 3 atm", write "T > 50" and "P < 3". (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check each answer choice against every condition</strong>. Don''t stop at the first condition. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use a systematic elimination process</strong>. For each option, check condition 1 (if it fails, eliminate and move on; if it passes, check condition 2; etc.). (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Only select an answer after confirming it satisfies ALL conditions</strong>. Be especially careful with questions containing "both", "all", "and"—these signal multiple requirements. Students who rush often select the first option that satisfies one condition without verifying it meets all of them.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Pitfall #4: Over-Complicating Simple Multi-Figure Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Not all multiple-figure questions are complex. Some are actually quite straightforward—they simply require looking up one value in Figure 1 and another value in Figure 2 without any sophisticated integration. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Over-thinking these questions wastes time</strong>. To avoid this: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Assess question complexity before overthinking</strong>. If it''s just asking for two separate facts from two figures, treat it as two simple lookups. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Don''t assume integration is needed if it''s not requested</strong>. "What was the temperature in Trial 1 and the pressure in Trial 2?" is asking for two separate values, not their relationship. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read the question literally</strong>. If it asks for simple comparison or listing, don''t invent complex relationships. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Trust straightforward interpretations</strong>. If a question seems simple, it probably is—answer it simply and move on. Some students, upon seeing "multiple figures", assume the question must be difficult and look for complexity that doesn''t exist, wasting valuable time.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Avoiding Pitfalls</strong><br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 1 Prevention:</strong> Question asks about enzyme A activity at pH 5<br>
Before reading: "I need enzyme A data at pH 5"<br>
Check figure label: "This is Figure 2, enzyme B" → WRONG FIGURE<br>
Switch to Figure 1: "enzyme A vs pH" → CORRECT<br>
Prevention: Always verify you''re reading the correct figure and variable<br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 2 Prevention:</strong> Figure 1 shows "Sample 1, 2, 3", Figure 2 shows "Low, Medium, High"<br>
Don''t assume Sample 1 = Low<br>
Check passage: "Sample 1 was tested at low concentration, Sample 2 at medium..." → Now you know the connection<br>
Prevention: Find the explicit link between different labeling systems<br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 3 Prevention:</strong> Question asks "When were BOTH T > 60°C AND P < 3 atm?"<br>
At t=20: Check Figure 1 → T = 65°C ✓ (Satisfies first condition)<br>
Don''t stop here! Check Figure 2 → P = 3.5 atm ✗ (Fails second condition)<br>
Eliminate this option and check others<br>
Prevention: Verify ALL conditions before selecting an answer<br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 4 Prevention:</strong> Question: "What was the temperature in Trial 1 and the pressure in Trial 2?"<br>
This is just two simple lookups—don''t overthink it<br>
Figure 1, Trial 1: T = 50°C<br>
Figure 2, Trial 2: P = 2 atm<br>
Done. No complex integration needed.<br>
Prevention: Answer simple questions simply
</p>
</div>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Multiple figures questions require synthesizing data from two or more separate figures or tables
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use a two-pass strategy: first overview to build a mental map, then question-driven detail reading
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Create a mental map associating each figure with its primary variables and identifying connecting variables
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use question-first navigation: read the question, identify needed variables, go directly to relevant figures
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Connecting variables (often the x-axis or independent variable) serve as bridges between figures
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Write down intermediate values when extracting data from multiple figures to avoid losing track
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For condition-matching questions, check every condition systematically before selecting an answer
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Always verify figure labels and axis labels to ensure you''re extracting data from the correct source
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Common question types include direct comparison, condition-matching, chained relationships, and data integration
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Don''t over-complicate simple multi-figure questions—if it asks for two separate facts, treat it as two simple lookups
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T18:09:19.214163+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (681bf2f3-53d9-4ced-bef2-0b4ff24d6709, 63bd0e37-1e9c-43c0-a53b-5221b5b2e012, '<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Percentages</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">On the ACT, you will need to know how to solve questions with simple percentages and with percentage</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">increases and decreases. While percentages may seem simple, they can often stump students who do not know</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">how to set them up correctly. This chapter will show you all the skills you need to know to handle percentage</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">questions quickly and easily on test day.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">2. Simple Percentages</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Simple percentage questions can be solved by properly setting up a proportion:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">You can think of the “original” as the starting value (the 100%) and the “new” as the percentage of the starting</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">value. If you are given a percentage value, always put it where the % 1s.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 1: Isaiah purchased a new watch for 72% of the original price. Isaiah paid no sales tax. Ifthe</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">original price was $160, which of the following is closest to the price Isaiah paid for the watch?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 88</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D.</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">3. Isaiah paid $115.20 for the watch. The answer is C.</h3>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">120% is the same as 1.2. 85% is the same as 0.85. Here, we can turn the 72% into</p>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">72. Let the price Isaiah paid for the watch be p. Isaiah paid 72% of the original price of $160 so</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">4. Isaiah paid $115.20 for the watch.</h3>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 2: Joey buys a new set of golf clubs for $720 when the clubs are on sale for 80% of the original</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">price. What was the original price, in dollars, of the set of golf clubs?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 648</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 864</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 900</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">5. The answer is D.</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">6. Chapter 9: Percentages</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Method #2 — Decimal Shortcut: For this question, we can turn 80% in 0.8 and solve:</p>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">8x = 720</li>
</ul>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">8</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The answer is D. We recommend the decimal shortcut, as it is faster for solving percentage questions.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The ACT can also ask you to deal with multiple <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">percent</strong> changes in the same question. To solve these</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">questions the fastest, you should do all the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">percent</strong> changes together in one step.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 3: Fred is trying to sell his bicycle, but he is having a hard time finding someone interested in</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">buying it. To sell the bicycle quickly, Fred decides to sell the bicycle for 95% of the original price to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Dave. Dave sells the bicycle 6 months later for 80% of the price that he purchased the bicycle for from</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Fred. The price that Dave sells the bicycle for is what <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">percent</strong> of the original price of the bicycle?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 87.5</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 80</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 76</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">bicycle to Dave for 95% of the original price, you multiply by 0.95. When Dave later sells the bicycle for 80%</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">of the purchase price, you multiply by 0.8. The final price that Dave sold the bicycle for is then:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The final price is 76% of the original price. The answer is D.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Method 2 — Plug In Numbers: The part about this question that confuses most students is that we are never</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">given any actual price for the bicycle. To make this question easier, pick an original price for the bicycle and</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">use that price to solve. Let’s say the original price of Fred’s bicycle $100. 100 is always a good number to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">pick for percentage problems because it is easy to calculate <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">percent</strong> changes from 100. Since Dave buys the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">bicycle for 95% of the original price, Dave pays $95 for the bicycle. Dave then sells the bicycle for 80% of the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">$95, so you can solve for the final price:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The final price is $76. Since the original price was $100, the final price is 76% of the original price. The</p>

<p style="height: 1px; margin: 0; padding: 0;"></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; visibility: hidden; height: 0; margin: 0; padding: 0; overflow: hidden;">.</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">Key Takeaways</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Master these concepts for ACT success
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Practice with ACT-style problems to build confidence
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Apply these strategies on test day
  </li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-16T16:35:20.416059+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (5d92fab8-69ef-49ef-ad33-2f707290c3c7, 66bdda34-bd6a-423d-9d75-8375248a2f2c, '<h3 style="margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;">Circle</strong></strong> Equations on the Coordinate Plane</h3>

<p style=" margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">A circle is all points that are the same <strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;">distance</strong></strong> (<strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;">radius</strong></strong>) from a center point. On the coordinate plane, we can write this as an equation!</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Standard Form of a Circle</h4>

<p style="font-size: 1.2rem; text-align: center; padding: 1rem;  border: 2px solid #3b82f6; border-radius: 8px; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
  <strong>(x − h)² + (y − k)² = r²</strong>
</p>

<ul style=" margin: 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>(h, k)</strong> = center of the circle</li>
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>r</strong> = radius of the circle</li>
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>r²</strong> = radius squared (what appears on the right side)</li>
</ul>

<div style="text-align: center; margin: 2rem 0;">
<svg width="400" height="420" viewBox="-10 -10 420 440">
  <defs>
    <pattern id="grid-circle" width="40" height="40" patternUnits="userSpaceOnUse">
      <path d="M 40 0 L 0 0 0 40" fill="none" stroke="#e5e7eb" stroke-width="0.5"/>
    </pattern>
  </defs>
  <rect width="400" height="400" fill="url(#grid-circle)"/>
  <line x1="0" y1="200" x2="400" y2="200" stroke="#000" stroke-width="2"/>
  <line x1="200" y1="0" x2="200" y2="400" stroke="#000" stroke-width="2"/>
  <circle cx="280" cy="160" r="80" fill="none" stroke="#2563eb" stroke-width="3"/>
  <circle cx="280" cy="160" r="4" fill="#ef4444"/>
  <text x="295" y="155" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="14" fill="#ef4444">(h, k)</text>
  <line x1="280" y1="160" x2="360" y2="160" stroke="#10b981" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="3,3"/>
  <text x="320" y="175" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="14" fill="#10b981">r</text>
  <text x="200" y="430" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="16" fill="#000" text-anchor="middle" font-weight="bold">(x − h)² + (y − k)² = r²</text>
</svg>
</div>

<ul style=" margin: 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><span style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;">💡 Key Pattern:</span></li>
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><span style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;">The signs in the equation tell you the center! If you see (x − 3)², the center x-coordinate is +3. If you see (x + 2)², the center x-coordinate is −2. The signs flip!</span></li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Example 1: Finding Center and Radius</h4>

<p style=" margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong>Problem:</strong> What is the center and radius of the circle (x − 5)² + (y + 2)² = 16?</p>

<p style="padding: 1rem;  border-left: 3px solid #10b981; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
  <strong>Solution:</strong><br>
  Compare to (x − h)² + (y − k)² = r²<br><br>
  (x − 5)² means h = 5 ✓<br>
  (y + 2)² means (y − (−2))², so k = −2 ✓<br>
  r² = 16, so r = 4 ✓<br><br>
  <strong>Center: (5, −2)</strong><br>
  <strong>Radius: 4</strong>
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Example 2: Writing Circle Equation</h4>

<p style=" margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong>Problem:</strong> Write the equation of a circle with center (−3, 1) and radius 7.</p>

<p style="padding: 1rem;  border-left: 3px solid #10b981; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
  <strong>Solution:</strong><br>
  Use (x − h)² + (y − k)² = r²<br>
  h = −3, k = 1, r = 7<br><br>
  (x − (−3))² + (y − 1)² = 7²<br>
  <strong>(x + 3)² + (y − 1)² = 49</strong>
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;">Completing the Square</strong></strong></h3>

<p style=" margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Sometimes circle equations aren''t in standard form. You''ll need to <strong>complete the square</strong> to find the center and radius.</p>


  <p style="font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.9rem; color: #92400e; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">📝 Steps to Complete the Square:</p>
  <ol style="margin: 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #78350f;">
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;">Group x terms and y terms separately</li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;">Take half of the x coefficient, square it, add to both sides</li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;">Take half of the y coefficient, square it, add to both sides</li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;">Factor each perfect square</li>
  </ol>


<h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Example 3: Completing the Square</h4>

<p style=" margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong>Problem:</strong> Convert x² + y² − 4x + 6y + 9 = 0 to standard form.</p>

<p style="padding: 1rem;  border-left: 3px solid #10b981; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
  <strong>Solution:</strong><br>
  Step 1: Group x and y terms<br>
  (x² − 4x) + (y² + 6y) = −9<br><br>
  Step 2: Complete the square for x<br>
  Half of −4 is −2, square it: (−2)² = 4<br>
  (x² − 4x + 4) + (y² + 6y) = −9 + 4<br><br>
  Step 3: Complete the square for y<br>
  Half of 6 is 3, square it: 3² = 9<br>
  (x² − 4x + 4) + (y² + 6y + 9) = −9 + 4 + 9<br><br>
  Step 4: Factor<br>
  <strong>(x − 2)² + (y + 3)² = 4</strong><br><br>
  Center: (2, −3), Radius: 2
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;">Ellipse</strong></strong> Basics</h3>

<p style=" margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">An <strong>ellipse</strong> is a stretched circle. It has two axes: a longer one (major axis) and a shorter one (minor axis).</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Standard Form of an Ellipse</h4>

<p style="font-size: 1.1rem; text-align: center; padding: 1rem;  border: 2px solid #9333ea; border-radius: 8px; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
  <strong>(x − h)²/a² + (y − k)²/b² = 1</strong>
</p>

<ul style=" margin: 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>(h, k)</strong> = center of the ellipse</li>
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>a</strong> = semi-major axis (longer radius)</li>
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>b</strong> = semi-minor axis (shorter radius)</li>
</ul>

<div style="text-align: center; margin: 2rem 0;">
<svg width="450" height="200" viewBox="0 0 450 200">
  <text x="225" y="40" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="18" fill="#000" text-anchor="middle" font-weight="bold">x² + 6x + 9 = (x + 3)²</text>
  <rect x="50" y="80" width="80" height="80" fill="#e0f2fe" stroke="#2563eb" stroke-width="2"/>
  <text x="90" y="175" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="14" fill="#2563eb" text-anchor="middle">x²</text>
  <rect x="140" y="80" width="40" height="80" fill="#fef3c7" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="2"/>
  <text x="160" y="175" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="14" fill="#f59e0b" text-anchor="middle">3x</text>
  <rect x="190" y="80" width="40" height="80" fill="#fef3c7" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="2"/>
  <text x="210" y="175" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="14" fill="#f59e0b" text-anchor="middle">3x</text>
  <rect x="240" y="80" width="40" height="40" fill="#d1fae5" stroke="#10b981" stroke-width="2"/>
  <text x="260" y="175" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="14" fill="#10b981" text-anchor="middle">9</text>
  <text x="320" y="130" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="24" fill="#000">=</text>
  <rect x="360" y="80" width="80" height="80" fill="#e0f2fe" stroke="#2563eb" stroke-width="3"/>
  <text x="400" y="175" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="14" fill="#2563eb" text-anchor="middle">(x+3)²</text>
</svg>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Example 4: Ellipse Center and Axes</h4>

<p style=" margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong>Problem:</strong> What is the center of the ellipse (x − 1)²/25 + (y + 2)²/9 = 1?</p>

<p style="padding: 1rem;  border-left: 3px solid #10b981; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
  <strong>Solution:</strong><br>
  Compare to (x − h)²/a² + (y − k)²/b² = 1<br><br>
  (x − 1)² means h = 1<br>
  (y + 2)² means k = −2<br><br>
  <strong>Center: (1, −2)</strong><br>
  Note: a² = 25 so a = 5, b² = 9 so b = 3
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline;">Hyperbola</strong></strong> Basics (Brief Overview)</h3>

<p style=" margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">A <strong>hyperbola</strong> has two separate curves that open outward. The equation looks similar to an ellipse, but with a minus sign.</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Standard Form of a Hyperbola</h4>

<p style="font-size: 1.1rem; text-align: center; padding: 1rem;  border: 2px solid #dc2626; border-radius: 8px; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
  <strong>(x − h)²/a² − (y − k)²/b² = 1</strong> (opens left-right)<br>
  or<br>
  <strong>(y − k)²/a² − (x − h)²/b² = 1</strong> (opens up-down)
</p>

<div style="text-align: center; margin: 2rem 0;">
<svg width="400" height="400" viewBox="-10 -10 420 420">
  <defs>
    <pattern id="grid-hyp" width="40" height="40" patternUnits="userSpaceOnUse">
      <path d="M 40 0 L 0 0 0 40" fill="none" stroke="#e5e7eb" stroke-width="0.5"/>
    </pattern>
  </defs>
  <rect width="400" height="400" fill="url(#grid-hyp)"/>
  <line x1="0" y1="200" x2="400" y2="200" stroke="#000" stroke-width="2"/>
  <line x1="200" y1="0" x2="200" y2="400" stroke="#000" stroke-width="2"/>
  <path d="M 260 60 Q 280 100 290 140 T 310 200 T 330 260 T 350 320" fill="none" stroke="#2563eb" stroke-width="3"/>
  <path d="M 140 60 Q 120 100 110 140 T 90 200 T 70 260 T 50 320" fill="none" stroke="#2563eb" stroke-width="3"/>
  <text x="200" y="380" font-family="Times New Roman, serif" font-size="16" fill="#000" text-anchor="middle">Two separate curves</text>
</svg>
</div>

<ul style=" margin: 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><span style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;">🔑 Quick Recognition:</span></li>
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><span style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;">Circle:  x² + y² (both positive, same coefficients)</span></li>
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><span style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;">Ellipse:  x²/a² + y²/b² = 1 (both positive, different denominators)</span></li>
  <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><span style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;">Hyperbola:  x²/a² − y²/b² = 1 (one is negative!)</span></li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Summary Table</h3>

<table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">
  <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">
    <th style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; color: #6b7280; font-size: 0.8rem;">Shape</th>
    <th style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; color: #6b7280; font-size: 0.8rem;">Equation</th>
    <th style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; color: #6b7280; font-size: 0.8rem;">Center</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; color: #374151;">Circle</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; color: #374151;">(x−h)² + (y−k)² = r²</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; color: #6b7280;">(h, k)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; color: #374151;">Ellipse</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; color: #374151;">(x−h)²/a² + (y−k)²/b² = 1</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; color: #6b7280;">(h, k)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; color: #374151;">Hyperbola</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; color: #374151;">(x−h)²/a² − (y−k)²/b² = 1</td>
    <td style="padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; color: #6b7280;">(h, k)</td>
  </tr>
</table>


  <h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">✓ Key Takeaways</h4>
  <ul style=" margin: 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;">✓ Circle: (x−h)² + (y−k)² = r²</li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;">✓ Signs flip: (x−3) means center x = 3, (y+2) means center y = −2</li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;">✓ Complete the square to convert to standard form</li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;">✓ Ellipse has +, Hyperbola has − (minus sign!)</li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;">✓ Center is always (h, k) for all conic sections</li>
  </ul>


  <h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">✓ Key Takeaways</h4>
  <ul style=" margin: 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Circle equation: (x−h)² + (y−k)² = r²</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Center is (h, k) and radius is r</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Ellipse: (x−h)²/a² + (y−k)²/b² = 1</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Hyperbola has a MINUS sign between squared terms</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Complete the square to convert general form to standard form</strong></li>
  </ul>


  <h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">✓ Key Takeaways</h4>
  <ul style=" margin: 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Circle equation: (x−h)² + (y−k)² = r²</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Center is (h, k) and radius is r</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Ellipse: (x−h)²/a² + (y−k)²/b² = 1</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Hyperbola has a MINUS sign between squared terms</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Complete the square to convert general form to standard form</strong></li>
  </ul>

<div style="background: #f0fdf4; padding: 1.5rem 2rem; border-radius: 8px; margin: 3rem 0 2rem 0; border-left: 4px solid #10b981;">
  <h4 style="margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">✓ Key Takeaways</h4>
  <ul style=" margin: 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Circle equation: (x−h)² + (y−k)² = r²</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Center is (h, k) and radius is r</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Ellipse: (x−h)²/a² + (y−k)²/b² = 1</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Hyperbola has a MINUS sign between squared terms</strong></li>
    <li style=" margin: 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Complete the square to convert general form to standard form</strong></li>
  </ul>
</div>', 0, '2025-10-13T18:09:19.214163+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (349b28de-3d2d-4900-88b3-db8de1a00647, 67437f5e-f4f2-45b1-a841-a2e0c43c0362, '<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Systems of Equations</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">2. The answer is C.</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">3. Word Problems</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Many word problems are systems of equations questions in disguise. For these questions, the biggest</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">challenge is turning the words into equations. If you can do that successfully, you then just need to solve the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">system of equations. Systems of equations questions on the ACT most commonly look something like this:</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 3: For her garden, Mary buys 42 plants for a total of $108. Mary is only going to plant</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">tomatoes and peppers. If a tomato plant costs $3.00 and pepper plant costs $2.00, how many pepper plants</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D.</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">equations. The first equation comes from the fact that we know Mary bought a total of 42 plants.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The second equation includes the prices of each plant to add to the total amount of money Mary spent buying</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Once we have these two equations, we can use elimination to solve. We are solving for the number of pepper</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">plants, y, so we can eliminate the tomato plants, x, by multiplying the first equation by —3.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Next, add the equations together and solve for y. Notice that the x-terms cancel out.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">4. The answer is D.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">On more challenging questions, there can be more than two unknowns, and we will need to write more than 2</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 4: Malik made $738 selling his artwork this month and is counting his cash. Malik only has $1,</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">$5, and $20 bills. He counts and notices that he has 5 more $5 bills than $20 bills and 6 more $1 bills than</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">$5 bills. How many $1 bills does Malik have?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 38</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 48</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 53</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">and z be the number of $20 bills. We can write three equations. First, we are told that Malik has $738. To</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">find the total amount of money Malik has, we multiply the number of bills by the dollar amount of each bill.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">5. Those must add up to a total of $738.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We have one equation with three unknowns. Well, that looks no fun! We cannot solve an equation with three</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">unknowns, so we need to write a few more equations with the rest of the information from the question.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We are told Malik has 5 more $5 bills than $20 bills and 6 more $1 bills than $5 bills, so the other equations</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We are asked to solve for $1 bills, which is x, so we want to put y and z in terms of x. First, let’s use the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">equation y + 6 = x above to solve for y in terms of x. Subtracting 6 from both sides we get</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Next, we need to solve for z in terms of x. To do so, we can plug in x — 6 for y in the equation z + 5 = y.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Now that we have y and z in terms of x, we can plug these values into our first equations and solve for x.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">1x +5(* — 6) + 20(x — 11) = 738</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The answer is B. Okay...that was not easy. Good news! There is an easier way to solve questions like this.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Method 2 — Backsolve: The answer choices tell us the possible number of $1 bills. We can use the answer</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">choices and play guess-and-check to see which one is correct. Let’s say we are going to check if answer</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Answer choice B says there are 38 $1 bills. If there are 6 more $1 bills than $5 bills, there would be 32 $5</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">bills. If there are 5 more $5 bills than $20 bills, there would be 27 $20 bills. Now, we just need to see if the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">38 $1 bills worked to get a total of $738, so the answer is B.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">None of the other answer choices would give you $738. That’s much easier than doing all that fancy algebra,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">right? For questions with more than 2 unknown values, always backsolve using the answer choices.</p>

<p style="height: 1px; margin: 0; padding: 0;"></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; visibility: hidden; height: 0; margin: 0; padding: 0; overflow: hidden;">.</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">Key Takeaways</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Master these concepts for ACT success
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Practice with ACT-style problems to build confidence
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Apply these strategies on test day
  </li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-16T08:23:49.356552+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (bb2e7b95-3d2d-4add-bf22-f8856a06c940, 6b26adb1-009a-453d-8a57-2c9a2aea2ca9, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Science
Topic: Question Diagnosis
Lesson Key: question-diagnosis
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Successfully diagnosing what each Science question is actually asking is crucial for answering accurately and efficiently, requiring you to identify <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">question types</strong>, recognize <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">key signal words</strong>, determine <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">where to find answers</strong>, and understand <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">what skills are being tested</strong>. Many students waste time by misunderstanding what a question asks or searching for information in the wrong place within a passage. This lesson teaches you how to quickly and accurately diagnose Science questions, explains the major question categories and their characteristics, provides frameworks for identifying what information you need, and shows you how to avoid common misinterpretation pitfalls that lead to incorrect answers despite having the right skills and knowledge.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. The Four Main Question Categories
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
ACT Science questions fall into four main categories based on what skill they''re testing: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Data Representation questions</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scientific Investigation questions</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Evaluation of Models and Inferences questions</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Hypothesis-Testing questions</strong>. Recognizing which category a question belongs to helps you know where to look for the answer and what type of reasoning to apply.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Data Representation Questions (40-50% of questions)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Data Representation questions</strong> ask you to extract specific values, identify trends, or interpret information directly from graphs, tables, or diagrams. These questions typically contain phrases like: "According to Figure 1...", "Based on Table 2...", "As shown in the graph...", or "What was the value of X when Y was...?" The answers to these questions are found directly in the figures—you don''t need to make complex inferences or apply outside knowledge. Common Data Representation question types include: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">specific value questions</strong> that ask for an exact data point, (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">trend identification questions</strong> that ask whether variables increase, decrease, or remain constant, (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">comparison questions</strong> that ask you to compare values across conditions, and (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">interpolation/extrapolation questions</strong> that ask you to estimate values between or beyond measured data points. To answer these efficiently, immediately look at the referenced figure and methodically find the requested information.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Scientific Investigation Questions (20-30% of questions)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scientific Investigation questions</strong> test your understanding of experimental design, variables, controls, and scientific methodology. These questions ask about: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">which variables were manipulated</strong> (independent variables), (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">which variables were measured</strong> (dependent variables), (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">which variables were controlled</strong> (held constant), (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">why specific procedures were used</strong>, or (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">how to extend or modify the experiment</strong>. Signal phrases include: "Which variable was directly manipulated?", "What was held constant?", "The purpose of Trial 1 was to...", "To investigate [new question], students should...", or "What hypothesis was being tested?" To answer these questions, focus on the experimental descriptions and understand the logic behind how the experiment was designed. You need to think about why scientists set up trials in specific ways and what each trial was meant to test.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Evaluation of Models and Inferences Questions (25-35% of questions)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Evaluation questions</strong> require higher-order thinking and ask you to: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">draw conclusions</strong> from data, (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">make inferences</strong> about what results suggest, (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">evaluate whether hypotheses are supported</strong> by evidence, or (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">predict outcomes</strong> based on trends. Signal phrases include: "Based on the results, which conclusion is best supported?", "The data are most consistent with which hypothesis?", "Which statement is supported by...?", "If the experiment had continued...", or "The results suggest that...". These questions require you to synthesize information, often from multiple figures or trials, and apply logical reasoning. Unlike Data Representation questions where answers are explicitly stated in figures, Evaluation questions ask you to think about what the data means and what logical conclusions can be drawn. Be careful to choose answers that are directly supported by the passage rather than answers that seem plausible but lack textual evidence.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Hypothesis-Testing and Viewpoint Comparison Questions (Primarily in Conflicting Viewpoints passages)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Hypothesis-Testing and Viewpoint questions</strong> appear primarily in Conflicting Viewpoints passages and ask you to: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">understand different scientific perspectives</strong>, (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">compare and contrast viewpoints</strong>, (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">identify points of agreement or disagreement</strong>, or (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">evaluate which viewpoint is supported by new evidence</strong>. Signal phrases include: "Scientist 1 would most likely agree that...", "According to Student 2''s view...", "Both scientists would agree that...", "Which finding would support Hypothesis A?", or "The two students disagree about...". To answer these questions effectively, you need to carefully read each viewpoint''s main claims and supporting evidence, noting similarities and differences between perspectives. Create a mental or written comparison of the key points of each view. These questions test reading comprehension and logical analysis rather than data interpretation, making them more similar to Reading section questions than typical Science questions.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Identifying Question Categories</strong><br><br>
<strong>Data Representation:</strong> "According to Figure 2, what was the temperature when pressure was 50 kPa?" → Look at Figure 2 and read the value directly<br><br>
<strong>Scientific Investigation:</strong> "Which variable was held constant across all three trials?" → Review experimental descriptions to identify what didn''t change<br><br>
<strong>Evaluation:</strong> "Based on the results of Experiments 1 and 2, which conclusion is most strongly supported?" → Synthesize data from multiple sources and apply logic<br><br>
<strong>Viewpoint Comparison:</strong> "Student 1 and Student 2 would most likely agree about which of the following?" → Compare the two viewpoints to find common ground
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Key Signal Words and Phrases
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Learning to recognize <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">signal words and phrases</strong> in question stems helps you quickly diagnose what type of question you''re facing and what approach to use. These linguistic clues tell you whether you need to find specific data, understand experimental design, draw conclusions, or compare viewpoints.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Signals for Direct Data-Reading Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When you see phrases like <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"According to..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"Based on..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"As shown in..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"What was the value..."</strong>, or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"In Figure/Table X..."</strong>, the question is asking you to extract information directly from a specific source. Your task is straightforward: locate the referenced figure or table and find the requested value, trend, or comparison. These are typically the fastest questions to answer because they don''t require complex reasoning—just careful data reading. Common variations include: "According to Figure 3, as temperature increased, pressure:", "Based on the data in Table 1, which trial had the highest concentration?", "What was the pH when volume was 30 mL?", or "As shown in the graph, at what time did the reaction rate peak?" When you see these signal words, immediately shift your attention to the specified figure and methodically locate the answer.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Signals for Experimental Design Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Phrases like <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"Which variable was..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"What was held constant..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"The purpose of..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"To test the hypothesis..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"What was directly manipulated..."</strong>, or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"How could the experiment be extended..."</strong> signal questions about experimental methodology and design. When you encounter these, focus on understanding the structure and logic of the experiment rather than specific data values. You need to think about: What changed between trials? What was measured as an outcome? What factors were kept the same to ensure a fair comparison? Why was the experiment set up this way? Example questions include: "Which variable was directly manipulated by the researchers?", "What was held constant in all three trials?", "The purpose of using a control group was to...", or "To determine whether light affects growth, students should...". Answer these by analyzing experimental descriptions and applying your understanding of scientific methodology.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Signals for Inference and Conclusion Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Words like <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"Based on the results..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"Which conclusion is supported..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"The data suggest..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"It can be inferred..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"The results are most consistent with..."</strong>, or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"If the experiment had continued..."</strong> indicate that you need to draw conclusions or make logical inferences rather than simply reading data. These questions require synthesis and reasoning. When you see these signals, recognize that you''ll need to: (1) consider multiple pieces of evidence, (2) apply logical thinking to determine what the data means, (3) eliminate answer choices that aren''t supported by the passage, and (4) select the conclusion that is most strongly backed by evidence. Example questions: "Based on the results of all three trials, which conclusion is best supported?", "The data in Figures 1 and 2 suggest that...", "Which hypothesis is most consistent with the experimental results?", or "If temperature had continued to increase beyond 80°C, reaction rate would most likely have...". Take your time with these questions and verify that your answer is truly supported by the passage.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Signals for Viewpoint and Agreement Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
In Conflicting Viewpoints passages, watch for phrases like <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"Scientist 1 believes..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"According to Student 2..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"Both scientists agree..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"The two viewpoints differ on..."</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"Which finding would support..."</strong>, or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"Hypothesis A differs from Hypothesis B in..."</strong>. These signal that you need to understand and compare different scientific perspectives. When you see these phrases, you should: (1) identify which specific viewpoint the question is asking about, (2) locate that viewpoint''s position on the topic in question, (3) compare it to other viewpoints if necessary, and (4) verify your answer against the text. Example questions: "Student 1 would most likely agree with which statement?", "According to Scientist 2, the primary cause of the phenomenon is...", "Both scientists would agree that...", "Which observation would support Hypothesis A but not Hypothesis B?", or "The main point of disagreement between the two students is...". These questions require careful reading comprehension and comparison skills.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Signal Word Recognition</strong><br><br>
<strong>Question 1:</strong> "According to Table 2, what was the volume when pressure was 2.0 atm?"<br>
<strong>Signal:</strong> "According to" → Direct data reading → Look at Table 2 and find the value<br><br>
<strong>Question 2:</strong> "Which variable was held constant in all three experiments?"<br>
<strong>Signal:</strong> "held constant" → Experimental design → Review what didn''t change between trials<br><br>
<strong>Question 3:</strong> "Based on the results, which hypothesis is most strongly supported?"<br>
<strong>Signal:</strong> "Based on the results... supported" → Inference/conclusion → Synthesize data and evaluate<br><br>
<strong>Question 4:</strong> "Student 1 and Student 2 would most likely agree about which of the following?"<br>
<strong>Signal:</strong> "Student 1 and Student 2... agree" → Viewpoint comparison → Find common ground
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Determining Where to Find Answers
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Efficient question-answering requires knowing <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">where to look</strong> for the information you need. Different question types require you to reference different parts of the passage: specific figures, experimental descriptions, result summaries, or viewpoint text. Learning to quickly identify the correct source saves significant time and prevents frustration.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Explicit References (Figure Numbers, Table Numbers)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Many Science questions provide <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">explicit references</strong> that tell you exactly where to look: "According to Figure 3...", "Based on Table 1...", "As shown in the diagram...", or "In Experiment 2...". When you see these explicit references, immediately go to that specific figure, table, or section. Don''t waste time re-reading other parts of the passage or trying to answer from memory. The explicit reference is a gift—it''s telling you precisely where the answer is located. If the question says "According to Figure 2," the answer will be found by analyzing Figure 2, not by reading text or examining other figures. If it says "In Experiment 3," focus on the description and results of Experiment 3 specifically. This direct approach is faster and more accurate than trying to work from memory or searching randomly through the passage. Even if you think you remember the information, always verify by checking the referenced source to avoid careless errors.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Implicit Clues (Variable Names, Trial Numbers)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When questions don''t explicitly reference a figure number, you can often determine where to look based on <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">variable names</strong> or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">trial numbers</strong> mentioned in the question. For example, if a question asks "How did pH affect reaction rate?", you know to look for a figure or table that shows pH and reaction rate together. If it asks "What temperature was used in Trial 2?", you should examine the description or data for Trial 2 specifically. Similarly, if a question mentions specific units like "kPa" or "mol/L," scan the passage for figures using those units. This detective work—using contextual clues to determine where relevant information is located—becomes faster with practice. When multiple figures show similar variables, the question number can provide additional guidance: questions 1-2 usually relate to early figures or experiments, while questions 5-6 often address later content. This logical progression helps you narrow down where to search.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Recognizing Questions Requiring Multiple Sources
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Some questions, particularly <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">evaluation and synthesis questions</strong>, require you to combine information from <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">multiple sources</strong>. Signal phrases include: "Based on the results of Experiments 1 and 2...", "According to Figures 1, 2, and 3...", "Comparing the data in all three trials...", or "Using information from both the table and the graph...". When you encounter these questions, recognize that you''ll need to: (1) examine each referenced source, (2) extract relevant information from each, (3) synthesize or compare the information, and (4) draw a conclusion based on the combined evidence. These questions take longer than single-source questions, so budget extra time. Create brief mental or written notes comparing the key findings from each source. For example, "Figure 1 shows pH increases with time; Figure 2 shows temperature increases with time; both increase together, suggesting they''re related." This systematic comparison helps you identify patterns and draw supported conclusions.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Knowing When to Reference Text vs. Figures
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Understanding when to focus on <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">text</strong> versus <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">figures</strong> prevents wasted time. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Figures and tables</strong> answer questions about: specific data values, trends, comparisons between conditions, and visual relationships. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Text</strong> answers questions about: experimental procedures, what variables represent, what equipment was used, what hypotheses were being tested, and why certain methods were chosen. For example, if a question asks "What was the concentration in Trial 3?", that''s a data value question—check the table or figure. But if it asks "Why did researchers heat the solution before measuring pH?", that''s a procedural explanation question—check the text describing methods. Similarly, viewpoint questions in Conflicting Viewpoints passages almost always require reading the text where each scientist''s argument is presented. Developing this instinct for where to look—figures for data, text for explanations—dramatically improves efficiency.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Locating Answer Sources</strong><br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> "According to Figure 2, as altitude increased from 0 to 3,000 m, atmospheric pressure:"<br>
<strong>Where to look:</strong> Figure 2 (explicit reference) → Find altitude and pressure variables<br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> "What was the purpose of using a water bath to maintain constant temperature?"<br>
<strong>Where to look:</strong> Text describing experimental procedures (looking for explanations, not data)<br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> "Based on Figures 1 and 3, which factor had a greater effect on reaction rate?"<br>
<strong>Where to look:</strong> Both Figure 1 and Figure 3 (multiple sources) → Compare the magnitude of effects<br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> "Student 2 argues that climate change is primarily caused by:"<br>
<strong>Where to look:</strong> Text of Student 2''s viewpoint (reading comprehension of argument)
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Question Misinterpretation Pitfalls
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Even when you have strong data interpretation skills, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">misinterpreting what a question is asking</strong> can lead to incorrect answers. Understanding common misinterpretation pitfalls helps you read questions more carefully and avoid preventable errors that waste your skills and knowledge.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Confusing "Increase" with "Decrease" or "Direct" with "Inverse"
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
One of the most common errors is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">mixing up directional language</strong>. Questions might ask "As X increased, Y:" and the correct answer is "increased" but students who misread the question select "decreased." Or a question asks about a "direct relationship" (both increase together) but students confuse it with an "inverse relationship" (one increases while the other decreases). To avoid this pitfall: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">read the question twice</strong> before looking at answer choices, (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">underline or circle</strong> key directional words like "increase," "decrease," "direct," "inverse," "positive," or "negative," (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">verify your answer</strong> by checking the figure one more time before moving on. This type of error is particularly frustrating because you may have correctly read the data but simply mixed up the wording. Slowing down for just 3-4 extra seconds to ensure you understand what direction the question is asking about can prevent these costly mistakes.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Missing Qualifiers Like "NOT," "EXCEPT," or "LEAST"
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Questions containing <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">negative qualifiers</strong> or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reversal words</strong> are specifically designed to test whether you''re reading carefully. Examples include: "Which of the following is NOT supported by the data?", "All of the following were held constant EXCEPT:", "Which conclusion is LEAST consistent with the results?", or "Which factor did NOT affect reaction rate?" These questions reverse the normal logic—instead of finding what IS true, you''re finding what ISN''T true. Students who skim too quickly often miss these critical words and select the opposite of the correct answer. To avoid this trap: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">circle or highlight</strong> any negative qualifiers when you read the question, (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">remind yourself</strong> that you''re looking for the exception or the false statement, not the true statement, (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">eliminate answers</strong> systematically by identifying which three ARE true (and therefore wrong) to find the one that is NOT true (the correct answer). These questions tend to be slightly harder, so allocate a few extra seconds to process them carefully.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Answering a Different Question Than What Was Asked
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Sometimes students find an answer that is true according to the passage but doesn''t actually answer the specific question asked. For example, a question might ask "What was the dependent variable in Experiment 2?" and a student selects an answer about the independent variable because they saw it mentioned in the experimental description. Or a question asks "According to Scientist 1..." but the student selects a statement from Scientist 2''s viewpoint. This happens when you''re working too quickly or when you find information that seems relevant but don''t verify that it actually addresses the question. To prevent this: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reread the question stem</strong> after you''ve found your answer but before selecting it, (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ask yourself</strong> "Does this answer specifically address what was asked?", (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">double-check</strong> that you''re referencing the correct figure, trial, or scientist mentioned in the question. Just because an answer choice is factually true doesn''t mean it''s correct—it must also answer the actual question.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Overthinking Simple Questions or Underthinking Complex Ones
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Students sometimes make questions harder than they are by <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">overthinking</strong> straightforward data-reading questions, or conversely, they treat complex synthesis questions too simplistically by <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">underthinking</strong> them. For simple questions like "According to Table 1, what was the pH at 60 seconds?", the answer is just the value in the table—don''t second-guess yourself or look for hidden complexity. The ACT doesn''t try to trick you with intentionally confusing data on these straightforward questions. However, for complex questions like "Based on all three experiments, which variable had the greatest effect on the outcome?", you DO need to think carefully, compare magnitudes of effects across experiments, and reason through the logic. The key is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">calibrating your effort level</strong> to the question type. Use signal words to help you gauge difficulty: "According to..." signals a simple question; "Based on... which conclusion is best supported..." signals a complex one that deserves more thought and time.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Avoiding Misinterpretation Pitfalls</strong><br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 1:</strong> Question asks "As pressure increased, volume:" → Circle "increased" to avoid mixing up the direction → Answer: decreased (inverse relationship)<br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 2:</strong> Question asks "All of the following were controlled variables EXCEPT:" → Circle "EXCEPT" to remember you''re looking for what WASN''T controlled → Answer: the independent variable that was manipulated<br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 3:</strong> Question asks "What was the dependent variable?" → Before selecting, reread question to confirm you''re answering about dependent, not independent variable<br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 4:</strong> Simple question: "According to Figure 1, what was Y when X = 10?" → Don''t overthink; just read the value from the graph<br>
Complex question: "Based on Figures 1-3, which factor most strongly affected the outcome?" → Take time to compare all three sources
</p>
</div>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Science questions fall into four categories: Data Representation, Scientific Investigation, Evaluation, and Viewpoint Comparison
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Data Representation questions use phrases like "According to..." and ask you to extract values or trends from figures
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Scientific Investigation questions ask about variables, controls, and experimental design using phrases like "held constant"
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Evaluation questions require synthesis and use phrases like "Based on the results..." or "which conclusion is supported"
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Explicit references ("Figure 2," "Table 3") tell you exactly where to find answers—use them immediately
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use variable names and trial numbers as implicit clues when questions don''t specify a figure number
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Figures answer data questions; text answers procedural and explanatory questions
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Circle directional words like "increase," "decrease," "direct," and "inverse" to avoid mixing them up
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Highlight negative qualifiers like "NOT," "EXCEPT," and "LEAST" to remember you''re finding the exception
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Always verify your answer actually addresses the specific question asked, not just a related topic
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T18:09:19.214163+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (d3d136ec-a07a-46be-97c3-917bd7581011, 6e078993-aabf-4358-a16e-4d2722852714, '<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Exponents and Roots</h3>

<p style="height: 1px; margin: 0; padding: 0;"></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; visibility: hidden; height: 0; margin: 0; padding: 0; overflow: hidden;">.</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">Key Takeaways</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
