INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (27b192b4-3038-4def-972e-c4353c49ee6f, 8907dfc4-e415-406a-b94c-743baf15db1e, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Quadratic equations</strong> are polynomial equations of degree two, taking the form ax² + bx + c = 0. On the ACT, you''ll need to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">factor quadratics</strong>, use the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">quadratic formula</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">complete the square</strong>, and understand <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">parabola properties</strong> to solve problems efficiently and analyze quadratic functions graphically.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Understanding Quadratic Functions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Standard Form and General Properties
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The standard form of a quadratic function is f(x) = ax² + bx + c, where a ≠ 0.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Key properties:</strong>
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>If a > 0, the parabola opens upward (U-shape)</li>
<li>If a < 0, the parabola opens downward (∩-shape)</li>
<li>The graph is a parabola, which is symmetric about a vertical line</li>
<li>The highest or lowest point is called the vertex</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Examples:</strong>
<br><br>
f(x) = x² - 4x + 3 → Opens upward (a = 1 > 0)
<br>
g(x) = -2x² + 8x - 5 → Opens downward (a = -2 < 0)
<br>
h(x) = 3x² → Opens upward, vertex at origin
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Vertex Form
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The vertex form of a quadratic is f(x) = a(x - h)² + k, where (h, k) is the vertex.
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>h represents the horizontal shift from the origin</li>
<li>k represents the vertical shift from the origin</li>
<li>The axis of symmetry is the line x = h</li>
<li>If a > 0, the vertex is a minimum; if a < 0, it''s a maximum</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> f(x) = 2(x - 3)² + 5
<br><br>
<strong>Vertex:</strong> (3, 5)
<br>
<strong>Opens:</strong> Upward (a = 2 > 0)
<br>
<strong>Axis of symmetry:</strong> x = 3
<br>
<strong>Minimum value:</strong> 5 (occurs at x = 3)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Finding the Vertex from Standard Form
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
For f(x) = ax² + bx + c, the vertex is at x = -b/(2a).
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
To find the y-coordinate of the vertex, substitute x = -b/(2a) into the function.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find the vertex of f(x) = 2x² - 8x + 5
<br><br>
<strong>x-coordinate:</strong> x = -(-8)/(2 · 2) = 8/4 = 2
<br><br>
<strong>y-coordinate:</strong> f(2) = 2(2)² - 8(2) + 5 = 8 - 16 + 5 = -3
<br><br>
<strong>Vertex:</strong> (2, -3)
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Solving Quadratic Equations by Factoring
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Zero Product Property
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
If AB = 0, then A = 0 or B = 0. This property allows us to solve quadratic equations by factoring.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Steps:</strong>
</p>

<ol style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Set the equation equal to zero</li>
<li>Factor the quadratic expression</li>
<li>Set each factor equal to zero</li>
<li>Solve for x</li>
</ol>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Solve x² - 5x + 6 = 0
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Already equals zero
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Factor: (x - 2)(x - 3) = 0
<br>
(Look for two numbers that multiply to 6 and add to -5: -2 and -3)
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Set each factor to zero:
<br>
x - 2 = 0 or x - 3 = 0
<br><br>
<strong>Step 4:</strong> Solve:
<br>
x = 2 or x = 3
<br><br>
<strong>Check:</strong> 2² - 5(2) + 6 = 4 - 10 + 6 = 0 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Factoring Different Forms
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Form 1: x² + bx + c</strong> — Find two numbers that multiply to c and add to b.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> x² + 7x + 12
<br>
Numbers: 3 and 4 (multiply to 12, add to 7)
<br>
<strong>Factored:</strong> (x + 3)(x + 4)
</p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Form 2: ax² + bx + c (a ≠ 1)</strong> — Use trial and error or the AC method.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> 2x² + 7x + 3
<br><br>
<strong>AC method:</strong> AC = 2 × 3 = 6
<br>
Find two numbers that multiply to 6 and add to 7: 1 and 6
<br><br>
Rewrite: 2x² + 1x + 6x + 3
<br>
Group: (2x² + 1x) + (6x + 3)
<br>
Factor: x(2x + 1) + 3(2x + 1)
<br>
<strong>Final:</strong> (x + 3)(2x + 1)
</p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Form 3: Difference of squares</strong> — a² - b² = (a + b)(a - b)
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> x² - 25 = 0
<br>
<strong>Factor:</strong> (x + 5)(x - 5) = 0
<br>
<strong>Solutions:</strong> x = -5 or x = 5
</p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Form 4: Perfect square trinomials</strong> — a² + 2ab + b² = (a + b)²
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> x² + 6x + 9 = 0
<br>
<strong>Recognize:</strong> (x)² + 2(x)(3) + (3)²
<br>
<strong>Factor:</strong> (x + 3)² = 0
<br>
<strong>Solution:</strong> x = -3 (repeated root)
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. The Quadratic Formula
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Formula and When to Use It
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
For any quadratic equation ax² + bx + c = 0, the solutions are:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>x = (-b ± √(b² - 4ac)) / (2a)</strong>
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Use the quadratic formula when:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>The quadratic doesn''t factor easily</li>
<li>You need exact answers with radicals</li>
<li>You want to guarantee finding all solutions</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Solve 2x² + 3x - 7 = 0
<br><br>
<strong>Identify:</strong> a = 2, b = 3, c = -7
<br><br>
<strong>Apply formula:</strong>
<br>
x = (-3 ± √(3² - 4(2)(-7))) / (2 · 2)
<br>
x = (-3 ± √(9 + 56)) / 4
<br>
x = (-3 ± √65) / 4
<br><br>
<strong>Solutions:</strong> x = (-3 + √65)/4 or x = (-3 - √65)/4
<br><br>
<strong>Approximate:</strong> x ≈ 1.266 or x ≈ -2.766
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Discriminant
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The discriminant is b² - 4ac. It determines the nature of the solutions:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>If b² - 4ac > 0: Two distinct real solutions</li>
<li>If b² - 4ac = 0: One repeated real solution (perfect square)</li>
<li>If b² - 4ac < 0: No real solutions (two complex solutions)</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Examples:</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>1.</strong> x² - 5x + 6 = 0
<br>
Discriminant: (-5)² - 4(1)(6) = 25 - 24 = 1 > 0
<br>
<strong>Result:</strong> Two distinct solutions (x = 2 and x = 3)
<br><br>
<strong>2.</strong> x² - 6x + 9 = 0
<br>
Discriminant: (-6)² - 4(1)(9) = 36 - 36 = 0
<br>
<strong>Result:</strong> One repeated solution (x = 3)
<br><br>
<strong>3.</strong> x² + 2x + 5 = 0
<br>
Discriminant: (2)² - 4(1)(5) = 4 - 20 = -16 < 0
<br>
<strong>Result:</strong> No real solutions
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Completing the Square
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Method and Purpose
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Completing the square converts ax² + bx + c into vertex form a(x - h)² + k. This method helps find the vertex and solve equations.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Steps for x² + bx + c = 0:</strong>
</p>

<ol style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Move the constant to the right side</li>
<li>Take half of b, square it, and add to both sides</li>
<li>Factor the left side as a perfect square</li>
<li>Solve by taking the square root of both sides</li>
</ol>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Solve x² + 6x + 2 = 0 by completing the square
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Move constant: x² + 6x = -2
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Half of 6 is 3, and 3² = 9. Add 9 to both sides:
<br>
x² + 6x + 9 = -2 + 9
<br>
x² + 6x + 9 = 7
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Factor the left side:
<br>
(x + 3)² = 7
<br><br>
<strong>Step 4:</strong> Take square root:
<br>
x + 3 = ±√7
<br>
x = -3 ± √7
<br><br>
<strong>Solutions:</strong> x = -3 + √7 or x = -3 - √7
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Converting to Vertex Form
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Convert f(x) = x² - 8x + 10 to vertex form
<br><br>
<strong>Complete the square:</strong>
<br>
f(x) = x² - 8x + 10
<br>
f(x) = (x² - 8x + 16) - 16 + 10
<br>
f(x) = (x - 4)² - 6
<br><br>
<strong>Vertex form:</strong> f(x) = (x - 4)² - 6
<br>
<strong>Vertex:</strong> (4, -6)
<br>
<strong>Opens:</strong> Upward
<br>
<strong>Minimum value:</strong> -6
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
When a ≠ 1
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
If the leading coefficient is not 1, factor it out first before completing the square.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Convert f(x) = 2x² - 12x + 14 to vertex form
<br><br>
<strong>Factor out a = 2:</strong>
<br>
f(x) = 2(x² - 6x) + 14
<br><br>
<strong>Complete the square inside parentheses:</strong>
<br>
Half of -6 is -3, and (-3)² = 9
<br>
f(x) = 2(x² - 6x + 9 - 9) + 14
<br>
f(x) = 2(x² - 6x + 9) - 18 + 14
<br>
f(x) = 2(x - 3)² - 4
<br><br>
<strong>Vertex:</strong> (3, -4)
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Graphing Quadratic Functions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Key Features to Identify
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Vertex:</strong> The highest or lowest point; found at x = -b/(2a)
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Axis of symmetry:</strong> The vertical line x = -b/(2a)
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Y-intercept:</strong> The point where x = 0; equals c in f(x) = ax² + bx + c
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>X-intercepts (roots/zeros):</strong> Points where f(x) = 0; found by solving ax² + bx + c = 0
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Direction:</strong> Opens up if a > 0, down if a < 0
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Analyze f(x) = -x² + 4x - 3
<br><br>
<strong>Direction:</strong> Opens downward (a = -1 < 0)
<br><br>
<strong>Vertex x-coordinate:</strong> x = -4/(2 · -1) = -4/(-2) = 2
<br>
<strong>Vertex y-coordinate:</strong> f(2) = -(2)² + 4(2) - 3 = -4 + 8 - 3 = 1
<br>
<strong>Vertex:</strong> (2, 1) — This is a maximum point
<br><br>
<strong>Y-intercept:</strong> f(0) = -3, point (0, -3)
<br><br>
<strong>X-intercepts:</strong> Solve -x² + 4x - 3 = 0
<br>
x² - 4x + 3 = 0
<br>
(x - 1)(x - 3) = 0
<br>
<strong>X-intercepts:</strong> (1, 0) and (3, 0)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Transformations of f(x) = x²
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Vertical shift:</strong> f(x) = x² + k shifts k units up (k > 0) or down (k < 0)
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Horizontal shift:</strong> f(x) = (x - h)² shifts h units right (h > 0) or left (h < 0)
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Vertical stretch/compression:</strong> f(x) = ax² stretches if |a| > 1, compresses if 0 < |a| < 1
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Reflection:</strong> f(x) = -x² reflects across the x-axis
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
6. Applications and Problem-Solving
</h4>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Projectile Motion Problems
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Height problems often use the form h(t) = -16t² + v₀t + h₀, where v₀ is initial velocity and h₀ is initial height.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A ball is thrown upward from a height of 5 feet with an initial velocity of 48 ft/s. The height is given by h(t) = -16t² + 48t + 5. Find the maximum height.
<br><br>
<strong>Find vertex (maximum):</strong>
<br>
t = -48/(2 · -16) = -48/(-32) = 1.5 seconds
<br><br>
<strong>Maximum height:</strong>
<br>
h(1.5) = -16(1.5)² + 48(1.5) + 5
<br>
h(1.5) = -16(2.25) + 72 + 5
<br>
h(1.5) = -36 + 72 + 5 = 41 feet
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Area and Optimization Problems
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A rectangular garden has a perimeter of 40 feet. Find the dimensions that maximize the area.
<br><br>
<strong>Let:</strong> x = width, then length = 20 - x (since 2x + 2(length) = 40)
<br><br>
<strong>Area:</strong> A(x) = x(20 - x) = 20x - x² = -x² + 20x
<br><br>
<strong>Find maximum:</strong>
<br>
x = -20/(2 · -1) = 10 feet
<br><br>
<strong>Length:</strong> 20 - 10 = 10 feet
<br><br>
<strong>Answer:</strong> A 10 ft × 10 ft square garden maximizes area
<br>
<strong>Maximum area:</strong> 100 square feet
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Common Mistakes to Avoid
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 1: Sign errors.</strong> Be careful with negative signs when factoring or using the quadratic formula.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 2: Forgetting both solutions.</strong> Quadratics typically have two solutions; don''t forget the ± symbol.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 3: Not setting equal to zero.</strong> Before factoring, make sure one side equals zero.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 4: Calculating -b/(2a) incorrectly.</strong> Remember to include the negative sign and divide by 2a, not just a.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0rem; font-weight: 400; visibility: hidden;">
Hidden Section Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 0rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.9;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Quadratics have the form ax² + bx + c where a ≠ 0; they graph as parabolas
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> If a > 0 the parabola opens upward; if a < 0 it opens downward
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> The vertex is at x = -b/(2a); substitute to find the y-coordinate
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Factor when possible using patterns like difference of squares or trinomial factoring
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Use the quadratic formula x = (-b ± √(b² - 4ac))/(2a) when factoring is difficult
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> The discriminant b² - 4ac determines the number and type of solutions
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Complete the square to convert to vertex form a(x - h)² + k
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> X-intercepts are found by solving ax² + bx + c = 0
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> The y-intercept equals c (the constant term)
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Always check solutions by substituting back into the original equation
</li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-16T01:11:44.791373+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (732e2e4f-7919-4669-812f-43802f616c6f, 8c14f258-04f7-4f34-85ab-55e6b2433159, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Reading
Topic: How to Approach the Reading Test
Lesson Key: reading-approaches
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Developing an effective approach to the ACT Reading section requires understanding the three main <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reading strategies</strong>—the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read-Then-Answer method</strong>, the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Skim-Then-Detail method</strong>, and the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Questions-First method</strong>—and determining which approach best suits your natural reading style, comprehension strengths, and time management needs. No single strategy works for everyone, and many successful test-takers adapt their approach based on passage type and difficulty. This lesson examines each major reading strategy in depth, explains their advantages and disadvantages, provides guidance on choosing the best approach for your individual needs, and offers techniques for customizing your strategy to maximize both accuracy and speed under the intense time pressure of the Reading section.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. The Read-Then-Answer Approach
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read-Then-Answer approach</strong>, also called the "thorough reading method," involves reading the entire passage carefully and actively before attempting any questions. This traditional strategy emphasizes <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">comprehension</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">retention</strong> over speed, making it ideal for strong readers who can maintain focus and absorb information efficiently.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
How the Read-Then-Answer Method Works
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
With this approach, you dedicate 3-4 minutes to reading the passage from beginning to end with full concentration and strategic annotation before looking at a single question. During this initial reading, you <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">actively engage</strong> with the text by underlining key names and terms, bracketing important examples, noting main ideas in margins, and tracking the author''s argument or narrative structure. The goal is to build comprehensive understanding so that when you reach the questions, you can answer many from memory or quickly locate relevant information. After completing the passage, you tackle questions in order, referring back to specific sections only when necessary for verification or detail questions. Students using this method typically spend 3-4 minutes reading and 4.5-5.5 minutes answering questions.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Advantages of Read-Then-Answer
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
This approach offers several significant benefits. First, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">comprehensive understanding</strong> of the passage allows you to answer questions more confidently and accurately, particularly main idea, purpose, and inference questions that require holistic comprehension. Second, you can answer many questions from <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">memory</strong> without constantly flipping back to the passage, which saves time overall. Third, this method reduces the risk of <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">misinterpretation</strong> because you understand the full context before analyzing specific details. Fourth, for students who find the constant back-and-forth of other methods disorienting, Read-Then-Answer provides a straightforward, linear process. Finally, this approach works especially well for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Prose Fiction passages</strong> where understanding character development, narrative flow, and tone requires reading the full story rather than jumping around.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Disadvantages and Challenges
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Despite its strengths, Read-Then-Answer has limitations. The most significant is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">time investment</strong>—spending 3-4 minutes on reading means you must answer questions very efficiently to stay on pace. If your reading speed is slow (below 250-300 words per minute), this method may cause you to run out of time. Second, even strong readers sometimes experience <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">information overload</strong>, where they read carefully but retain little because they tried to absorb every detail. Third, for dense or confusing passages, you might spend 4-5 minutes reading and still feel lost, wasting valuable time. Fourth, this method can encourage <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">passive reading</strong> if you''re not deliberately engaging with the text—your eyes move across words but your brain doesn''t process meaning.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Optimizing Read-Then-Answer for Success
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
To maximize this method''s effectiveness, implement these strategies: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read actively</strong>, not passively, by constantly asking yourself questions about the content and purpose. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Annotate strategically</strong>—mark only the most essential information rather than underlining half the passage. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Summarize</strong> each paragraph''s main point in 2-4 words in the margin to create a roadmap. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Monitor your pace</strong>—if you''re spending more than 4 minutes reading, you need to speed up or switch approaches. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Don''t get bogged down</strong> in confusing sections; note them and move forward, returning if questions address those areas. Finally, after reading, take 5 seconds to mentally summarize the main idea and structure before diving into questions.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Read-Then-Answer in Action</strong><br><br>
<strong>Minutes 0:00-3:30:</strong> Read the entire Prose Fiction passage carefully, underlining character names and key emotions, noting tone shifts, and writing brief margin notes like "MC''s childhood," "meets artist," "conflict with father."<br><br>
<strong>Minute 3:30:</strong> Mental summary: "Story about a young musician torn between family expectations and artistic passion. Narrator is sympathetic to protagonist."<br><br>
<strong>Minutes 3:30-8:45:</strong> Answer all 10 questions, referring back only for specific line reference questions and to verify uncertain answers. Many questions answered from memory of passage structure and content.<br><br>
<strong>Result:</strong> High accuracy due to thorough comprehension, completed within time limit.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. The Skim-Then-Detail Approach
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Skim-Then-Detail approach</strong> balances speed and comprehension by quickly surveying the passage to grasp its general structure and main ideas, then returning to read specific sections carefully when answering questions. This hybrid method works well for students who struggle to finish all four passages or who find dense text overwhelming when reading thoroughly.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
How Skim-Then-Detail Works
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
This approach involves two phases. In the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">skim phase</strong> (1.5-2 minutes), you quickly read the first paragraph completely (it usually introduces the topic and sets the tone), then read only the first and last sentence of each middle paragraph (these typically contain topic sentences and concluding thoughts), and finally read the last paragraph completely (it often summarizes or concludes). During skimming, note the passage''s general topic, structure, and tone without worrying about specific details. In the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">detail phase</strong> (6-7 minutes), you tackle questions in order, returning to relevant sections of the passage to read carefully and find specific information needed for each question. This method trusts that questions will guide you to important details.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Advantages of Skim-Then-Detail
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
This approach offers unique benefits for certain students. First, it''s <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">time-efficient</strong>—spending only 1.5-2 minutes on initial reading leaves more time for questions. Second, it reduces <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">information overload</strong> by having you focus on details only when needed rather than trying to absorb everything at once. Third, reading with questions in mind provides <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">purpose and direction</strong>, which can improve focus for students who struggle with attention during sustained reading. Fourth, this method works particularly well for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Social Science and Natural Science passages</strong> that have clear topic sentences and organized paragraph structure. Finally, for students who read slowly but analyze quickly, this approach plays to their strengths by minimizing reading volume while maintaining comprehension quality.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Disadvantages and Challenges
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Skim-Then-Detail also has drawbacks. The primary challenge is maintaining <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">context</strong>—without reading the full passage, you might misinterpret details because you lack surrounding information. Second, this approach requires extensive <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">back-and-forth</strong> between questions and passage, which some students find disorienting or time-consuming. Third, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">main idea questions</strong> can be difficult because you haven''t read enough to grasp the overall purpose. Fourth, for passages without clear topic sentences—particularly Prose Fiction and some Humanities passages with flowing narrative style—skimming first and last sentences may provide insufficient context. Finally, students who skim too quickly may miss critical information and end up needing to reread large sections anyway, negating the time savings.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Optimizing Skim-Then-Detail for Success
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
To use this method effectively: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Skim actively</strong>, not mindlessly—even during the quick skim, engage with what you''re reading. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Create a mental map</strong> noting where different topics are discussed so you can relocate information quickly. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Write brief labels</strong> in margins during skimming (e.g., "intro," "problem," "solution," "example") to create landmarks. When reading for questions, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">read broadly</strong> around the relevant section—don''t just read one sentence in isolation. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Save main idea questions</strong> for last, after you''ve read most of the passage through answering detail questions. Finally, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">adapt this strategy</strong> by passage type—skim less for fiction, more for organized expository passages.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Skim-Then-Detail in Action</strong><br><br>
<strong>Minutes 0:00-1:45:</strong> Read first paragraph completely (introduces climate change research). Read first/last sentences of middle paragraphs (note structure: background, methodology, findings, implications). Read last paragraph completely (conclusions about policy). Mental note: "Science passage about climate study, organized by research process."<br><br>
<strong>Minutes 1:45-8:30:</strong> Answer questions in order. Q1 asks about main purpose—based on skim, answer "to present research findings." Q2 asks detail from paragraph 3—return and read that full paragraph carefully to answer. Continue this pattern.<br><br>
<strong>Result:</strong> Time-efficient, sufficient comprehension for most questions.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. The Questions-First Approach
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Questions-First approach</strong>, sometimes called the "targeted reading method," involves reading the questions before reading the passage. This strategy provides a roadmap of what to look for, turning passive reading into an active search for specific information. While controversial and not suitable for everyone, it can be highly effective for certain students and passage types.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
How Questions-First Works
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
This approach begins by spending 1-1.5 minutes <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reading all question stems</strong> (the questions themselves, not the answer choices) to understand what the questions will ask about. Note key terms, names, or line references that questions mention. Then read the passage with these questions in mind, knowing what information you''re hunting for. As you read and encounter information related to a question, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">mark it</strong> (underline, bracket, or write the question number in the margin). Some practitioners answer questions as they read, while others read the entire passage with questions in mind, then answer all questions afterward. The key is that questions shape your reading focus from the start.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Advantages of Questions-First
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
This method offers distinct advantages. First, it provides <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">clear purpose</strong> for your reading—you know exactly what to look for rather than trying to absorb everything. Second, it virtually eliminates the need to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reread</strong> sections because you marked relevant information as you encountered it. Third, for students who struggle with <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">attention and focus</strong>, having specific targets makes reading feel more like a scavenger hunt than a tedious task. Fourth, this approach works exceptionally well for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">detail-heavy passages</strong> with many specific questions about particular sections. Finally, it maximizes efficiency by ensuring you focus mental energy on information that''s actually tested rather than details that no question addresses.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Disadvantages and Challenges
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Questions-First has significant drawbacks that make it unsuitable for many students. First, reading 10 questions before the passage can cause <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">cognitive overload</strong>—you might not remember what you''re looking for by the time you start reading. Second, focusing only on question-related information may cause you to miss <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">context</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">big-picture understanding</strong> needed for main idea and inference questions. Third, this method is particularly ineffective for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Prose Fiction passages</strong> where understanding narrative flow, character development, and tone requires reading the story naturally rather than hunting for specific details. Fourth, some students find the constant mental juggling between remembering questions and reading the passage too distracting. Finally, you risk <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">misinterpreting</strong> details by reading them out of context.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Optimizing Questions-First for Success
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
To use this method effectively: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read question stems only</strong>, not answer choices, to avoid information overload. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Make brief notes</strong> about what each question asks—you won''t remember all 10 otherwise. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Still read for overall understanding</strong>, not just detail hunting—you need context for harder questions. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use this method selectively</strong>—it works better for Social Science and Natural Science than for Prose Fiction or complex Humanities passages. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Mark passage sections</strong> with question numbers as you find relevant info. Finally, if you find yourself constantly forgetting what you''re looking for, this method probably isn''t right for you—switch to Read-Then-Answer or Skim-Then-Detail.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Questions-First in Action</strong><br><br>
<strong>Minutes 0:00-1:15:</strong> Read all 10 question stems. Note: Q1 asks about main purpose, Q2-Q4 ask about specific paragraphs, Q5 asks about "renewable energy" (write "ren. energy" in margin), Q6 vocabulary question about line 45, etc.<br><br>
<strong>Minutes 1:15-7:30:</strong> Read passage with questions in mind. When encountering "renewable energy" in paragraph 3, underline it and write "Q5" in margin. When reaching line 45, circle the vocabulary word and write "Q6." Continue marking as you read.<br><br>
<strong>Minutes 7:30-8:45:</strong> Answer questions using your marked sections. Most answers require minimal searching because you marked relevant info during reading.<br><br>
<strong>Result:</strong> Very efficient for well-organized passages with detail questions.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Choosing and Customizing Your Approach
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The best reading approach is the one that maximizes your personal combination of <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">speed</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">comprehension</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">accuracy</strong>. Rather than rigidly adhering to one method, successful test-takers often develop hybrid approaches or switch strategies based on passage characteristics. This flexibility, combined with deliberate practice, leads to optimal performance.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Determining Your Best Primary Strategy
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
To identify which approach suits you best, conduct a systematic <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">experiment</strong> during practice. Take three practice passages of the same type (e.g., three Social Science passages) and complete one with each method under timed conditions. Track both your <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">accuracy</strong> (number correct out of 10) and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">time</strong> (how long you took). The method that gives you the best accuracy within the time limit is your primary strategy. Also consider subjective factors: Which method felt most comfortable? Which caused the least stress? Which allowed you to maintain focus best? Your ideal strategy should score well, finish within 8-9 minutes, and feel manageable. Repeat this experiment with different passage types—you might discover that Read-Then-Answer works best for fiction while Skim-Then-Detail works better for science.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Adapting Strategies by Passage Type
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Many high-scoring students use different approaches for different passage types based on each passage''s characteristics. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Prose Fiction passages</strong> generally work best with Read-Then-Answer because narrative flow, character development, and tone require reading the story naturally from beginning to end. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Social Science passages</strong>, with their clear structure and explicit topic sentences, work well with Skim-Then-Detail or even Questions-First. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Humanities passages</strong> vary—biographical or historical content may work with any method, while literary criticism might require Read-Then-Answer for full comprehension. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Natural Science passages</strong> often work well with Skim-Then-Detail because they''re typically well-organized with clear explanations. Practice with each passage type to identify your optimal approach for each.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Creating Hybrid Approaches
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
You don''t need to use any method in its pure form—many students develop <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">hybrid strategies</strong> that combine elements from multiple approaches. For example, you might: Read the first and last paragraphs thoroughly, skim middle paragraphs, then answer questions with detailed reading as needed (hybrid of Read-Then-Answer and Skim-Then-Detail). Read question stems first to know what to look for, then read the passage thoroughly before answering questions (hybrid of Questions-First and Read-Then-Answer). Read the passage carefully but glance at questions midway through to refocus your attention (Read-Then-Answer with question preview). The key is experimenting to find what works for you. Don''t feel constrained by the "official" methods—customize based on your strengths.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Building Consistency Through Practice
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Once you''ve identified your primary strategy (or strategies by passage type), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">practice it consistently</strong> until it becomes automatic. Switching methods randomly or trying new approaches on test day creates confusion and wastes mental energy. Your goal is to make your chosen approach so habitual that you don''t need to think about the process—you can focus entirely on comprehension and answering questions. However, remain <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">flexibly committed</strong>: if a particular passage isn''t working with your usual method (maybe it''s unusually dense or confusing), don''t be afraid to adapt. For instance, if you normally skim but encounter a complex fiction passage, slow down and read more carefully. The best test-takers have a default approach but can adjust when needed. Track your progress over multiple practice tests to ensure your chosen strategy consistently delivers results.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Customized Approach by Passage Type</strong><br><br>
<strong>Prose Fiction (Passage 1):</strong> Read-Then-Answer—read the entire story carefully with focus on characters and plot. Time: 8:30 total.<br><br>
<strong>Social Science (Passage 2):</strong> Skim-Then-Detail—quickly skim structure, then read for questions. Time: 8:00 total.<br><br>
<strong>Humanities (Passage 3):</strong> Read-Then-Answer—artist biography needs full reading for context. Time: 8:45 total.<br><br>
<strong>Natural Science (Passage 4):</strong> Questions-First—well-organized science passage with detail questions works well with targeted reading. Time: 9:45 total (used banked time from earlier passages).<br><br>
By customizing approaches, you maximize efficiency and accuracy across all passage types.
</p>
</div>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Read-Then-Answer works best for strong readers who can maintain focus and retention during thorough reading
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Skim-Then-Detail balances speed and comprehension by surveying first, then reading for specific questions
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Questions-First provides targeted reading focus but may cause information overload and miss big-picture context
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Experiment with all three methods during practice to identify which maximizes your accuracy and speed
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Prose Fiction passages generally work best with Read-Then-Answer to maintain narrative flow and character understanding
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Social Science and Natural Science passages often work well with Skim-Then-Detail or Questions-First
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Many successful students use different strategies for different passage types based on each passage''s characteristics
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Hybrid approaches that combine elements from multiple methods can be highly effective when customized to your strengths
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Practice your chosen strategy consistently until it becomes automatic, but remain flexible to adapt when needed
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Track both accuracy and time when testing strategies to ensure your approach works under realistic conditions
  </li>
</ul>
