<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Pythagorean triples are sets of whole numbers that work in the Pythagorean theorem. On the ACT, you</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">should look out for the two common Pythagorean triples.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">These triangles can also be scaled up by multiplying all of the side lengths by the same number to create</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">more Pythagorean triples. For example, a3, 4, 5 nght triangle can be doubled to become a 6, 8, 10 right</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">triangle, tripled to become 9, 12, 15, and so on.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Chapter 4: Geometry Part 2 - Shapes</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">You will need to be familiar with two special right triangles: 45° — 45° — 90° and 30° — 60° — 90°. The side</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">lengths of these triangles are always in a particular ratio.</p>

