<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The slope is - and the y-intercept is y = 3, so the equation of the line is y = =x +3. The answer is C.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">If we only know the slope of a line and a point on the line, we need to use point-slope form:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">where (x1, y;) is a point on the line and m</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">is the slope. Once we plug in the slope and point to point-slope</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">form, we can turn the equation back into slope-intercept form by solving for y.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 5: Line w passes through points (2, 10) and (5, —2). What is the y-intercept of line w?</h4>

