INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (ec556f81-a509-4a5c-82a9-ee7858c3a6ad, afea0497-db6f-4b9a-9396-0f605ea53e8a, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Math
Topic: Permutations and Combinations
Lesson Key: 6.4
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Mastering <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">counting techniques</strong> is crucial for solving complex ACT probability and arrangement problems. This lesson covers the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">fundamental counting principle</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">permutations</strong> (ordered arrangements), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">combinations</strong> (unordered selections), and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">factorial notation</strong>. Understanding when order matters versus when it doesn''t is the key to choosing the right counting method. These concepts typically appear in 2-3 questions per ACT test and are essential for students targeting scores above 30.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Fundamental Counting Principle and Factorials
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">fundamental counting principle</strong> states that if one event can occur in m ways and another independent event can occur in n ways, then both events together can occur in m × n ways. This principle extends to any number of events and forms the foundation for more complex counting. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Factorial notation</strong> (n!) represents the product of all positive integers from 1 to n and is essential for calculating permutations and combinations.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Fundamental Counting Principle
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>If Event 1 can occur in m ways, Event 2 in n ways, Event 3 in p ways, then all events together can occur in m × n × p ways.</strong>
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A restaurant offers 4 appetizers, 6 main courses, and 3 desserts. How many different three-course meals are possible?
<br><br>
<strong>Solution:</strong>
<br>
Choices for appetizer: 4
<br>
Choices for main course: 6
<br>
Choices for dessert: 3
<br><br>
Total meals = 4 × 6 × 3 = 72 different meals
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Understanding Factorials
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Factorial notation:</strong> n! = n × (n-1) × (n-2) × ... × 3 × 2 × 1
<br><br>
<strong>Special cases:</strong>
<br>
0! = 1 (by definition)
<br>
1! = 1
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Examples of factorials:</strong>
<br><br>
3! = 3 × 2 × 1 = 6
<br>
4! = 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 24
<br>
5! = 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 120
<br>
6! = 6 × 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 720
<br><br>
<strong>Useful property:</strong> n! = n × (n-1)!
<br>
Example: 7! = 7 × 6! = 7 × 720 = 5,040
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Simplifying Factorial Expressions
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Simplify 8! / 6!
<br><br>
<strong>Method 1: Cancel common factors</strong>
<br>
8! / 6! = (8 × 7 × 6!) / 6! = 8 × 7 = 56
<br><br>
<strong>Method 2: Expand and cancel</strong>
<br>
8! = 8 × 7 × 6 × 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1
<br>
6! = 6 × 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1
<br>
8! / 6! = (8 × 7 × 6!)/ 6! = 8 × 7 = 56
<br><br>
<strong>Key insight:</strong> When dividing factorials, cancel the smaller factorial from the larger one.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Counting with Restrictions
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> How many 3-digit numbers can be formed using the digits 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 if no digit can be repeated?
<br><br>
<strong>First digit:</strong> 5 choices (any of 1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
<br>
<strong>Second digit:</strong> 4 choices (any except the first digit used)
<br>
<strong>Third digit:</strong> 3 choices (any except the two digits already used)
<br><br>
Total = 5 × 4 × 3 = 60 different 3-digit numbers
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 1: Fundamental Counting Principle
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    A password must contain 2 letters followed by 3 digits. Letters can be any of the 26 letters (A-Z) and can repeat. Digits can be 0-9 and can repeat. How many different passwords are possible?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> 260</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> 2,600</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> 67,600</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> 676,000</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> 6,760,000</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>First letter:</strong> 26 choices</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Second letter:</strong> 26 choices (can repeat)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>First digit:</strong> 10 choices (0-9)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Second digit:</strong> 10 choices</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Third digit:</strong> 10 choices</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">Total = 26 × 26 × 10 × 10 × 10 = 676,000</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: D</strong> — Multiply choices for each position!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Permutations (Order Matters)
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">permutation</strong> is an arrangement of objects where order matters. The key question is: "In how many ways can we arrange these objects?" Different orders count as different permutations. For example, ABC and BAC are different permutations of the same three letters. The formula <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">nPr</strong> calculates the number of ways to arrange r objects selected from n total objects.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Permutations of All Objects
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> The number of ways to arrange n distinct objects is n!
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> In how many ways can 5 people stand in a line?
<br><br>
<strong>First position:</strong> 5 choices
<br>
<strong>Second position:</strong> 4 choices
<br>
<strong>Third position:</strong> 3 choices
<br>
<strong>Fourth position:</strong> 2 choices
<br>
<strong>Fifth position:</strong> 1 choice
<br><br>
Total arrangements = 5! = 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 120 ways
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Permutations of Some Objects (nPr)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> nPr = n! / (n-r)!
<br>
This gives the number of ways to arrange r objects chosen from n total objects.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> How many ways can a president, vice president, and secretary be chosen from 8 candidates?
<br><br>
We''re choosing 3 people from 8, and order matters (president ≠ vice president).
<br><br>
<strong>Using formula:</strong>
<br>
₈P₃ = 8! / (8-3)! = 8! / 5!
<br>
= (8 × 7 × 6 × 5!) / 5!
<br>
= 8 × 7 × 6
<br>
= 336 ways
<br><br>
<strong>Using counting principle:</strong>
<br>
President: 8 choices
<br>
Vice president: 7 choices (one person already chosen)
<br>
Secretary: 6 choices (two people already chosen)
<br>
Total = 8 × 7 × 6 = 336 ways
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Circular Permutations
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>For arranging n objects in a circle:</strong> (n-1)!
<br><br>
We use (n-1)! instead of n! because rotations of the same arrangement are considered identical in a circle.
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> In how many ways can 6 people sit around a circular table?
<br><br>
<strong>Solution:</strong> (6-1)! = 5! = 120 ways
<br><br>
<strong>Why not 6!?</strong> Because rotating everyone one seat clockwise produces the same circular arrangement.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Permutations with Repetition
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>When objects repeat:</strong> n! / (n₁! × n₂! × ... × nₖ!)
<br>
where n₁, n₂, ..., nₖ are the frequencies of each repeated object
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> How many distinct arrangements of the letters in MISSISSIPPI?
<br><br>
<strong>Count letters:</strong>
<br>
M: 1, I: 4, S: 4, P: 2
<br>
Total letters: 11
<br><br>
<strong>Formula:</strong>
<br>
11! / (1! × 4! × 4! × 2!)
<br>
= 39,916,800 / (1 × 24 × 24 × 2)
<br>
= 39,916,800 / 1,152
<br>
= 34,650 distinct arrangements
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 2: Permutations
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    A bookshelf has space for 4 books. If you have 7 different books to choose from, in how many ways can you arrange 4 books on the shelf?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> 28</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> 35</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> 210</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> 840</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> 5,040</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Order matters</strong> (different arrangements on shelf), so use permutations</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">₇P₄ = 7! / (7-4)! = 7! / 3!</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">= (7 × 6 × 5 × 4 × 3!) / 3!</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">= 7 × 6 × 5 × 4 = 840</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: J</strong> — Order matters, so permutation not combination!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Combinations (Order Doesn''t Matter)
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">combination</strong> is a selection of objects where order does NOT matter. The key question is: "In how many ways can we select these objects?" Different selections count as different combinations, but different orders of the same selection do not. For example, selecting {A, B, C} is the same combination as {C, A, B}. The formula <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">nCr</strong> (also written as "n choose r") calculates the number of ways to select r objects from n total objects.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Combinations Formula
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> nCr = n! / [r! × (n-r)!]
<br><br>
This gives the number of ways to choose r objects from n total objects when order doesn''t matter.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> How many ways can you choose 3 students from a class of 10 to form a committee?
<br><br>
Order doesn''t matter (choosing Alice, Bob, Carlos is the same as Carlos, Alice, Bob).
<br><br>
₁₀C₃ = 10! / [3! × (10-3)!]
<br>
= 10! / (3! × 7!)
<br>
= (10 × 9 × 8 × 7!) / (3! × 7!)
<br>
= (10 × 9 × 8) / (3 × 2 × 1)
<br>
= 720 / 6
<br>
= 120 ways
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Permutations vs. Combinations
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Key difference:</strong> nPr counts ordered arrangements; nCr counts unordered selections
<br><br>
<strong>Relationship:</strong> nPr = nCr × r!
<br>
(Each combination can be arranged in r! ways)
<br><br>
<strong>Example with 3 items from {A, B, C, D, E}:</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>Permutations ₅P₃:</strong> ABC, ACB, BAC, BCA, CAB, CBA, ABD, ADB, ... = 60 total
<br>
(All different orderings count)
<br><br>
<strong>Combinations ₅C₃:</strong> {ABC}, {ABD}, {ABE}, {ACD}, ... = 10 total
<br>
(ABC and ACB count as same selection)
<br><br>
<strong>Check:</strong> ₅P₃ = 60 = ₅C₃ × 3! = 10 × 6 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Complementary Counting
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
Sometimes it''s easier to count what you DON''T want, then subtract from the total.
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> How many ways can you choose at least 2 people from a group of 5?
<br><br>
<strong>Direct method:</strong> ₅C₂ + ₅C₃ + ₅C₄ + ₅C₅ = 10 + 10 + 5 + 1 = 26
<br><br>
<strong>Complementary method:</strong>
<br>
Total ways to choose any number: 2⁵ = 32 (each person in or out)
<br>
Subtract choosing 0 people: ₅C₀ = 1
<br>
Subtract choosing 1 person: ₅C₁ = 5
<br>
Result: 32 - 1 - 5 = 26 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Combinations with Multiple Groups
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A committee of 5 people must include 3 women and 2 men. There are 8 women and 6 men available. How many different committees can be formed?
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Choose 3 women from 8
<br>
₈C₃ = 8! / (3! × 5!) = (8 × 7 × 6) / (3 × 2 × 1) = 336 / 6 = 56
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Choose 2 men from 6
<br>
₆C₂ = 6! / (2! × 4!) = (6 × 5) / (2 × 1) = 30 / 2 = 15
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Multiply (each women selection can pair with each men selection)
<br>
Total committees = 56 × 15 = 840
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 3: Combinations
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    A pizza shop offers 8 different toppings. If you want to order a pizza with exactly 3 toppings, how many different pizzas can you order?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> 24</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> 56</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> 120</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> 336</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> 512</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Order doesn''t matter</strong> (pepperoni + mushroom + olive = olive + pepperoni + mushroom)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">Use combinations: ₈C₃ = 8! / (3! × 5!)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">= (8 × 7 × 6) / (3 × 2 × 1)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">= 336 / 6 = 56</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: B</strong> — Order doesn''t matter, so combination not permutation!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Advanced Counting Problems
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Advanced counting problems</strong> often combine multiple techniques and require careful analysis to determine which method to use. You''ll encounter problems with <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">restrictions</strong> (certain objects must be together or apart), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">multiple stages</strong> (combining permutations and combinations), and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">casework</strong> (breaking into separate cases). The key is identifying whether order matters, what restrictions apply, and whether to count directly or use complementary counting.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Problems with "Together" Restrictions
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Strategy:</strong> Treat grouped objects as a single unit, then arrange within the group.
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> In how many ways can 5 people sit in a row if two specific people must sit next to each other?
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Treat the two people as one unit
<br>
Now we have 4 "units" to arrange: (AB), C, D, E
<br>
These can be arranged in 4! = 24 ways
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> The two people can be arranged within their unit
<br>
AB or BA: 2! = 2 ways
<br><br>
<strong>Total:</strong> 24 × 2 = 48 ways
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Problems with "Apart" Restrictions
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Strategy:</strong> Total arrangements - arrangements where they''re together
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Using the same 5 people, in how many ways can they sit if two specific people must NOT sit next to each other?
<br><br>
<strong>Total arrangements:</strong> 5! = 120
<br>
<strong>Arrangements where they ARE together:</strong> 48 (from previous example)
<br>
<strong>Arrangements where they''re NOT together:</strong> 120 - 48 = 72
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Distributing Objects into Groups
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> How many ways can 9 students be divided into three groups of 3?
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Choose 3 from 9 for first group: ₉C₃ = 84
<br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Choose 3 from remaining 6 for second group: ₆C₃ = 20
<br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Remaining 3 automatically form third group: ₃C₃ = 1
<br><br>
<strong>Product:</strong> 84 × 20 × 1 = 1,680
<br><br>
<strong>But wait!</strong> The groups are indistinguishable (no "first," "second," "third")
<br>
We''ve overcounted by a factor of 3! = 6 (number of ways to label 3 groups)
<br><br>
<strong>Final answer:</strong> 1,680 / 6 = 280 ways
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Choosing When to Use Each Method
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Use Fundamental Counting Principle when:</strong>
<br>
• Making a series of independent choices
<br>
• Building something step by step
<br>
• Creating passwords, codes, or sequences
<br><br>
<strong>Use Permutations when:</strong>
<br>
• Order matters
<br>
• Arranging objects in positions
<br>
• Assigning distinct roles (president, VP, etc.)
<br><br>
<strong>Use Combinations when:</strong>
<br>
• Order doesn''t matter
<br>
• Selecting committee members
<br>
• Choosing items from a menu
<br>
• Forming groups without assigned positions
<br><br>
<strong>Key question to ask:</strong> "If I swap two items, does it create a different outcome?"
<br>
If YES → permutation
<br>
If NO → combination
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 4: Complex Counting
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    How many 4-digit numbers can be formed using the digits 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 without repetition, where the number must be even?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> 60</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> 120</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> 180</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> 240</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> 360</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Start with the restriction:</strong> last digit must be even (2, 4, or 6)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Last digit:</strong> 3 choices (2, 4, or 6)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>First digit:</strong> 5 choices (any of remaining 5 digits)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Second digit:</strong> 4 choices (any of remaining 4 digits)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Third digit:</strong> 3 choices (any of remaining 3 digits)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">Total = 3 × 5 × 4 × 3 = 180</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: H</strong> — Handle restrictions first, then count remaining choices!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Fundamental counting principle: multiply number of choices for each independent event
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>n! = n × (n-1) × (n-2) × ... × 2 × 1; factorial counts all arrangements of n objects
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Permutations (nPr): use when order matters; formula is n!/(n-r)!
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Combinations (nCr): use when order doesn''t matter; formula is n!/[r!(n-r)!]
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Key question: "Does swapping two items create a different outcome?" Yes=permutation, No=combination
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Circular arrangements: (n-1)! because rotations are considered identical
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Permutations with repetition: divide by factorials of repeated items
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For "together" restrictions: treat grouped items as single unit, then arrange within
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For "apart" restrictions: use complementary counting (total - together cases)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Handle restrictions first in counting problems, then count remaining free choices
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-16T01:11:47.804874+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (84ebcab2-ae6c-4873-b4a4-e0e0ddd9fa42, b304f042-84bf-4939-b666-b872b1703f41, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scientific notation</strong> expresses very large or small numbers compactly as a × 10^n.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Format</h3>

<div style="text-align: center; font-size: 20px; margin: 1.5rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: #f3f4f6; border-radius: 8px;">
  <strong>a × 10^n<br><br>where 1 ≤ a < 10<br>n = number of decimal places moved</strong>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">2. Converting</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">Large numbers: positive exponent (5,000,000 = 5 × 10^6)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">Small numbers: negative exponent (0.00003 = 3 × 10^-5)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">Move decimal right → decrease exponent</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">Move decimal left → increase exponent</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">3. Operations</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">Multiply: multiply coefficients, add exponents</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">Divide: divide coefficients, subtract exponents</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">Example: (2×10^3) × (3×10^4) = 6×10^7</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">Key Takeaways</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Format: a × 10^n where 1 ≤ a < 10
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Positive exponent = large, negative = small
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Multiply: add exponents; Divide: subtract exponents
  </li>
</ul>
', 1, '2025-10-14T00:43:13.222325+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (6109f98d-743a-4a0f-b796-0fccc9d31926, b3567108-62ab-4112-b38d-4a4c7e6611af, '<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Mean, Median, Mode, and Range</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Notice that to find the total points for each class, we multiplied the class average by the number of students. In</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">general terms, we multiply the average by the number of items to find the sum. This is commonly the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">first step in many average questions, so make sure that you remember this simple step to find the sum</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">whenever you are given an average.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Now, we can solve for the average score for all students combined.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">2. Total Points</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">3. Total Students</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">4. The answer is C.</h3>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 3: Erica’s golden retriever gave birth twice in the last two years. Her first litter had 7 puppies</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">with an average weight of p lbs. Her second litter had 5 puppies with an average weight of m pounds.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Which of the following expressions correctly calculates the average weight w, in pounds, of all of the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">puppies that Erica’s golden retriever gave birth to over the last two years?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. w= ——</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. w</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">weight of all the puppies and divide it by the total number of puppies. First, we can find the total weight of her</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">7p = total weight of puppies in 1st litter</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We can repeat this to find the total weight of the second litter:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">5m = total weight of puppies in 2nd litter</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We know that there are 12 puppies total, so now we can calculate the average weight.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">5. The answer is C.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Method 2 — Pick Numbers. For many students, this question is difficult because we are not given any values</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">for the average weights of the litters. To make this question easier, we can use substitution and pick numbers.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Let’s say the first litter has an average weight of 1 pound (p = 1) and the second litter has an average weight</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">of 3 pounds (m = 3). We can use our numbers to solve for the average weight of the puppies in both litters.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Total Weight of 1st Litter = 7 x 1=7</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The first litter had 7 puppies with an average weight of 1 pound, so the total weight of the litter is 7 pounds.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">6. Total Weight of 2nd Litter</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The second litter had 5 puppies with an average weight of 3 pounds, so the total weight is 15 pounds. Now,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">we can find the average weight of each puppy from these two litters.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">With our values of p = 1 and m = 3, we found that w = = To find the correct answer choice, plug in our</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">values of p = 1 and m = 3 to the answer choices and see which one gives you w = =: Below, you can see</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">how the correct answer choice C gives us the correct value for w.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">7. The answer is C.</h3>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 4: During the first 30 minutes of work at Birkee’s Bakery, Vaivani decorated 23 cookies per</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">minute for the first 10 minutes and then at 14 cookies per minute for the next 20 minutes. Which of the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">following gives the average number of cookies that Vaivani decorated per minute for her first 30 minutes</p>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">5</li>
</ul>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D.</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">average of 23 cookies per minute is for 10 minutes and the second average of 14 cookies per minute is for 20</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">minutes, these averages cannot be treated equally. In math, this is called a weighted average. To solve</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">weighted average questions with two items, we can use the equation below:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">(average #1)(weight #1) + (average #2)(weight #2)</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">In this equation, the two averages are the given averages, so we plug in 23 for average #1 and 14 for average</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">#2. The weight refers to the significance of the data point. Exactly what the weight is will depend on the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">question. For Example 4, the weight is the number of minutes, with 10 being weight #1 and 20 being weight</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">#2. If there was a question where we were trying to calculate your final grade and 70% of your grade was</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">from homework and 30% was from tests, the percentages of 70 and 30 would be the weights. The weights are</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">used to reflect that certain averages have more “weight,” or more significance, than others.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Now, let’s get back to Example 4 and use the weighted average formula to solve:</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">8. The answer is D.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The weighted average formula is a very important one and can be used to solve many ACT average questions.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Looking back to Example 2, we can use a weighted average to solve. In that question, the averages are given</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">as 85 for the first class and 90 for the second class. The weight is the number of students in each class, which</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We even could use the weighted average formula for Example 3. The averages are given to be p and m. The</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">weight is the number of puppies in each litter, which is 7 and 5.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Make sure that you understand how the weighted average formula works. As you can see, knowing how to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">properly find a weighted average can allow you to solve many difficult-looking average questions in one quick</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">9. Step.</h3>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 5: Patricia’s average score on her first 4 chemistry tests is 88. How many points higher than</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">her current average score must Patricia score on her 5th test for her new average on all 5 tests to increase</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 8</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 6</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 5</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">find the total number of points Patricia must have scored on her first 4 tests.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Since we know the final average must be 90, we can now solve for the 5" test score, x.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">10. Chapter 12: Mean, Median, Mode, and Range</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Patricia’s 5" test score is 98, which is 10 points higher than the original average of 88. The answer is A.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Mathematically, this works because the additional 10 points above the average are equally divided over 5 tests,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">so the overall score will increase by =, or 2 points. If that shortcut method is confusing to you, just stick with</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the normal method we used to solve questions like this.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 6: The mean household income in a neighborhood with 80 residents is $90,250 per year. Ifa</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">new family moves in with a household income of $1,859,000, which of the following values for the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">neighborhood will most likely change the least?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A. Mean</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. Median</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. Maximum</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. Range</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">of the neighborhood. In statistics, we call values that are far higher or lower than any other numbers in the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">data set outliers. Any outlier will greatly increase the range and maximum value. The new family’s</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">income is also so large that it will increase the mean household income for the neighborhood.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The median will change the least. Since the median is the middle value in a data set, any outliers always</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">have a minimal effect on the median. The answer is B.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 7: For her science fair experiment, Monica wanted to find out if her tree frog or bullfrog has the</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">bigger jump. She placed each frog on a starting spot and then measured how far the frogs jumped, in</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">inches. The results for each frog, in inches, are below:</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">11. Tree Frog: 41, 18, 30, 8, 14, 33</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">12. Bullfrog: 38, 19, 66, 48, 45, 33, 10</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Iffis the median jump length for the tree frog and / is the median jump length for the bullfrog, what is the</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 20</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 24</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 29</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">13. Tree Frog: 8, 14, 18, 30, 33, 41</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">14. Bullfrog:</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Next, we cross out numbers from both sides to find the median. For data sets with an odd number of numbers,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">such as the bullfrog data in this question, the median is just the middle value. For data sets with an even</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">number of numbers, such as the tree frog data in this question, you need to take the average of the two middle</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Tree Frog: 8, +4, 18, 30, 33, 44</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Bullfrog: +0, 49, 33, 38, 45, 48, 66</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">15. The answer is A.</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">16. Finding the Median in a Table</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The ACT also sometimes asks you to find the median value in a frequency table. For these questions, we will</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">need to use a more efficient method than listing all the values and crossing off to find the median value.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 8: The school newspaper recently surveyed 51 students about their monthly consumption of</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">cheeseburgers. The results of the survey are summarized in the table below. What was the median</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">number of cheeseburgers eaten each month by the students in the survey?</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">17. Number of Burgers Eaten</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">18. Number of Students</h3>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A. 0</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 2-3</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 4-5</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">find the median term, there are three quick steps:</p>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;"></li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">19. Add 1 to the total number of items in the data set.</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;"></li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">20. Divide that number by 2.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">If we have a data set with an odd number of items, the number we get is the term that is</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">If we have a data set with an even number of items, we will get an answer that ends in 0.5.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">In this case, the median is the average of the two middle terms. The two middle terms are</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the integers right above and below the value that we get from our first two steps. For</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">example, if we have a group of 20, we would get 10.5 in step 2. This tell us that two</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">middle terms will be the 10th and 11th terms. We find the median by finding the average</p>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;"></li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">21. Find where the term is in the table.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">In this question, we have 51 students who were surveyed, so following Step 1 above</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">we find the 26th student will be the median data point in the set. To find where the 26th student is in the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">table, start at the top of the table and simply add up the students until you find the 26th student. Here,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">there are 7 students who ate 0 burgers and 19 who ate 1 burger. If we add 7 and 19 together, we get 26,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">so we can tell that the 26th student ate 1 burger. As a result, the median is 1 and the answer is B.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">22. Chapter 12: Mean, Median, Mode, and Range</h3>

<p style="height: 1px; margin: 0; padding: 0;"></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; visibility: hidden; height: 0; margin: 0; padding: 0; overflow: hidden;">.</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">Key Takeaways</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Master these concepts for ACT success
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Practice with ACT-style problems to build confidence
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Apply these strategies on test day
  </li>
</ul>', 1, '2025-10-16T06:35:19.27126+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (274654e0-eb7f-47ae-99ec-6bb34c1f9a6a, b67d7cbd-29c3-4dd1-b764-9d54541691f3, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Math
Topic: Mean, Median, Mode, and Range
Lesson Key: 6.1
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Understanding <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">measures of central tendency</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">measures of spread</strong> is fundamental for ACT Math statistics problems. These problems test your ability to calculate <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">mean</strong> (average), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">median</strong> (middle value), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">mode</strong> (most frequent), and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">range</strong> (spread), as well as interpret what these values reveal about data sets. Statistics questions appear in 4-6 questions per ACT—that''s about 7-10% of all math questions! This lesson covers basic calculations, effects of outliers, weighted averages, and how to find missing values when given summary statistics.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Understanding Mean (Average)
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">mean</strong>, or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">arithmetic average</strong>, is the sum of all values divided by the number of values. It''s the most common measure of central tendency and is sensitive to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">outliers</strong> (extremely high or low values). The ACT frequently tests your ability to work backwards from a given mean to find missing values or calculate required scores.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Calculating the Mean
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> Mean = (Sum of all values) / (Number of values)
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find the mean of 12, 18, 15, 20, 10
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Sum = 12 + 18 + 15 + 20 + 10 = 75
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Count = 5 values
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Mean = 75 ÷ 5 = 15
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Finding Missing Values
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> The mean of 5 test scores is 84. Four scores are 78, 82, 88, and 90. What is the fifth score?
<br><br>
<strong>Method 1: Use the formula</strong>
<br>
Mean = Total / Number of scores
<br>
84 = Total / 5
<br>
Total = 84 × 5 = 420
<br><br>
Sum of known scores: 78 + 82 + 88 + 90 = 338
<br>
Fifth score = 420 - 338 = 82
<br><br>
<strong>Method 2: Think about deviations from mean</strong>
<br>
78 is 6 below mean (-6)
<br>
82 is 2 below mean (-2)
<br>
88 is 4 above mean (+4)
<br>
90 is 6 above mean (+6)
<br>
Total deviation so far: -6 - 2 + 4 + 6 = +2
<br>
Fifth score must be 2 below mean: 84 - 2 = 82
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Effect of Adding or Removing Values
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Five numbers have a mean of 20. If 30 is added to the set, what is the new mean?
<br><br>
<strong>Original sum:</strong> 5 × 20 = 100
<br>
<strong>New sum:</strong> 100 + 30 = 130
<br>
<strong>New mean:</strong> 130 ÷ 6 ≈ 21.67
<br><br>
<strong>Key insight:</strong> Adding a value above the mean increases the mean; adding below decreases it
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Weighted Averages
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A student scores 85 on a test worth 40% of the grade and 90 on a test worth 60%. What is the weighted average?
<br><br>
<strong>Calculation:</strong> (85 × 0.40) + (90 × 0.60) = 34 + 54 = 88
<br><br>
<strong>Formula:</strong> Weighted average = Σ(value × weight) where weights sum to 1
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 1: Mean Calculation
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    Sarah''s test scores are 88, 92, 85, and 79. What score must she earn on her fifth test to have an average of exactly 88?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> 88</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> 92</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> 95</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> 96</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> 100</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Required total for average of 88 over 5 tests: 88 × 5 = 440</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Current sum: 88 + 92 + 85 + 79 = 344</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Fifth score needed: 440 - 344 = 96</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: D</strong> — Work backwards from the desired mean!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Understanding Median
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">median</strong> is the middle value when data is arranged in order. Unlike the mean, the median is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">resistant to outliers</strong>, making it a better measure of central tendency for skewed data. For an <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">odd number</strong> of values, the median is the middle value. For an <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">even number</strong>, it''s the average of the two middle values.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Finding the Median (Odd Number of Values)
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find the median of 15, 22, 18, 30, 12
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Arrange in order: 12, 15, 18, 22, 30
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Count: 5 values (odd)
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Middle position = (5 + 1) / 2 = 3rd value
<br><br>
<strong>Median:</strong> 18
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Finding the Median (Even Number of Values)
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find the median of 8, 12, 15, 20, 25, 30
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Already in order
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Count: 6 values (even)
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Two middle positions: 3rd and 4th values (15 and 20)
<br><br>
<strong>Median:</strong> (15 + 20) / 2 = 17.5
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Median vs Mean with Outliers
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Data set: 5, 6, 7, 8, 100
<br><br>
<strong>Mean:</strong> (5 + 6 + 7 + 8 + 100) / 5 = 126 / 5 = 25.2
<br>
<strong>Median:</strong> 7 (middle value)
<br><br>
<strong>The outlier (100) dramatically affects the mean but not the median</strong>
<br><br>
This is why median income is often reported instead of mean income—a few billionaires would skew the mean upward!
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Finding Missing Values Given the Median
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Five numbers in order are x, 12, 18, 24, 30. If the median is 18, what could x be?
<br><br>
<strong>Analysis:</strong> The median (3rd value) is 18 ✓
<br><br>
<strong>Constraint:</strong> For the ordering to be valid, x must be ≤ 12
<br><br>
<strong>Answer:</strong> x can be any value ≤ 12 (like 5, 10, 12, etc.)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 2: Median Calculation
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    The test scores for 7 students are: 72, 85, 91, 88, 76, 95, 82. What is the median score?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> 82</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> 85</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> 86.5</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> 88</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> 91</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Arrange in order: 72, 76, 82, 85, 88, 91, 95</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Count: 7 values (odd number)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Middle position = (7 + 1) / 2 = 4th value</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 4:</strong> The 4th value is 85</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: G</strong> — Always arrange data in order first!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Mode and Range
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">mode</strong> is the value that appears most frequently in a data set. A set can have <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">no mode</strong> (all values appear equally), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">one mode</strong> (unimodal), or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">multiple modes</strong> (bimodal, trimodal, or multimodal). The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">range</strong> measures the spread of data and equals the difference between the maximum and minimum values.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Finding the Mode
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example 1: One mode</strong>
<br>
Data: 3, 7, 7, 9, 12, 7, 15
<br><br>
<strong>Mode:</strong> 7 (appears 3 times, more than any other value)
<br><br>
<strong>Example 2: Two modes (bimodal)</strong>
<br>
Data: 5, 8, 8, 10, 12, 12, 15
<br><br>
<strong>Modes:</strong> 8 and 12 (both appear twice)
<br><br>
<strong>Example 3: No mode</strong>
<br>
Data: 2, 4, 6, 8, 10
<br><br>
<strong>Mode:</strong> None (all values appear exactly once)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Calculating the Range
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> Range = Maximum value - Minimum value
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find the range of 12, 8, 15, 22, 9, 18
<br><br>
<strong>Maximum:</strong> 22
<br>
<strong>Minimum:</strong> 8
<br>
<strong>Range:</strong> 22 - 8 = 14
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Effect of Adding/Removing Values on Range
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Original data:</strong> 5, 10, 15, 20 (range = 20 - 5 = 15)
<br><br>
<strong>Add 25:</strong> 5, 10, 15, 20, 25 (range = 25 - 5 = 20) ← increased
<br><br>
<strong>Add 12:</strong> 5, 10, 12, 15, 20 (range = 20 - 5 = 15) ← unchanged
<br><br>
<strong>Key insight:</strong> Range only changes if you add a new maximum or minimum
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
When to Use Which Measure
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Use Mean when:</strong> Data is roughly symmetric with no extreme outliers
<br><br>
<strong>Use Median when:</strong> Data has outliers or is skewed (like income or home prices)
<br><br>
<strong>Use Mode when:</strong> You want the most common value (like shoe size or survey responses)
<br><br>
<strong>Use Range when:</strong> You want a simple measure of spread (though it''s sensitive to outliers)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 3: Mode and Range
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    A data set contains the values: 14, 18, 14, 22, 26, 18, 30, 14. What are the mode and range?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> Mode = 14, Range = 14</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> Mode = 14, Range = 16</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> Mode = 18, Range = 16</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> Mode = 14, Range = 30</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> Mode = 19, Range = 16</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Count frequencies: 14 appears 3 times, 18 appears 2 times, others appear once</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Mode = 14 (most frequent)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Range = Max - Min = 30 - 14 = 16</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: B</strong> — Count carefully to find the mode!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Advanced Applications and Comparisons
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Advanced statistics problems</strong> require comparing multiple measures, understanding their relationships, and interpreting what they reveal about data <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">distribution</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">skewness</strong>. You''ll also need to work with <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">grouped data</strong>, calculate measures from <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">frequency tables</strong>, and understand how transforming data affects summary statistics.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Relationships Between Mean, Median, and Mode
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Symmetric distribution:</strong> Mean ≈ Median ≈ Mode
<br>
Example: 2, 4, 5, 6, 6, 7, 8, 10
<br><br>
<strong>Right-skewed (positively skewed):</strong> Mode < Median < Mean
<br>
Example: 2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5, 12 (the 12 pulls the mean up)
<br><br>
<strong>Left-skewed (negatively skewed):</strong> Mean < Median < Mode
<br>
Example: 1, 8, 9, 9, 10, 10, 11 (the 1 pulls the mean down)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Working with Frequency Tables
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Calculate the mean from this frequency table:
<br><br>
Value: 2, Frequency: 3
<br>
Value: 4, Frequency: 5
<br>
Value: 6, Frequency: 2
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Calculate weighted sum: (2×3) + (4×5) + (6×2) = 6 + 20 + 12 = 38
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Total frequency: 3 + 5 + 2 = 10
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Mean = 38 / 10 = 3.8
<br><br>
<strong>Mode:</strong> 4 (highest frequency of 5)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Effect of Transformations on Statistics
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Original data:</strong> 2, 4, 6, 8, 10
<br>
Mean = 6, Median = 6, Range = 8
<br><br>
<strong>Add 5 to each value:</strong> 7, 9, 11, 13, 15
<br>
Mean = 11 (increased by 5)
<br>
Median = 11 (increased by 5)
<br>
Range = 8 (unchanged!)
<br><br>
<strong>Multiply each value by 2:</strong> 4, 8, 12, 16, 20
<br>
Mean = 12 (multiplied by 2)
<br>
Median = 12 (multiplied by 2)
<br>
Range = 16 (multiplied by 2)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Combining Data Sets
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Class A has 20 students with mean score 80. Class B has 30 students with mean score 90. What is the combined mean?
<br><br>
<strong>Wrong approach:</strong> (80 + 90) / 2 = 85 ✗
<br><br>
<strong>Right approach:</strong>
<br>
Total from Class A: 20 × 80 = 1,600
<br>
Total from Class B: 30 × 90 = 2,700
<br>
Combined total: 1,600 + 2,700 = 4,300
<br>
Combined count: 20 + 30 = 50
<br>
Combined mean: 4,300 / 50 = 86
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 4: Complex Application
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    The mean of six numbers is 15. If one of the numbers is removed, the mean of the remaining five numbers is 12. What was the removed number?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> 3</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> 12</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> 15</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> 27</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> 30</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Original sum of 6 numbers: 15 × 6 = 90</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> New sum of 5 numbers: 12 × 5 = 60</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Removed number: 90 - 60 = 30</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: K</strong> — Calculate total sums, then subtract!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Mean = sum ÷ count; to find missing values, work backwards using total sum
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Median requires arranging data in order first; it''s the middle value (or average of two middle values)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Mode is the most frequent value; a data set can have no mode, one mode, or multiple modes
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Range = maximum - minimum; it only changes if you add a new extreme value
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Mean is sensitive to outliers; median is resistant to outliers
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>In symmetric data: mean ≈ median; in skewed data: they differ
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For frequency tables: multiply each value by its frequency, sum, then divide by total frequency
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Adding constant to all values: mean and median increase by that constant, range unchanged
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Multiplying all values by constant: mean, median, and range all multiply by that constant
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>When combining data sets, use weighted averages based on group sizes
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-16T01:08:00.49077+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (bf194ccf-edc6-47e7-aee8-c4cfa78499fc, b71b1a4f-4c89-4c91-9b00-f0e845fa0c91, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">On the ACT, you need to know how lines, parabolas, and other <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">functions shift and transform</strong> in the coordinate plane. All functions follow the same transformation rules.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Transformation Rules</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Four key rules govern how functions transform:</p>

<div style="text-align: center; font-size: 18px; margin: 1.5rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: #f3f4f6; border-radius: 8px;">
  <strong>1. Inside parentheses → Horizontal shifts<br>
  Adding shifts LEFT, subtracting shifts RIGHT<br><br>
  2. Outside parentheses → Vertical shifts<br>
  Adding shifts UP, subtracting shifts DOWN<br><br>
  3. Negative sign in front → Vertical flip over x-axis<br><br>
  4. Coefficient in front → Vertical stretch/compression<br>
  Greater than 1 = stretch, less than 1 = compression</strong>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">2. Horizontal Shifts</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Numbers inside the parentheses cause horizontal shifts. The direction may seem backwards:</p>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;"><strong>f(x − 3):</strong> Shifts 3 units RIGHT (subtracting shifts right)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;"><strong>f(x + 2):</strong> Shifts 2 units LEFT (adding shifts left)</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">3. Vertical Shifts</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Numbers outside the parentheses cause vertical shifts. This follows intuition:</p>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;"><strong>f(x) + 4:</strong> Shifts 4 units UP (adding shifts up)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;"><strong>f(x) − 3:</strong> Shifts 3 units DOWN (subtracting shifts down)</li>
</ul>', 1, '2025-10-14T00:38:17.33404+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (90342246-4a03-4ae9-93ad-4176c1c0684d, b7e9b337-8dd0-4ec5-8e57-badb58a43bca, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Science
Topic: Figures and Text Integration
Lesson Key: figures-text
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Figures and text integration questions require you to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">combine information from visual data</strong> with details from the passage text, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">interpret figures using context</strong> provided in written descriptions, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">apply definitions and explanations</strong> from the passage to understand what figures show, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">synthesize numerical data with conceptual information</strong>. Unlike pure data-reading questions that can be answered entirely from figures, or pure comprehension questions that require only the text, these hybrid questions test your ability to move fluidly between written explanations and visual representations, use passage context to interpret ambiguous figure elements, and connect theoretical concepts described in text with empirical results shown in graphs and tables. This lesson teaches you systematic approaches for identifying when text context is necessary to interpret figures, explains how to efficiently locate relevant passage information for figure-based questions, provides strategies for understanding figure components that require passage definitions, and shows you how to avoid the common pitfall of attempting to answer questions from figures alone when passage context is essential.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Understanding When Text Context is Essential
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Text-dependent figure questions</strong> cannot be answered correctly from the figures alone—they require understanding <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">definitions, experimental conditions, or explanations</strong> provided in the passage text.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Recognizing When You Need the Passage Text
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Several <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">signals indicate</strong> that passage text is necessary: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Figure labels use technical terms or abbreviations</strong> that aren''t defined in the figure itself. If a graph shows "Species A" and "Species B" but doesn''t explain what these species are, you need the passage. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Questions ask about conditions, procedures, or variables mentioned in the question but not visible in the figure</strong>. If a question asks "In which trial was the catalyst used?", the figure might show different trials but the passage text explains which had the catalyst. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Questions require interpretation beyond raw data</strong>, such as "Which figure shows the results when the independent variable was held constant?" You need the passage to know what the independent variable is and whether it was held constant. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Answer choices refer to concepts or categories</strong> (like "acidic solution", "endothermic reaction", "control group") that require understanding what conditions or characteristics define these categories. If you look at a figure and realize you don''t understand what a label means, or you can''t determine which condition corresponds to what the question is asking, that''s your signal to check the passage text.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Types of Information Typically Found in Passage Text
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Passage text typically provides: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Definitions of technical terms</strong>. The passage might define "pH" or explain what "absorbance" means, which helps you understand what the figure''s y-axis represents. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Experimental procedures and conditions</strong>. The text explains that "Students measured temperature every 5 minutes while heating the solution" or "Trial 1 used distilled water; Trial 2 used salt water", clarifying what conditions differ between data sets. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Variable relationships and theoretical background</strong>. The passage might explain that "As temperature increases, molecular motion increases, leading to higher reaction rates", helping you interpret why a figure shows an upward trend. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identification of samples, species, or materials</strong>. The text might state "Solution A contained 0.1 M NaCl; Solution B contained 0.1 M KCl", explaining what the labels "Solution A" and "Solution B" in the figure represent. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Units and measurement methods</strong>. The passage clarifies "Students measured mass in grams using a digital balance" or explains that "light intensity was measured in lumens". This information contextualizes the numerical data in figures and helps you understand what''s actually being measured.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Initial Passage Scan for Figure Context
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
During your <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">initial passage reading</strong> (before diving into questions), perform a quick scan specifically to understand how text and figures relate: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read the passage introduction</strong> (first 2-3 sentences) to understand the general topic and what''s being studied. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scan for sections that reference figures</strong>. Look for phrases like "as shown in Figure 1", "results are presented in Table 1", or "see Figure 2". These tell you where text and figures connect. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Note any definitions or explanations of variables</strong>. If the passage defines what "trial 1" versus "trial 2" represents, make a mental note. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify experimental conditions</strong> described in the text that might explain differences between data sets in figures. This 20-30 second scan creates a mental map of where to look when you need text context for figure interpretation, saving you time when questions require integrated information.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Common Scenarios Requiring Text Integration
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Certain <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">recurring scenarios</strong> almost always require text integration: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scenario 1: Identifying control groups or variables.</strong> Questions like "Which trial was the control?" require the passage to explain which conditions define the control. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scenario 2: Distinguishing between similar-looking data sets.</strong> If multiple lines or bars in a figure look similar, the passage explains what differentiates them (different catalysts, different concentrations, etc.). <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scenario 3: Questions about "why" or causation.</strong> While figures show patterns, the passage often explains why those patterns occur or what theoretical principle they demonstrate. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scenario 4: Converting between figure labels and question terminology.</strong> The question asks about "acidic conditions" but the figure shows "pH < 7"—the passage provides the knowledge that pH < 7 means acidic. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scenario 5: Questions asking what would happen under different conditions.</strong> "What would happen if temperature were decreased?" requires understanding from the passage what factors affect the measured variable, not just reading data points. Recognizing these scenarios helps you know immediately that text consultation is necessary.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Identifying Text Dependency</strong><br><br>
<strong>Figure shows:</strong> Three lines labeled "Trial 1", "Trial 2", "Trial 3" showing temperature vs. time<br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> "In which trial was the insulated container used?"<br><br>
<strong>Analysis:</strong><br>
- Figure shows data for three trials but doesn''t indicate which had insulation<br>
- The question asks about experimental conditions not shown in the figure<br>
- Signal: You need the passage text<br><br>
<strong>Passage text says:</strong> "Students heated water in three containers: Trial 1 used a glass beaker, Trial 2 used an insulated thermos, and Trial 3 used a metal pot."<br><br>
<strong>Now you know:</strong> Trial 2 used the insulated container<br><br>
Without reading the passage, you could see the data but couldn''t identify which trial had insulation. The figure and text must be integrated to answer correctly.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Strategies for Efficiently Locating Relevant Passage Information
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When you''ve identified that a question requires text context, you need <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">efficient search strategies</strong> to find the relevant information quickly without re-reading the entire passage.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Keywords to Navigate the Passage
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Keyword scanning</strong> is the fastest way to locate specific information: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Extract key terms from the question</strong>. If the question asks about "the catalyst", your keyword is "catalyst". If it asks about "Trial 2", your keyword is "Trial 2". (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scan the passage for that exact term or close synonyms</strong>. Don''t read every word—let your eyes move quickly down the page looking for the keyword to "pop out". (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">When you locate the keyword, read the surrounding 1-2 sentences</strong> carefully. The relevant information is usually within this context. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If the keyword appears multiple times</strong>, quickly skim each occurrence to determine which provides the needed information. For example, "Trial 2" might be mentioned in the methods (describing setup) and results (describing outcomes)—you likely need the methods section. This targeted scanning is much faster than re-reading the entire passage and helps you find information in 10-15 seconds rather than 45-60 seconds.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Understanding Passage Structure to Predict Information Location
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
ACT Science passages follow <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">predictable structures</strong>, which helps you know where to look: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Introduction (first paragraph)</strong>: Provides general topic, background, and definitions of key terms. Look here for: what''s being studied, why it matters, definitions of technical terms. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Methods/Procedure section</strong>: Explains how experiments were conducted, what varied between trials, what was measured. Look here for: experimental conditions, differences between trials, control vs. experimental groups, measurement procedures. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Results section (often integrated with figures)</strong>: Describes what was observed. Look here for: interpretations of trends, explanations of patterns. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Figure captions or notes</strong>: Provide specific details about what figures show. Look here for: units, definitions of symbols or labels, special conditions. When you need to find specific information, think about what type of information it is, then go directly to the relevant section rather than searching randomly.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Cross-Reference Method for Figure Labels
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When a figure uses <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">labels, abbreviations, or symbols</strong> that aren''t self-explanatory, use this systematic approach: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify the unclear label</strong>. For example, a figure might show "Solution X" and "Solution Y" but not explain what these are. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check the figure caption first</strong>. Many figures include notes like "X = distilled water, Y = salt water" right below the figure. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If not in the caption, scan the passage for the label term</strong>. Search for "Solution X" or just "X" in the passage. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read the sentence containing the label</strong> to understand what it represents. The passage might say "Students prepared Solution X by dissolving 10 g of sugar in water" and "Solution Y contained no sugar", clarifying what each represents. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Make a quick note if needed</strong> (like writing "X=sugar, Y=no sugar" near the figure) so you don''t have to look it up again for subsequent questions. This cross-reference method is essential for correctly interpreting figures that use abstract labels.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Recognizing When Information Isn''t Explicitly Stated
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Sometimes, the connection between text and figures requires <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">inference rather than explicit statement</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">The passage describes a general principle</strong>, and you need to apply it to interpret figure patterns. For example, "Increasing temperature increases molecular motion" helps you understand why a graph shows higher reaction rates at higher temperatures, even though the passage doesn''t explicitly say "Figure 1 shows that higher temperatures cause higher reaction rates". (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">The passage describes different conditions</strong>, and you need to match them to unlabeled figure elements. If the passage says "Trial 1 had the highest initial concentration" and Figure 1 shows three lines with one starting highest, you can infer that the highest line represents Trial 1. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Definitions must be applied to classify data</strong>. The passage might define "basic solutions have pH > 7" and then ask which trial used a basic solution—you check the figure to see which trial had pH > 7. To handle these situations: Read the passage for general principles and definitions, then actively apply them to interpret figure data rather than expecting every connection to be explicitly spelled out.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Efficient Information Location</strong><br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> "Which trial used the control group?"<br><br>
<strong>Step 1 (Keyword identification):</strong> Keywords are "trial" and "control group"<br><br>
<strong>Step 2 (Predict location):</strong> Experimental conditions → likely in methods/procedure section<br><br>
<strong>Step 3 (Keyword scan):</strong> Scan passage for "control"<br>
Found in paragraph 2: "Students set up four trials. Trial 1 served as the control with no fertilizer added. Trials 2, 3, and 4 received different amounts of fertilizer."<br><br>
<strong>Step 4 (Extract answer):</strong> Trial 1 = control<br><br>
<strong>Time elapsed:</strong> 10-15 seconds<br><br>
Without this systematic approach, you might waste 45+ seconds re-reading the entire passage trying to find which trial was the control.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Integrating Text Explanations with Figure Data
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Integration</strong> means combining what you learn from the passage text with what you observe in figures to form complete, accurate answers.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Text to Interpret Figure Trends
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When questions ask you to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">explain or interpret trends</strong>, you often need both figure data (to see what happened) and passage text (to explain why): (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify the trend in the figure</strong>. For example, "As pH increases, enzyme activity increases up to pH 7, then decreases". (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for passage explanations of what affects the measured variable</strong>. The passage might explain: "Enzymes work best at optimal pH. Too acidic or too basic conditions denature the enzyme". (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Connect the explanation to the trend</strong>. The peak at pH 7 represents the optimal pH; below and above that, denaturation reduces activity. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use this integrated understanding to answer interpretation questions</strong> like "Why did enzyme activity decrease above pH 7?" Answer: "The basic conditions caused denaturation". The figure tells you that it decreased; the passage tells you why. Together, they form a complete answer.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Text to Distinguish Between Figure Elements
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When figures contain <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">multiple data sets</strong> (multiple lines, multiple bars, multiple trials), passage text often explains what distinguishes them: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Note what varies between the data sets</strong>. The figure might show three different lines but not explain what''s different about them. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Find the passage description of experimental setup</strong>. The text might explain: "Trial 1 used a copper catalyst, Trial 2 used an iron catalyst, Trial 3 used no catalyst". (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Match passage descriptions to figure elements</strong>. If the passage says "reactions with catalysts were faster" and you see two lines above one line in the figure, you can infer that the top two lines are Trials 1 and 2 (with catalysts) and the bottom line is Trial 3 (no catalyst). (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use this matching to answer questions</strong> about specific conditions. "Which trial showed the fastest rate?" = whichever line is highest = Trials 1 or 2 (one with a catalyst). This integration allows you to identify what different figure elements represent even when labels are minimal.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Applying Text Definitions to Categorize Figure Data
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Many questions require you to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">apply definitions from the text</strong> to classify or categorize data in figures: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify the category or classification mentioned in the question</strong>. For example, "Which trials used endothermic reactions?" (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Find the passage definition of that category</strong>. The text might say: "Endothermic reactions absorb heat, causing temperature to decrease". (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check the figure to see which data meets the definition</strong>. Look at the temperature data in the figure—which trials show temperature decreasing? (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Those trials match the category</strong>. If Trials 2 and 4 show temperature decreasing, those were endothermic. This process requires actively applying text-based definitions to classify figure data. You can''t answer these questions from the figure alone (which just shows temperature changes) or from the text alone (which defines endothermic but doesn''t say which specific trials were endothermic)—you must integrate both sources.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Text to Make Predictions Beyond Figure Data
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Some questions ask you to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">predict what would happen under conditions not shown in the figure</strong>: "If students increased the concentration further, what would likely happen to the reaction rate?" To answer these: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Observe the trend in the figure</strong>. The figure might show that as concentration increases from 0.1 to 0.5 M, reaction rate increases from 10 to 50 units/sec. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check the passage for theoretical explanations</strong>. The text might explain: "Higher concentration means more reactant molecules available for collisions, increasing reaction rate". (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Apply the principle to make the prediction</strong>. Since higher concentration consistently increases rate, further increases in concentration would likely continue to increase rate. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Select the answer that matches your reasoning</strong>. The figure shows the pattern; the text explains the underlying mechanism; together they enable prediction beyond the measured data.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Integrating Text and Figure</strong><br><br>
<strong>Passage text says:</strong> "Solutions with pH < 7 are acidic. Solutions with pH = 7 are neutral. Solutions with pH > 7 are basic."<br><br>
<strong>Figure shows:</strong> Table with four solutions and their measured pH values:
- Solution A: pH = 4
- Solution B: pH = 7
- Solution C: pH = 9
- Solution D: pH = 11<br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> "Which solutions were basic?"<br><br>
<strong>Integration process:</strong><br>
Step 1: Find definition of "basic" in passage → pH > 7<br>
Step 2: Check figure for pH values > 7 → Solutions C (pH 9) and D (pH 11)<br>
Step 3: Integrate → Solutions C and D were basic<br><br>
<strong>Answer:</strong> C and D<br><br>
Neither the text alone (which defines basic but doesn''t identify specific solutions) nor the figure alone (which shows pH values but doesn''t define what "basic" means) is sufficient. You must integrate both.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Pitfalls and Advanced Strategies
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Avoiding common mistakes</strong> and employing advanced strategies helps you maximize accuracy on text-figure integration questions.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Pitfall #1: Attempting to Answer from Figures Alone
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The most common error is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">trying to answer text-dependent questions using only figure data</strong>. Students see a question that mentions a figure and immediately look at the figure without reading the passage, leading to wrong answers when context is essential. To avoid this: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Always read the question completely</strong> before deciding you only need the figure. Look for terminology that requires definition or context. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If a question asks about concepts, categories, or conditions</strong> (like "control group", "acidic solution", "endothermic reaction"), assume you need the passage. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If you look at the figure and can''t tell which element corresponds to what the question asks</strong>, that''s a signal you need text context. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">When in doubt, do a quick 10-second passage scan</strong> for relevant keywords. This small time investment prevents wrong answers. Many students prioritize speed over accuracy and skip the passage consultation, resulting in preventable errors.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Pitfall #2: Mismatching Passage Descriptions to Figure Elements
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When passages describe multiple conditions and figures show multiple data sets, students sometimes <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">incorrectly match</strong> which description goes with which figure element. For example, if the passage describes Trial 1, 2, and 3 in one order but the figure shows them in a different order or with different symbols, confusion results. To prevent this: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for explicit connections</strong>. Check if the passage or figure caption explicitly states "Trial 1 is shown as circles, Trial 2 as squares". (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use distinguishing characteristics to match</strong>. If the passage says "Trial 1 had the highest initial temperature" and one line in the figure starts highest, that''s Trial 1. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Don''t assume order matches</strong>. Just because the passage discusses A, B, C in that order doesn''t mean the figure shows them left-to-right or top-to-bottom in the same order. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Verify your matching makes sense</strong>. If the passage says "adding a catalyst increased the rate" and you''ve matched the slowest line to the catalyst condition, you''ve likely mismatched.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Pitfall #3: Over-Relying on Prior Knowledge Instead of Passage Definitions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Some students use <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">outside knowledge</strong> to interpret figures rather than using passage definitions, which can lead to errors if the passage uses terms in specific ways. For example, you might know from chemistry class that "catalyst" generally speeds up reactions, but a specific passage might define a catalyst differently for that context, or might be testing a different aspect. To avoid this: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Always use passage definitions when provided</strong>. If the passage defines a term, use that definition rather than your prior knowledge. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">The ACT Science section tests reading comprehension and data interpretation</strong>, not recall of outside science facts. The passage provides all needed information. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If your prior knowledge conflicts with passage information</strong>, trust the passage. The passage is the authoritative source for that question. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Prior knowledge is helpful for general understanding</strong> but shouldn''t override specific passage details. While some general science knowledge is useful, relying on it instead of reading carefully causes errors when passages use terms in specific ways.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Advanced Strategy: Annotating Figures with Text Context
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
An <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">efficient advanced technique</strong> is to annotate figures with brief notes from the passage: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">When you find important text context for a figure</strong>, write a brief note directly on or next to the figure. For example, if the passage says "Trial 1 used the catalyst", write "catalyst" next to the Trial 1 line in the figure. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Label unclear abbreviations or symbols</strong>. If the figure shows "A" and "B" and the passage explains these are "acidic" and "basic" solutions, write those terms near the labels. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Note key conditions or characteristics</strong>. If the passage indicates which trial was the control, which had the highest concentration, etc., mark this on the figure. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">These annotations serve as a reference for all questions</strong>, so you don''t have to re-consult the passage repeatedly for the same information. This technique is especially valuable for complex passages with multiple trials or conditions. The few seconds spent annotating save significant time across multiple questions and reduce errors from forgetting or confusing text context.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Avoiding Pitfalls</strong><br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 1 - Figure-Only Attempt:</strong><br>
Question: "Which trial used the control group?"<br>
Figure shows: Three lines labeled Trial 1, 2, 3<br>
Wrong approach: Guess based on the figure alone → 33% chance<br>
Correct approach: Scan passage → "Trial 1 was the control" → 100% confidence<br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 2 - Mismatching:</strong><br>
Passage: "Solution A was most concentrated. Solution B was least concentrated."<br>
Figure: Two lines, top line and bottom line (unlabeled which is which)<br>
Wrong assumption: Top line must be A because it''s mentioned first<br>
Correct reasoning: "Most concentrated" should show highest values → Check which line shows higher values → That''s Solution A (might be bottom line if axes show it differently)<br><br>
<strong>Pitfall 3 - Prior Knowledge Override:</strong><br>
Question: "Which solution was acidic?"<br>
You know: Lemon juice is acidic<br>
Passage: "Acidic solutions have pH < 7. Solution X had pH 5, Solution Y had pH 9."<br>
Wrong: Choose Solution Y because you remember it''s what you tested in class once<br>
Correct: Use passage definition → pH < 7 = acidic → Solution X (pH 5) is acidic<br><br>
<strong>Advanced Strategy - Annotation:</strong><br>
After reading passage, annotate figure:<br>
Trial 1 → Write "control" next to it<br>
Trial 2 → Write "high temp"<br>
Trial 3 → Write "low temp"<br>
Now all subsequent questions can be answered quickly using annotations without re-reading passage.
</p>
</div>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Many questions require integrating information from both passage text and figures—neither source alone is sufficient
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>If questions ask about concepts, categories, or conditions not defined in the figure, you need passage text
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Passage text provides definitions, experimental conditions, variable relationships, and sample identifications
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use keyword scanning to quickly locate relevant passage information without re-reading everything
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Check figure captions first for definitions of labels and symbols before searching the full passage
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Apply text definitions to categorize figure data (e.g., use pH definition to identify which solutions are acidic)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use passage explanations to interpret trends and make predictions beyond the measured data range
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Don''t attempt to answer text-dependent questions from figures alone—always check if context is needed
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Verify that passage descriptions correctly match figure elements—don''t assume they''re in the same order
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Annotate figures with brief text context to save time on subsequent questions requiring the same information
  </li>
</ul>
