<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Solutions, Roots, x-intercepts, and Zeros for Quadratic Equations</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The ACT may ask you to find the “solutions,”</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">“roots,” x-intercepts,” or “zeros” of a quadratic equation. All</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">these terms refer to the values of x that make f(x) = 0. Remember, all these terms mean the same thing. We</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">will refer to these as the “solutions” in the rest of this chapter.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To find the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">solution</strong>(s), set the quadratic equation equal to zero and factor. Let’s pick up with the example we</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We just showed how we can factor this quadratic to get</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To find the solutions, set each factor equal to zero and solve.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The solutions are x = = and x = 1.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Remember that the solutions are also the x-intercepts if the quadratic is graphed (more on this on the next</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 3: What is the sum of the roots of the polynomial f(x) = x2 — 11x +18?</h4>

