<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Horizontal shifts change the where the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">function is at x = 0. Normally, the sine</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">function passes through the origin.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">However, if the function shifts</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">horizontally, it may no longer pass</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">through the origin (as seen with the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Horizontal shifts are the least common type of transformation with sine and cosine functions on the ACT.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Summary of Transformation Rules for Sine and Cosine Functions</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">All the transformation rules we have covered in this chapter are summarized below:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">|A| is the amplitude of the function (half of the total height of the graph).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">e The period of the function for sine, cosine, secant, and cosecant is equal to |. For tangent</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">and cotangent graphs, the period is equal to El.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">C shifts the graph horizontally. A positive value of C shifts the graph left, and a negative value of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">C shifts the graph to the right. The magnitude of the shift is equal to <,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">D shifts the graph vertically. A positive value of D shifts the graph up, and a negative value of D</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">shifts the graph down. The magnitude of the shift is equal to D.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Tangent functions are very rarely tested on the ACT, but they have appeared on the test before and will appear</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">again. You should only study this if you feel confident on the other trigonometry topics or are aiming for</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Tangent functions look quite different from the sine and cosine functions we just learned, but if you know</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">what a tangent function generally looks like, you should be able to answer any tangent graphing questions</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">e Tangent functions cross the origin.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Tangent functions do not have an amplitude.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Tangent functions have vertical asymptotes (shown</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">as dotted lines in the graph) that occur regularly z</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Tangent functions repeat infinitely in both directions.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">*Note that the “basics to know” listed above are for y = tan x. Horizontal and vertical shifts can change</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the characteristics of a tangent function.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The period of a tangent function is defined by EI, where B is the constant that x is multiplied by in the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Using the graph above, notice that the period is equal to 7. The easiest way to find the period of a tangent</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">function is to find the distance between the vertical asymptotes.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Transformations of Tangent Functions</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Tangent functions follow the same rules as sine and cosine functions for vertical and horizontal shifting</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">that we summarized on the previous page.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">That covers pretty much everything you need to know for tangent graphs on the ACT! If you know the basics</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">of what a tangent graph looks like, how to find the period of a tangent function, and the rules for vertical and</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">horizontal shifting, you should be able to solve a tangent graphing question if it appears on your ACT.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 12: Which of the following equations properly describes the function shown below?</h4>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Solution</strong>:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The vertical shift is the easier part, so we will start with that. A tangent function normally intersects the origin,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">but we see the tangent function passing through the point (0,—1). Therefore, we know the function is shifted</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">down 1 unit, so we must see —1 as the D-value. We can eliminate C because the vertical shift is incorrect.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To find the period of a tangent function, we find the distance between two vertical asymptotes. We see two</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">vertical asymptotes at x = —7 and x = 7 so we know the period of the function is ></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Now that we know the period, we need to use the B-values in the answer choices to find which one has a</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">period of > Remember, we use Hl to find the period for tangent functions, not |</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Questions like this have only appeared at the end of ACTs as part of the hard questions from 45-60 and are not</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">common. If you are preparing for test day in a more of a rush, graphing tangents is not an important topic to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">For students who are aiming for top scores, make sure you understand how to solve a question like this, as it is</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">not too technically hard if you understand the basics.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The ACT LOVES to test you on two advanced trigonometry rules: Law of Sines and Law of Cosines. Many</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">of you will have never learned these before, so we will teach you everything you need to know in this chapter.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">These two topics are very common on the ACT, so you need to memorize both the law of sines and law</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">of cosines equations for test day.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The Law of Sines rules written below is true for any type of triangle. It is important to note that Law of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Sines can be used for non-right triangles.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The Law of Sines is a property for any triangle. For Law of Sines (and Law of Cosines), we no longer use</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">SOH-CAH-TOA. So, for the sines in the equation above, do not think opposite over hypotenuse. Instead,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">remember that an expression such as sin(20°) has a numerical value, so we treat it as a number.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Law of Sines can also be written as:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">This equation is the same as the one above — everything is just flipped. You can memorize and use either</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">equation. Both are equally effective. You need to memorize the equation because the ACT does not always</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We use the Law of Sines to solve for an unknown side or angle in a triangle.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 13: Which of the following correctly solve for the value of x in the triangle below?</h4>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Solution</strong>:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Here, we have two pairs: 110° and 850 and 28° and x. To solve, we set up the Law of Sines equation.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Now, we solve for x. To do so, we first cross-multiply and then divide by sin(110°).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">*Note: For Law of Sines questions on the ACT, the answer choices usually give away that you need to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">use Law of Sines. If you ever see answer choices like the ones in Example 12, you are looking at a Law of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Sines question. Most questions do not ask you to solve for a numerical value. Usually, you are asked to find</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">which expression in the answer choices correctly solves for the unknown as we did in the example above.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">That first example was a simpler example, as we were asked to solve for a side length. What if we were asked</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 14: In the triangle shown below, which of the following expressions correctly solves for k ?</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. sinTM+ aa )</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. sin“? (=)</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Solution</strong>:</strong></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">57. To solve, we start by setting up the Law of Sines equation.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We want to solve for k, so first we need to multiply both sides by 92.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Ok, now for the fun (hard) part! We know what sin(k°) is equal to, so to solve for k we need to use the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">inverse sine function. If you need to review inverse functions, we covered them on page 148.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The answer is B. Now if you are thinking, woah, that was hard! Yes, it absolutely was. Questions like this</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">are often some that students find most difficult on the ACT. A question like Example 13 would be one that is</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">meant to challenge the best math students. If you have never done any of this advanced trigonometry before</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">and find this extremely difficult, you can always skip these questions on test day and save them for last.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">As with the Law of Sines rules we just learned, the Law of Cosines is a property of any triangle. Law of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Cosines is used to find a missing side or angle in a non-right triangle. The Law of Cosines equation is</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We use Law of Cosines when we do not have two pairs of angles and opposite side lengths. It is important to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">notice that the a-value in the equation is the side length opposite the angle A. The other two side lengths, b</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">and c, are interchangeable since they do the same thing in the equation.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">On the ACT, you are not always given the Law of Cosines, so you need to memorize the equation. The</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">ACT sometimes includes the equation in a note below the question, but it is not always provided.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">You need to know how to set up the Law of Cosines correctly. Depending on the difficult of the question, you</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">may need to perform additional algebra to solve for the unknown value, as we did in the Law of Sines</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 15: Three dancers, Alex, Bialy, and Charlie, are standing on stage at the points shown by the</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">comers of the triangle below. Alex is standing 35 feet from Bialy, 31 feet from Charlie, and the angle</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">formed where Alex is standing has a measure of 28°. Which of the following equations solves for the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">distance, in feet, between Bialy and Charlie?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 352 + 312 — 2(35)(31) cos 28°</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Solution</strong>:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">use normal SOH-CAH-TOA. We are not provided two pairs of angles and opposite side lengths, so we cannot</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The side length we are solving for is opposite the angle that we are given, so the length between Bialy and</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Charlie is the a-value. 35 and 31 are b and c. Plugging these values into the Law of Cosines equation, we get:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">a* = 357 + 31? — 2(35)(31) cos 28°</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To solve for a, we take the square root of both sides.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">a = 352 + 312 — 2(35)(31) cos 28°</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">*Note: For Law of Cosines questions on the ACT, the answer choices usually give away that you need to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">use Law of Cosines. If you see any complicated looking answer choices with cosines, like C and D in</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Example 14, you are looking at a Law of Cosines question.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Remember the unit circle? The one your math teacher made you memorize all of those points for? Well, it’s</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">back. However, the unit circle is NOT a commonly tested topic on the ACT (and the least commonly</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">tested trigonometry topic). You should only study this if you feel confident on the other trigonometry</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">topics or are aiming for a top ACT Math score.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">You do not need to memorize all the points but should know the basics of the unit circle for the ACT. For</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">students aiming for top math scores, we recommend memorizing the entire unit circle.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">A complete unit circle is shown below.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Angles on the unit circle can be expressed in degrees or radians. Just as we can describe the temperature in</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Fahrenheit or Celsius, we can describe an angle in degree or radians. If you have not worked with radians</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">before, all you need to know is that 7 radians = 180 degrees. It is important to memorize this conversion for</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">test day. We will cover radians vs. degrees at the end of this chapter in more depth.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">There are a few important principles to know with the unit circle.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The cosine of any angle on the unit circle is equal to the x-coordinate of the corresponding point.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The sine of any angle on the unit circle is equal to the y-coordinate of the corresponding point.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The tangent of any angle on the unit circle is equal to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">which simplifies to tan(60°) = V3.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Understanding these three principles and memorizing the unit circle can make many unit circle questions easy.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 16: On the interval 0 < 6 < 27, sin@ = 2 is true for what value(s) of 6 ?</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A. =,</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Solution</strong>:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The interval from 0 < @ < 27 includes the entire unit circle, but sometimes the ACT limits which portion of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the unit circle we should look at with a smaller interval.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Remember, the sine of any angle is equal to the y-coordinate of the point. So, we need to look at the unit</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">circle and find the point(s) that have 2 as the y-coordinate. If we look at the unit circle (or have it</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">memorized), we see that 7 and = have 8 as the y-coordinate, so we know</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The other important thing to know for the unit circle is which quadrants cosine, sine, and tangent are positive</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">or negative. The unit circle below shows the values (positive or negative) for cosine, sine, and tangent.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">A common moniker to memorize this is “All Student Take Calculus.” “AII” tells us all 3 values are positive in</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the 1st quadrant. “Students” stands for Sine and tells us only sine 1s positive in the 2nd quadrant and the other</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">values are negative. “Take” stands for Tangent and tells us only tangent is positive in the 3rd quadrant.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">“Calculus” tells us only Cosine is positive in the 4th quadrant.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The most common way the ACT tests this knowledge is with a more advanced version of Example 3 that we</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">solved earlier in this chapter.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 17: For an angle with a measure of q in a right triangle, sing = = and tang = — =, what is the</h4>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Solution</strong>:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">How does that change the question? Well, since sin > 0 and tan < 0, we know that g must be in the 2nd</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">quadrant. In the 2nd quadrant, cos < 0, so we already know that C, D, and E are incorrect.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The rest of the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">solution</strong> is the same as we already did for Example 3, so we will not show it again here. The</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">only difference is that when we solve for cos gq = = from the triangle we drew, we make the value negative</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">since we are in the 2nd quadrant, so the answer is A.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Radians are another unit to measure angles. Just like we can measure temperature in Fahrenheit or Celsius, we</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">can measure an angle in degrees or radians. For the ACT, you need memorize the conversion below:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To convert between radians and degrees, use following 2 rules:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To convert from radians to degrees, multiply by a</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To convert from degrees to radians, multiply by</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 18: Angle D has a measure of 200°. If angle D can be written in its most simplified form as</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">=i radians, where a and b are both integers, what is the value of a + b?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 38</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Solution</strong>:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">conversion question, start with the given, which is 200°, and then use the conversion factor to change the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">, the degree signs cancel, so we are left with radians. The question says angle D</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">can be written as 5 radians, so we can see thata = 10 andb =9. a+b = 19. The answer is C.</p>

<p style="height: 1px; margin: 0; padding: 0;"></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; visibility: hidden; height: 0; margin: 0; padding: 0; overflow: hidden;">.</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">Key Takeaways</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Master these concepts for ACT success
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Practice with ACT-style problems to build confidence
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Apply these strategies on test day
  </li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-16T01:07:59.529236+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (8d1af833-8cb4-4a0b-9d49-a886c0434af5, bc360ff1-6a1b-4982-8bb0-6d1da31934f8, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Function transformations allow you to predict how graphs shift, stretch, reflect, and compress based on changes to the equation. Mastering these transformations helps you quickly sketch graphs and solve ACT problems involving function families.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Vertical and Horizontal Shifts
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Vertical shifts</strong> move the entire graph up or down without changing its shape. Adding a constant k to the function shifts the graph vertically: f(x) + k moves up k units if k > 0, and down |k| units if k < 0.
</p>', 0, '2025-10-16T16:09:00.61681+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (e8387e33-a812-44df-8af8-4bdf1c73146e, bea21e83-3495-4287-aeb9-c1ba70e0c182, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Logical placement questions</strong> test your ability to organize information effectively by determining where a sentence belongs within a paragraph or where a paragraph belongs within an essay. These questions require you to understand <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">logical flow</strong>, recognize <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">transitions</strong>, and identify how ideas build upon one another. Whether you''re placing a sentence within a paragraph or reordering entire paragraphs, success depends on identifying <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">chronological sequences</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">cause-effect relationships</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">references</strong> that connect ideas.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Understanding Sentence Placement Questions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Question Format
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Sentence placement questions present a sentence (usually in a box) and ask you to determine where it should be placed within a paragraph. The paragraph''s sentences are numbered [1], [2], [3], [4], etc., and answer choices typically offer:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>A. Where it is now (before sentence 1)</li>
<li>B. After sentence 1</li>
<li>C. After sentence 2</li>
<li>D. After sentence 3</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
You must determine which position creates the most logical flow of ideas.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Key Strategies for Sentence Placement
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
To place a sentence correctly, look for specific connections between the sentence and its context:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Identify references:</strong> Look for pronouns (it, they, this, that) or demonstrative phrases (this technique, these results) in the sentence you''re placing. These references must have clear antecedents—the noun they refer to must appear in the preceding sentence.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>Sentence to place:</strong> [This discovery changed how scientists understood the disease.]
<br><br>
<strong>Key question:</strong> What does "this discovery" refer to? It must be placed immediately after a sentence that describes a specific discovery.
<br><br>
If sentence 2 says "In 2010, researchers identified a genetic marker linked to the condition," then "this discovery" logically refers to the genetic marker identification. The sentence should be placed after sentence 2.
</p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Follow chronological order:</strong> If the sentence describes an event, action, or step in a process, it must fit the time sequence established by surrounding sentences.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Match cause and effect:</strong> If the sentence describes a result or consequence, it must follow the sentence that presents the cause.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Recognize topic shifts:</strong> The sentence might introduce a new idea or conclude a discussion. Place it where the topic naturally transitions.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Reading for Context
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Don''t just read the sentence you''re placing—carefully read the entire paragraph to understand:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>The paragraph''s organization:</strong> Is it chronological? Does it move from general to specific? From problem to solution?</li>
<li><strong>What each numbered sentence discusses:</strong> Identify the main point of sentences 1, 2, 3, and 4</li>
<li><strong>How ideas currently flow:</strong> Look for transitions and logical connections between existing sentences</li>
<li><strong>Where gaps or transitions occur:</strong> The sentence you''re placing often fills a logical gap or creates a necessary transition</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
This comprehensive understanding helps you identify where the new sentence naturally fits.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Analyzing References and Transitions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Pronouns and Demonstrative References
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The most reliable clues for sentence placement are pronouns and demonstrative phrases that require clear antecedents:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Pronouns requiring antecedents:</strong>
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><em>It, they, them, these, those</em> must refer to specific nouns in the preceding sentence</li>
<li><em>He, she, her, his</em> must follow introduction of the person</li>
<li>The pronoun and its antecedent must agree in number (singular/plural)</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>Sentence to place:</strong> [She spent the next decade refining these techniques.]
<br><br>
<strong>Analysis:</strong> Two clues here:
<br>
1. "She" requires a female person to be introduced first
<br>
2. "These techniques" requires specific techniques to be mentioned immediately before
<br><br>
The sentence must be placed after a sentence that both introduces a female person and describes specific techniques she developed.
</p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Demonstrative phrases:</strong>
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>"This method," "this approach," "this discovery" refer to something specific just mentioned</li>
<li>"Such techniques," "such results" point to examples or outcomes in the previous sentence</li>
<li>"That finding," "that conclusion" reference a specific claim or result</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
These phrases create strong dependencies—the sentence containing them MUST immediately follow the sentence that introduces what they reference.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Transition Words as Placement Clues
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Transition words and phrases in the sentence you''re placing reveal its logical relationship to surrounding sentences:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Continuation/Addition transitions</strong> (moreover, furthermore, additionally, also) indicate the sentence should follow related content, adding to the same idea.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Contrast transitions</strong> (however, nevertheless, yet, in contrast) signal the sentence presents an opposing or different idea from what precedes it.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Cause/Effect transitions</strong> (therefore, consequently, as a result, thus) show the sentence presents a result or conclusion and must follow the cause or premise.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>Sentence to place:</strong> [As a result, the population declined by 40% in just five years.]
<br><br>
"As a result" signals this sentence presents a consequence. It must be placed after a sentence describing the cause of the population decline (such as habitat loss, disease, or environmental change).
<br><br>
If sentence 3 says "Pollution from the nearby factory poisoned the lake," then the population decline is a logical result of that pollution. Place the sentence after sentence 3.
</p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Sequential transitions</strong> (first, next, then, finally) indicate position in a step-by-step process or chronological sequence.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example/Illustration transitions</strong> (for example, for instance, specifically) show the sentence provides a concrete example and should follow a general statement.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Chronological and Sequential Clues
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Many paragraphs follow a time-based order. Look for:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>Dates and time markers:</strong> "In 2015," "After graduation," "During her childhood," "By the end of the decade"</li>
<li><strong>Age or life stage references:</strong> "At age 12," "As a young adult," "In her later years"</li>
<li><strong>Process steps:</strong> "Before mixing," "During fermentation," "After cooling"</li>
<li><strong>Historical periods:</strong> "During the Renaissance," "In the post-war era"</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The sentence you''re placing must fit this chronological progression. If sentence 1 discusses the 1990s and sentence 2 discusses the 2010s, a sentence about events in 2005 logically fits between them.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong>
<br><br>
[1] Chen began studying marine biology in college. [2] After earning her doctorate, she joined the research team at the Scripps Institution. [3] There, she made her groundbreaking discovery about coral reef resilience.
<br><br>
<strong>Sentence to place:</strong> [Her undergraduate thesis on tidal ecosystems earned recognition from the National Science Foundation.]
<br><br>
<strong>Analysis:</strong> "Undergraduate thesis" happens during college, which is mentioned in sentence 1. "After earning her doctorate" in sentence 2 comes later. Therefore, the sentence about her undergraduate work should be placed after sentence 1, before sentence 2.
<br><br>
<strong>Answer: After sentence 1</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Understanding Paragraph Placement Questions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Question Format
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Paragraph placement questions typically appear at the end of a passage and ask you to determine the most logical order for numbered paragraphs. The question format is:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
"For the sake of logic and coherence, Paragraph 3 should be placed:"
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>F. where it is now.</li>
<li>G. after Paragraph 1.</li>
<li>H. after Paragraph 4.</li>
<li>J. after Paragraph 5.</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
These questions test your understanding of how entire paragraphs relate to one another and build the essay''s argument or narrative.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Identifying Each Paragraph''s Function
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
To reorder paragraphs effectively, identify what each paragraph does:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Introduction paragraphs:</strong>
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Introduce the topic, person, or event</li>
<li>Provide essential background or context</li>
<li>Usually contain the essay''s thesis or main idea</li>
<li>Should come first (or very early) in the essay</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Development paragraphs:</strong>
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Present evidence, examples, or details</li>
<li>Build on information from previous paragraphs</li>
<li>Often follow chronological or logical progression</li>
<li>May introduce new aspects of the topic</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Conclusion paragraphs:</strong>
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Summarize or reflect on what''s been discussed</li>
<li>Present final outcomes or implications</li>
<li>May look to the future or broader significance</li>
<li>Should come last (or very late) in the essay</li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Looking for Dependencies Between Paragraphs
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Certain paragraphs depend on others and cannot be placed before them:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>References to previously mentioned information:</strong> If a paragraph begins with "This discovery" or "These efforts," it must follow the paragraph that introduces the discovery or efforts.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Chronological dependencies:</strong> A paragraph about "her later career" cannot come before paragraphs about her early life and education.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Logical progression:</strong> A paragraph describing results depends on earlier paragraphs explaining the experiment or process.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>Paragraph 2:</strong> Discusses how Dr. Lopez developed a new vaccine in 2015
<br>
<strong>Paragraph 3:</strong> Begins with "Following this breakthrough, she received the Nobel Prize"
<br><br>
<strong>Analysis:</strong> "This breakthrough" in Paragraph 3 clearly refers to the vaccine development in Paragraph 2. Therefore, Paragraph 3 MUST come after Paragraph 2. Any answer choice that places Paragraph 3 before Paragraph 2 is automatically wrong.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Common Essay Organization Patterns
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Recognizing these common patterns helps you determine logical paragraph order:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Chronological/Biographical:</strong> Follows a person''s life or events over time—childhood, education, career, later achievements.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Problem-Solution:</strong> Introduces a problem, explains its causes or severity, presents solutions, describes outcomes.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>General to Specific:</strong> Begins with broad context, narrows to specific examples, cases, or applications.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Cause and Effect:</strong> Presents a situation or cause, then explores various effects or consequences.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Process Description:</strong> Explains steps in order—preparation, execution, results, significance.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Identify which pattern the essay follows, then ensure paragraphs appear in the order that pattern requires.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Strategic Approach and Practice
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Step-by-Step Method for Sentence Placement
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 1: Read the sentence to be placed.</strong> Identify key clues:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Pronouns or demonstrative references (it, this, these, that)</li>
<li>Transition words (however, therefore, for example)</li>
<li>Time markers or chronological clues</li>
<li>Specific terms that need to be introduced first</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 2: Read the entire paragraph.</strong> Understand the flow and identify what each numbered sentence discusses.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 3: Test each placement option.</strong> For each answer choice, mentally insert the sentence in that position and ask:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Do all references have clear antecedents?</li>
<li>Does the chronology make sense?</li>
<li>Do transitions work logically?</li>
<li>Does the sentence flow naturally in and out?</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 4: Eliminate illogical placements.</strong> Often you can quickly eliminate 1-2 options that create obvious problems (references with no antecedents, chronological impossibilities).
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 5: Choose the most natural fit.</strong> The correct placement creates smooth logical flow without forcing connections.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Step-by-Step Method for Paragraph Placement
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 1: Identify the paragraph in question.</strong> Read it carefully and note:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Its main topic or purpose</li>
<li>Opening references or transitions</li>
<li>Chronological or logical markers</li>
<li>Dependencies on other information</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 2: Skim all paragraphs.</strong> Get a sense of:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Which introduces the topic</li>
<li>The chronological or logical sequence</li>
<li>Which concludes the essay</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 3: Look for strong dependencies.</strong> Identify any paragraph that clearly must come before or after the paragraph in question.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 4: Test each placement option.</strong> Consider whether each position creates logical flow or causes problems.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 5: Select the option that creates the most coherent progression.</strong> The correct placement follows the essay''s organizational pattern and maintains all logical dependencies.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Time Management
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Placement questions require careful reading but shouldn''t consume excessive time:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>Sentence placement: 45-60 seconds</strong> - Read the paragraph and test placement logically</li>
<li><strong>Paragraph placement: 60-90 seconds</strong> - Requires skimming multiple paragraphs but clear dependencies often make the answer obvious</li>
<li><strong>Use strong clues first:</strong> If you spot a clear pronoun reference or chronological marker, use it to quickly eliminate wrong answers</li>
<li><strong>Don''t overthink:</strong> The correct placement should feel natural; if you''re forcing connections, you''ve likely chosen the wrong position</li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Complete Practice Example
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Paragraph:</strong>
<br><br>
[1] The restoration project began in 2018 with a survey of the building''s structural damage. [2] Workers carefully removed layers of old paint to reveal the original murals underneath. [3] By 2022, the historic theater had been transformed, returning to its 1920s grandeur. [4] Artisans spent months recreating decorative plasterwork that had deteriorated over the decades.
<br><br>
<strong>Sentence to place:</strong> [These murals, painted by renowned artist Diego Rivera, had been hidden for nearly 80 years.]
<br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> For the sake of logic and coherence, this sentence should be placed:
<br><br>
A. where it is now (before sentence 1)<br>
B. after sentence 1<br>
C. after sentence 2<br>
D. after sentence 3
<br><br>
<strong>Analysis:</strong>
<br>
<strong>Key clue:</strong> "These murals" is a demonstrative reference requiring an antecedent—murals must be mentioned immediately before this sentence.
<br><br>
<strong>Chronology check:</strong> The sentence provides additional detail about murals, not a time-sequenced step in the restoration.
<br><br>
<strong>Testing options:</strong>
<br>
- Before sentence 1: No prior mention of murals—"these murals" has no antecedent ❌
<br>
- After sentence 1: Sentence 1 discusses structural survey, not murals ❌
<br>
- After sentence 2: Sentence 2 mentions "the original murals"—"these murals" clearly refers to them ✓
<br>
- After sentence 3: This would separate the description of the murals from their discovery, disrupting flow ❌
<br><br>
The sentence provides elaboration about the murals mentioned in sentence 2 (who painted them, how long they were hidden). This information naturally follows the discovery of the murals.
<br><br>
<strong>Answer: C (after sentence 2)</strong>
</p>
</div>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Advanced Example (Paragraph Placement):</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>Essay about a scientist''s career:</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>Paragraph 1:</strong> Introduces Dr. Sarah Kim and her childhood fascination with insects
<br>
<strong>Paragraph 2:</strong> Describes her groundbreaking discovery of a new species in 2019
<br>
<strong>Paragraph 3:</strong> Discusses her graduate research at Cornell University
<br>
<strong>Paragraph 4:</strong> Explains how this discovery led to her receiving the MacArthur Fellowship
<br>
<strong>Paragraph 5:</strong> Reflects on her current work inspiring young scientists
<br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> For the sake of logic and coherence, Paragraph 3 should be placed:
<br><br>
F. where it is now<br>
G. after Paragraph 1<br>
H. after Paragraph 4<br>
J. after Paragraph 5
<br><br>
<strong>Analysis:</strong>
<br>
<strong>Organization pattern:</strong> Biographical/chronological essay about Dr. Kim''s life and career
<br><br>
<strong>Chronological markers:</strong>
<br>
- Paragraph 1: childhood
<br>
- Paragraph 2: 2019 discovery
<br>
- Paragraph 3: graduate research (typically early career, before major discoveries)
<br>
- Paragraph 4: "this discovery" refers to the 2019 discovery in Paragraph 2, describes its consequence
<br>
- Paragraph 5: "current work" indicates present day, conclusion
<br><br>
<strong>Problem:</strong> Graduate research should come before the 2019 discovery, not after it. The chronology is out of order.
<br><br>
<strong>Testing options:</strong>
<br>
- Where it is now (after Paragraph 2): Creates chronological problem ❌
<br>
- After Paragraph 1: Follows childhood with education—chronologically logical ✓
<br>
- After Paragraph 4: Would place graduate school after major discovery and award ❌
<br>
- After Paragraph 5: Would make graduate school the conclusion ❌
<br><br>
<strong>Logical order:</strong> Childhood (P1) → Education/Graduate research (P3) → 2019 Discovery (P2) → Award (P4) → Current work (P5)
<br><br>
<strong>Answer: G (after Paragraph 1)</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0rem; font-weight: 400; visibility: hidden;">
Hidden Section Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 0rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.9;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Logical placement questions test your ability to organize sentences within paragraphs or paragraphs within essays based on logical flow and connections
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> For sentence placement, look for pronouns and demonstrative references (it, this, these, that) that require clear antecedents in the preceding sentence
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Transition words reveal logical relationships—therefore/as a result signal effects that must follow causes; however/in contrast signal opposing ideas
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Follow chronological order—dates, ages, life stages, and time markers must appear in temporal sequence
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Read the entire paragraph to understand its organization and flow before deciding where a sentence belongs
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> For paragraph placement, identify each paragraph''s function (introduction, development, conclusion) and recognize the essay''s organizational pattern
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Look for dependencies—paragraphs with references like "this discovery" or "these efforts" must follow the paragraph introducing what they reference
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Common essay patterns include chronological/biographical, problem-solution, general-to-specific, cause-effect, and process description
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Test each placement option by mentally inserting the sentence/paragraph and checking whether references, chronology, and transitions work logically
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Budget 45-60 seconds for sentence placement, 60-90 seconds for paragraph placement—strong clues often make answers obvious quickly
</li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-13T19:26:15.237439+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (1e95dc06-8a66-4e9a-a404-dd1566d0449d, c03272c5-ebaf-4ebd-8cfb-daed7061cce0, '<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Ratios and Proportions</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">2. Ratios</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We use ratios to make comparisons between two things. Ratios do not give the exact number of items but</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">instead allow us to concisely compare the relationship between two things at the same time.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">As an example, if we have oranges and apples in a basket in the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong> of 2:3, it does not necessarily mean that</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">we have 2 oranges and 3 apples. Instead, the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong> tells us that for every 2 oranges, there are 3 apples. Asa</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">result, you can think of this <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong> as 2x: 3x because we must multiply 2 and 3 by the same value to keep the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">2:3 <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong>. Using this “x” trick will help you on many <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong> questions where you are given a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong> but not any</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">On the ACT, you will need to solve <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong> questions in four different ways. We will review the four types of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong> questions below along with the methods you should use to solve them:</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 1: The ratio of red marbles to green marbles in a bag 1s 4:6. If there are a total of 80 marbles in</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the bag and all of the marbles in the bag are red or green, how many of the marbles are red?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 20</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 32</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 48</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">red marbles and the 6x represents the green marbles.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Red Marbles + Green Marbles = 80</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To solve for the red marbles, we plug x = 8 back into the 4x.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">3. The answer is C.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Method #2: Set up a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Proportion</strong>. We can set up a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">proportion</strong> from the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong>. Since the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratio</strong> or red marbles</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">to green marbles is 4: 6, we know that</p>

