  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Apply these strategies on test day
  </li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-16T16:35:20.79404+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (d18ed265-8ff9-4dd2-b1d3-e883de17971f, c03d9bbc-0d0e-47f1-ac58-cfb6f3e56776, '<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Probability</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Advanced probability questions like examples 8-10 commonly appear at the end of the ACT, usually in</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">questions 35-45, and most students find them very difficult. However, using this simple diagram trick makes</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">questions like this quick and easy to solve!</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">2. Expected Value</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The expected value is the outcome you expect for a probability based event, like how many questions you</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">might answer correctly if you guess on a multiply choice test. For example, if you guess randomly on a</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">60-question multiple-choice math test which choices A, B, C, and D, you can expect to get 25% correct (15 out</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The calculation behind this is simple: take the probability of an event occurring and multiply by the number of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Where P(A) is the probability that event A occurs and A is the number of times event A occurs. For our</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">multiple-choice test example, the probability of guessing an answer correctly is - and the number of questions</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Expected Value = P(guess correctly) x number of questions = =x 60 = 15</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">If you guess randomly on the 60 questions, the expected number of correct answers is 15.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 11: A bag contains 12 identically sized, solid-colored balls. 3 balls are black, 5 are green, 2 are</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">blue, and 2 are yellow. A ball is drawn at random and returned to the bag, and the results are recorded. If</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">this experiment is conducted 600 times, how many times would a green ball be expected to be selected?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 250</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 300</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">3. The answer is C.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">This is the easy type of expected value question that would appear somewhere in the first 30 questions. More</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">advanced expected value questions will include multiple possible outcomes from the same event.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">For example, let’s say that there are four cards on the table facedown. Each card has a number written on it,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">which represents the amount of money the winner gets. If two cards have a 1, one card has a 3, and one card</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">has a 11, what is the expected value of playing the game?</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The approach is the same as before, except that now we need to add the sum of all the expected values using</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Expected Value = P(A) x A + P(B)xB+ P(C)xC...</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">P(A) is probability that events A occurs, and A is the payout for event A. P(B) is probability that events B</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">occurs, and B is the payout for event B, and so on for however many events there are. For our example, the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">probability is the likelihood of picking a card with a certain number. The payout for each event is the number</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">There are 2 cards with a 1, so the probability of randomly picking a card with a 1 on it is =. There is 1 card</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">with a 3, so the probability of randomly picking a card with a 3 on it is = There is 1 card with an 11, so the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">probability of randomly picking a card with a 11 on it is = Using the expected value equation above, we can</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Expected Value = = x 1 + =x 3+ = x 11 = = 4</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The expected value of drawing a card is =, or $4.00. Since the card numbers are only 1, 3, and 11, the winner</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">will never get exactly $4.00, but that is the average payout expected based on the probability and payouts.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 12: Terry is playing a game involving ten identical cards in a deck. Each card has a single</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">number written on it: 4 cards have a 2, 3 cards have a 5, 2 cards have a 10, and 1 card has a 25. Terry will</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">choose a card at random, and he will be awarded the number of points equal to the number written on the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">card. What is the expected value for the number of points that Terry will be awarded if he draws 1 card?</p>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">4</li>
<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 5</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 6.8</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 7.5</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">points awarded from each event, which is just the number on the card. The probability of drawing a 2 is =, the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">probability of drawing a 5 is =, probability of drawing a 10 is = and probability of drawing a 25 is =</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">4. Putting this in our expect value equation, we get:</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Expected Value =+x24+2x54+2x10+—x25= 68</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">5. The answer is C.</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Advanced expected value questions like Example 12 will most likely appear at the end of the test in questions</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">35-45. Students aiming for top math scores should memorize how to set this up.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">6. Chapter 22: Probability</h3>

<p style="height: 1px; margin: 0; padding: 0;"></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; visibility: hidden; height: 0; margin: 0; padding: 0; overflow: hidden;">.</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">Key Takeaways</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Master these concepts for ACT success
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Practice with ACT-style problems to build confidence
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Apply these strategies on test day
  </li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-16T16:35:53.67907+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (738dea66-0736-48e3-b43e-35347ff8a6ec, c3f697b7-4856-4a80-a42d-c20431f1eb26, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Math
Topic: Trigonometry
Lesson Key: 7.1
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Mastering <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">trigonometry</strong> is essential for achieving top scores on the ACT Math section. This lesson covers <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">SOHCAHTOA</strong> (sine, cosine, tangent relationships), the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">unit circle</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">trigonometric identities</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">radian measure</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">trigonometric graphs</strong>. Trigonometry questions appear in 4-6 problems per ACT test and separate high scorers from average performers. Understanding how angles relate to sides in triangles and how trig functions behave is crucial for success.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Right Triangle Trigonometry (SOHCAHTOA)
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The foundation of trigonometry lies in <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">right triangle relationships</strong>. The mnemonic <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">SOHCAHTOA</strong> helps remember the three primary ratios: sine equals opposite over hypotenuse, cosine equals adjacent over hypotenuse, and tangent equals opposite over adjacent. These ratios are defined for any acute angle in a right triangle and provide powerful tools for finding unknown sides and angles. Understanding these fundamental relationships is essential before moving to more advanced trigonometry concepts.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Three Primary Ratios
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
For an angle θ in a right triangle:
<br><br>
<strong>SOH:</strong> sin(θ) = Opposite / Hypotenuse
<br>
<strong>CAH:</strong> cos(θ) = Adjacent / Hypotenuse
<br>
<strong>TOA:</strong> tan(θ) = Opposite / Adjacent
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> In a right triangle, the hypotenuse is 13, one leg is 5. Find sin(θ), cos(θ), and tan(θ) for the angle opposite the leg of length 5.
<br><br>
<strong>First, find the other leg using Pythagorean theorem:</strong>
<br>
5² + b² = 13²
<br>
25 + b² = 169
<br>
b² = 144
<br>
b = 12
<br><br>
<strong>Now identify sides relative to θ:</strong>
<br>
Opposite = 5
<br>
Adjacent = 12
<br>
Hypotenuse = 13
<br><br>
<strong>Calculate ratios:</strong>
<br>
sin(θ) = 5/13
<br>
cos(θ) = 12/13
<br>
tan(θ) = 5/12
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Special Right Triangles
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>45-45-90 Triangle:</strong>
<br>
Sides in ratio 1 : 1 : √2
<br>
If legs = 1, then hypotenuse = √2
<br><br>
sin(45°) = 1/√2 = √2/2
<br>
cos(45°) = 1/√2 = √2/2
<br>
tan(45°) = 1/1 = 1
<br><br>
<strong>30-60-90 Triangle:</strong>
<br>
Sides in ratio 1 : √3 : 2
<br>
Short leg : Long leg : Hypotenuse
<br><br>
<strong>For 30° angle:</strong>
<br>
sin(30°) = 1/2
<br>
cos(30°) = √3/2
<br>
tan(30°) = 1/√3 = √3/3
<br><br>
<strong>For 60° angle:</strong>
<br>
sin(60°) = √3/2
<br>
cos(60°) = 1/2
<br>
tan(60°) = √3
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Inverse Trigonometric Functions
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>When you know the ratio and need the angle:</strong>
<br><br>
sin⁻¹(x) or arcsin(x) gives the angle whose sine is x
<br>
cos⁻¹(x) or arccos(x) gives the angle whose cosine is x
<br>
tan⁻¹(x) or arctan(x) gives the angle whose tangent is x
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> If sin(θ) = 0.6, find θ
<br>
θ = sin⁻¹(0.6) ≈ 36.87°
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> In a right triangle, opposite = 7, adjacent = 24. Find the angle.
<br>
tan(θ) = 7/24
<br>
θ = tan⁻¹(7/24) ≈ 16.26°
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Solving for Unknown Sides
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A ladder leans against a wall at a 70° angle with the ground. If the ladder is 20 feet long, how high up the wall does it reach?
<br><br>
<strong>Setup:</strong>
<br>
The ladder is the hypotenuse (20 ft)
<br>
The height is opposite the 70° angle
<br>
Use: sin(θ) = opposite / hypotenuse
<br><br>
sin(70°) = h / 20
<br>
h = 20 × sin(70°)
<br>
h ≈ 20 × 0.9397
<br>
h ≈ 18.79 feet
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 1: Right Triangle Trig
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    In a right triangle, one angle is 35° and the side adjacent to this angle is 10. What is the length of the hypotenuse?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> 8.2</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> 10</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> 12.2</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> 14.3</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> 17.4</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>We have:</strong> adjacent = 10, need hypotenuse</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Use CAH:</strong> cos(35°) = adjacent / hypotenuse</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">cos(35°) = 10 / h</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">h = 10 / cos(35°) ≈ 10 / 0.8192 ≈ 12.2</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: C</strong> — Use cosine for adjacent/hypotenuse!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. The Unit Circle and Radian Measure
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">unit circle</strong> is a circle with radius 1 centered at the origin, providing a geometric interpretation of trigonometric functions for all angles, not just acute angles in right triangles. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Radian measure</strong> is an alternative to degrees where angles are measured by arc length on the unit circle. Understanding the unit circle allows you to evaluate trig functions for any angle and recognize patterns in their values. The relationship between degrees and radians is fundamental: 180° = π radians.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Converting Between Degrees and Radians
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Key relationship:</strong> 180° = π radians
<br><br>
<strong>To convert degrees to radians:</strong> multiply by π/180
<br>
<strong>To convert radians to degrees:</strong> multiply by 180/π
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Common conversions:</strong>
<br><br>
30° = π/6 radians
<br>
45° = π/4 radians
<br>
60° = π/3 radians
<br>
90° = π/2 radians
<br>
180° = π radians
<br>
270° = 3π/2 radians
<br>
360° = 2π radians
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Convert 135° to radians
<br>
135° × (π/180) = 135π/180 = 3π/4 radians
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Convert 5π/6 to degrees
<br>
(5π/6) × (180/π) = (5 × 180)/6 = 900/6 = 150°
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Unit Circle Coordinates
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>For any angle θ on the unit circle:</strong>
<br>
Point coordinates: (cos θ, sin θ)
<br><br>
<strong>This means:</strong>
<br>
x-coordinate = cos(θ)
<br>
y-coordinate = sin(θ)
<br>
tan(θ) = sin(θ) / cos(θ) = y / x
<br><br>
<strong>Key points on unit circle:</strong>
<br>
0° (0 radians): (1, 0) → cos(0) = 1, sin(0) = 0
<br>
90° (π/2): (0, 1) → cos(90°) = 0, sin(90°) = 1
<br>
180° (π): (-1, 0) → cos(180°) = -1, sin(180°) = 0
<br>
270° (3π/2): (0, -1) → cos(270°) = 0, sin(270°) = -1
<br>
360° (2π): (1, 0) → back to start
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Reference Angles and All Quadrants
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>ASTC rule (All Students Take Calculus):</strong>
<br>
Quadrant I (0° to 90°): All trig functions positive
<br>
Quadrant II (90° to 180°): Sine positive, others negative
<br>
Quadrant III (180° to 270°): Tangent positive, others negative
<br>
Quadrant IV (270° to 360°): Cosine positive, others negative
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Find sin(150°)
<br>
150° is in Quadrant II (sine positive)
<br>
Reference angle: 180° - 150° = 30°
<br>
sin(150°) = sin(30°) = 1/2
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Find cos(240°)
<br>
240° is in Quadrant III (cosine negative)
<br>
Reference angle: 240° - 180° = 60°
<br>
cos(240°) = -cos(60°) = -1/2
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Coterminal Angles
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Coterminal angles</strong> differ by 360° (or 2π radians) and have the same trig values.
<br><br>
<strong>Examples:</strong>
<br>
30°, 390°, 750°, -330° are all coterminal
<br>
sin(30°) = sin(390°) = sin(750°) = sin(-330°) = 1/2
<br><br>
<strong>To find coterminal angles:</strong>
<br>
Add or subtract 360° (or 2π radians)
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Find a positive coterminal angle for -120°
<br>
-120° + 360° = 240°
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 2: Unit Circle
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    What is the value of sin(7π/6)?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> -1/2</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> -√3/2</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> 0</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> 1/2</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> √3/2</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> 7π/6 = π + π/6 = 180° + 30° = 210°</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> 210° is in Quadrant III (sine negative)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Reference angle = 210° - 180° = 30°</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 4:</strong> sin(210°) = -sin(30°) = -1/2</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: F</strong> — Use reference angle and quadrant sign!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Trigonometric Identities and Equations
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Trigonometric identities</strong> are equations that are true for all values of the variables. The most important are the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Pythagorean identity</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reciprocal identities</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">quotient identities</strong>. These identities allow you to simplify expressions, solve equations, and transform between different trig functions. Understanding how to manipulate and apply these identities is crucial for advanced trigonometry problems on the ACT.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Fundamental Identities
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Pythagorean Identity:</strong>
<br>
sin²θ + cos²θ = 1
<br>
(Most important identity!)
<br><br>
<strong>Variations:</strong>
<br>
sin²θ = 1 - cos²θ
<br>
cos²θ = 1 - sin²θ
<br>
1 + tan²θ = sec²θ
<br>
1 + cot²θ = csc²θ
<br><br>
<strong>Quotient Identities:</strong>
<br>
tan θ = sin θ / cos θ
<br>
cot θ = cos θ / sin θ
<br><br>
<strong>Reciprocal Identities:</strong>
<br>
csc θ = 1 / sin θ
<br>
sec θ = 1 / cos θ
<br>
cot θ = 1 / tan θ
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Identities to Simplify
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example 1:</strong> If sin θ = 3/5 and θ is in Quadrant I, find cos θ
<br><br>
<strong>Use Pythagorean identity:</strong>
<br>
sin²θ + cos²θ = 1
<br>
(3/5)² + cos²θ = 1
<br>
9/25 + cos²θ = 1
<br>
cos²θ = 1 - 9/25 = 16/25
<br>
cos θ = ±4/5
<br><br>
Since θ is in Quadrant I (where cosine is positive):
<br>
cos θ = 4/5
<br><br>
<strong>Example 2:</strong> Simplify (1 - sin²x) / cos x
<br><br>
<strong>Use identity sin²x + cos²x = 1:</strong>
<br>
1 - sin²x = cos²x
<br><br>
So: (1 - sin²x) / cos x = cos²x / cos x = cos x
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Solving Trigonometric Equations
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Solve 2sin θ - 1 = 0 for 0° ≤ θ < 360°
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Isolate sin θ
<br>
2sin θ = 1
<br>
sin θ = 1/2
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Find angles where sin θ = 1/2
<br>
Reference angle: 30° (since sin 30° = 1/2)
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Sine is positive in Quadrants I and II
<br>
Quadrant I: θ = 30°
<br>
Quadrant II: θ = 180° - 30° = 150°
<br><br>
<strong>Solutions:</strong> θ = 30° or θ = 150°
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Double-Angle and Sum Formulas
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Double-Angle Formulas:</strong>
<br>
sin(2θ) = 2sin θ cos θ
<br>
cos(2θ) = cos²θ - sin²θ = 2cos²θ - 1 = 1 - 2sin²θ
<br>
tan(2θ) = 2tan θ / (1 - tan²θ)
<br><br>
<strong>Sum/Difference Formulas:</strong>
<br>
sin(A + B) = sin A cos B + cos A sin B
<br>
cos(A + B) = cos A cos B - sin A sin B
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> If sin θ = 3/5 and cos θ = 4/5, find sin(2θ)
<br>
sin(2θ) = 2sin θ cos θ = 2(3/5)(4/5) = 24/25
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 3: Identities
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    Which of the following is equivalent to (sin²x)(csc²x) - 1?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> -1</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> 0</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> 1</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> sin²x</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> cos²x</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Use reciprocal identity: csc x = 1/sin x</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">So csc²x = 1/sin²x</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> (sin²x)(csc²x) = (sin²x)(1/sin²x) = 1</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> 1 - 1 = 0</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: B</strong> — Reciprocal functions multiply to 1!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Graphs of Trigonometric Functions
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Understanding the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">graphs of trig functions</strong> helps visualize their periodic behavior and identify key features. The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">amplitude</strong> measures the height of oscillation, the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">period</strong> is the length of one complete cycle, and the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">phase shift</strong> indicates horizontal translation. Vertical shifts move the midline up or down. Recognizing transformations of parent functions y = sin x, y = cos x, and y = tan x is essential for analyzing trig graphs on the ACT.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Parent Function: y = sin x
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Properties of y = sin x:</strong>
<br>
• Domain: all real numbers
<br>
• Range: [-1, 1]
<br>
• Period: 2π (or 360°)
<br>
• Amplitude: 1
<br>
• Starts at origin (0, 0)
<br>
• Maximum at π/2, minimum at 3π/2
<br><br>
<strong>Key points in one period:</strong>
<br>
(0, 0), (π/2, 1), (π, 0), (3π/2, -1), (2π, 0)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Parent Function: y = cos x
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Properties of y = cos x:</strong>
<br>
• Domain: all real numbers
<br>
• Range: [-1, 1]
<br>
• Period: 2π (or 360°)
<br>
• Amplitude: 1
<br>
• Starts at maximum (0, 1)
<br>
• Zero crossings at π/2 and 3π/2
<br><br>
<strong>Key points in one period:</strong>
<br>
(0, 1), (π/2, 0), (π, -1), (3π/2, 0), (2π, 1)
<br><br>
<strong>Relationship:</strong> cos x = sin(x + π/2)
<br>
Cosine is sine shifted left by π/2
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Transformations: y = A sin(Bx - C) + D
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>A:</strong> Amplitude = |A| (vertical stretch/compression)
<br>
If A is negative, graph reflects over x-axis
<br><br>
<strong>B:</strong> Period = 2π/|B| (horizontal stretch/compression)
<br>
Larger B means shorter period (more cycles)
<br><br>
<strong>C:</strong> Phase shift = C/B (horizontal shift)
<br>
Positive C/B shifts right, negative shifts left
<br><br>
<strong>D:</strong> Vertical shift (moves midline up/down)
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> y = 3sin(2x - π) + 1
<br>
Amplitude = 3
<br>
Period = 2π/2 = π
<br>
Phase shift = π/2 (right)
<br>
Vertical shift = 1 (up)
<br>
Range: [1-3, 1+3] = [-2, 4]
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Parent Function: y = tan x
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Properties of y = tan x:</strong>
<br>
• Domain: all real numbers except π/2 + πn (where n is any integer)
<br>
• Range: all real numbers
<br>
• Period: π (not 2π!)
<br>
• No amplitude (unbounded)
<br>
• Vertical asymptotes at x = π/2 + πn
<br>
• Passes through origin (0, 0)
<br><br>
<strong>Key feature:</strong> Repeats every π radians
<br>
Increases from -∞ to +∞ between consecutive asymptotes
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 4: Trig Graphs
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    What is the period of the function y = sin(4x)?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> π/4</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> π/2</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> π</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> 2π</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> 4π</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Formula:</strong> For y = sin(Bx), period = 2π/B</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Here:</strong> B = 4</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">Period = 2π/4 = π/2</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Interpretation:</strong> The function completes 4 cycles in 2π (so one cycle in π/2)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: G</strong> — Larger B means shorter period!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>SOHCAHTOA: sin = opp/hyp, cos = adj/hyp, tan = opp/adj for right triangles
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Special triangles: 30-60-90 (1:√3:2) and 45-45-90 (1:1:√2) give exact trig values
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Radian conversion: 180° = π radians; multiply by π/180 or 180/π to convert
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Unit circle: point at angle θ has coordinates (cos θ, sin θ) on radius-1 circle
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>ASTC rule: QI=All positive, QII=Sine positive, QIII=Tangent positive, QIV=Cosine positive
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Pythagorean identity: sin²θ + cos²θ = 1, the most important trig identity
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Reciprocals: csc = 1/sin, sec = 1/cos, cot = 1/tan
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Sine and cosine have amplitude 1, period 2π, and range [-1, 1]
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For y = A sin(Bx - C) + D: amplitude |A|, period 2π/B, phase shift C/B, vertical shift D
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Tangent has period π (not 2π) and vertical asymptotes at odd multiples of π/2
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-16T01:11:48.005871+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (94e62367-ef7f-428e-acd6-fab733633a96, c3f9756e-dc45-42db-a6cf-658eea077f4d, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Ratios and proportions</strong> compare quantities and establish relationships between them. On the ACT, you''ll use <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ratios</strong> to compare parts, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">proportions</strong> to solve for unknowns, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">scale factors</strong> to work with similar figures, maps, and real-world applications.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Understanding Ratios
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Definition and Notation
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
A ratio compares two quantities. It can be written as a:b, a/b, or "a to b".
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Part-to-part ratio: Compares one part to another part</li>
<li>Part-to-whole ratio: Compares one part to the total</li>
<li>Ratios can be simplified like fractions</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> In a class of 30 students, 18 are girls and 12 are boys.
<br><br>
<strong>Girls to boys (part-to-part):</strong> 18:12 = 3:2
<br>
<strong>Girls to total (part-to-whole):</strong> 18:30 = 3:5
<br>
<strong>Boys to total (part-to-whole):</strong> 12:30 = 2:5
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Working with Ratio Parts
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
When a ratio is a:b, think of it as "a parts to b parts" of a total of (a + b) parts.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Divide $240 in the ratio 3:5.
<br><br>
<strong>Total parts:</strong> 3 + 5 = 8
<br>
<strong>Value of 1 part:</strong> 240 ÷ 8 = $30
<br><br>
<strong>First amount:</strong> 3 × 30 = $90
<br>
<strong>Second amount:</strong> 5 × 30 = $150
<br><br>
<strong>Check:</strong> 90 + 150 = 240 ✓ and 90:150 = 3:5 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Solving Proportions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
What is a Proportion?
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
A proportion states that two ratios are equal: a/b = c/d
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Cross-multiplication:</strong> If a/b = c/d, then ad = bc
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Solve for x: x/12 = 5/8
<br><br>
<strong>Cross-multiply:</strong>
<br>
8x = 12 × 5
<br>
8x = 60
<br>
x = 7.5
<br><br>
<strong>Check:</strong> 7.5/12 = 0.625 and 5/8 = 0.625 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Unit Rate Problems
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> If 5 pounds of apples cost $8, how much do 12 pounds cost?
<br><br>
<strong>Set up proportion:</strong> 5/8 = 12/x
<br><br>
<strong>Cross-multiply:</strong>
<br>
5x = 8 × 12
<br>
5x = 96
<br>
x = $19.20
<br><br>
<strong>Alternative (unit rate):</strong>
<br>
Cost per pound: 8 ÷ 5 = $1.60
<br>
12 pounds: 12 × 1.60 = $19.20
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Similar Figures and Scale
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Scale Factor
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Similar figures have the same shape but different sizes. The scale factor is the ratio of corresponding lengths.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Two similar triangles have corresponding sides of 6 cm and 15 cm. If another side of the smaller triangle is 8 cm, what is the corresponding side of the larger triangle?
<br><br>
<strong>Scale factor:</strong> 15/6 = 2.5
<br><br>
<strong>Corresponding side:</strong> 8 × 2.5 = 20 cm
<br><br>
<strong>Or use proportion:</strong> 6/15 = 8/x
<br>
6x = 120
<br>
x = 20 cm
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Area and Volume Ratios
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>If the scale factor is k:</strong>
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Lengths are in ratio k:1</li>
<li>Areas are in ratio k²:1</li>
<li>Volumes are in ratio k³:1</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Two similar rectangles have sides in ratio 2:3. If the smaller has area 20 cm², what is the area of the larger?
<br><br>
<strong>Scale factor:</strong> 3/2 = 1.5
<br>
<strong>Area factor:</strong> (1.5)² = 2.25
<br><br>
<strong>Larger area:</strong> 20 × 2.25 = 45 cm²
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Advanced Applications
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Three-Way Ratios
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Divide 180 in the ratio 2:3:4.
<br><br>
<strong>Total parts:</strong> 2 + 3 + 4 = 9
<br>
<strong>One part:</strong> 180 ÷ 9 = 20
<br><br>
<strong>First amount:</strong> 2 × 20 = 40
<br>
<strong>Second amount:</strong> 3 × 20 = 60
<br>
<strong>Third amount:</strong> 4 × 20 = 80
<br><br>
<strong>Check:</strong> 40 + 60 + 80 = 180 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Map Scales
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A map scale is 1:50,000. If two cities are 6 cm apart on the map, what is the actual distance in km?
<br><br>
<strong>Map distance:</strong> 6 cm
<br>
<strong>Actual distance:</strong> 6 × 50,000 = 300,000 cm
<br><br>
<strong>Convert to km:</strong> 300,000 cm = 3,000 m = 3 km
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0rem; font-weight: 400; visibility: hidden;">
Hidden Section Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 0rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.9;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Ratios compare quantities and can be simplified like fractions
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Part-to-part ratios compare parts; part-to-whole ratios compare to the total
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> For ratio a:b, total parts = a + b; find one part value by dividing total by (a + b)
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Proportions state two ratios are equal; solve using cross-multiplication
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> If a/b = c/d, then ad = bc (cross-multiplication rule)
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Scale factor k means lengths multiply by k, areas by k², volumes by k³
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Unit rate helps solve proportion problems by finding value per one unit
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> For three-way ratios a:b:c, total parts = a + b + c
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Map scales are ratios; multiply map distance by scale factor for actual distance
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Always check your answer makes sense in context
</li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-16T01:11:46.354719+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (579ce8b0-896f-4ac5-b7da-6e35ca26addd, c7b14c88-6559-4caa-87d1-311d271b9a78, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Math
Topic: Probability
Lesson Key: 6.3
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Understanding <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">probability</strong> is essential for success on the ACT Math section. This lesson covers <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">basic probability</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">compound events</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">conditional probability</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">independent events</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">expected value</strong>. Probability questions appear in 3-5 problems per test, making them a significant component of your math score. You''ll learn to calculate probabilities for simple and complex scenarios, understand how events relate to each other, and predict long-term outcomes using expected value calculations.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Basic Probability Concepts
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Probability</strong> measures the likelihood of an event occurring, expressed as a number between 0 and 1 (or 0% to 100%). The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">sample space</strong> includes all possible outcomes, while an <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">event</strong> is a specific outcome or set of outcomes. Understanding the fundamental probability formula and how to count favorable and total outcomes is the foundation for all probability problems.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Basic Probability Formula
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> P(Event) = (Number of favorable outcomes) / (Total number of possible outcomes)
<br><br>
<strong>Properties:</strong>
<br>
• 0 ≤ P(Event) ≤ 1
<br>
• P(impossible event) = 0
<br>
• P(certain event) = 1
<br>
• P(not A) = 1 - P(A)
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> What is the probability of rolling a 4 on a standard die?
<br><br>
<strong>Favorable outcomes:</strong> 1 (only the face showing 4)
<br>
<strong>Total outcomes:</strong> 6 (faces showing 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, or 6)
<br>
<strong>Probability:</strong> P(4) = 1/6 ≈ 0.167 or about 16.7%
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Probability with Cards, Coins, and Dice
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Standard deck of cards:</strong>
<br>
• 52 total cards
<br>
• 4 suits (hearts, diamonds, clubs, spades)
<br>
• 13 ranks per suit (A, 2-10, J, Q, K)
<br>
• 26 red cards, 26 black cards
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Probability of drawing a heart?
<br>
P(heart) = 13/52 = 1/4 = 0.25 or 25%
<br><br>
<strong>Coin flips:</strong>
<br>
P(heads) = 1/2
<br>
P(tails) = 1/2
<br><br>
<strong>Standard die:</strong>
<br>
P(any specific number) = 1/6
<br>
P(even number) = 3/6 = 1/2
<br>
P(number > 4) = 2/6 = 1/3
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Complementary Events
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The <strong>complement</strong> of an event A (written as A'' or "not A") includes all outcomes that are NOT in A.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> P(A'') = 1 - P(A)
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> If P(rain tomorrow) = 0.3, what is P(no rain tomorrow)?
<br><br>
P(no rain) = 1 - P(rain) = 1 - 0.3 = 0.7 or 70%
<br><br>
<strong>Why this is useful:</strong> Sometimes it''s easier to calculate the probability something doesn''t happen and subtract from 1.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Probability with Replacement vs. Without Replacement
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>With replacement:</strong> Item is returned before next selection (outcomes independent)
<br>
<strong>Without replacement:</strong> Item is not returned (outcomes dependent)
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Bag contains 3 red and 2 blue marbles
<br><br>
<strong>With replacement:</strong>
<br>
P(red on first draw) = 3/5
<br>
P(red on second draw) = 3/5 (same, because marble was replaced)
<br><br>
<strong>Without replacement:</strong>
<br>
P(red on first draw) = 3/5
<br>
P(red on second draw given red on first) = 2/4 = 1/2 (one red marble is gone)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 1: Basic Probability
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    A bag contains 5 red marbles, 3 blue marbles, and 7 green marbles. If one marble is selected at random, what is the probability it is NOT green?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> 3/15</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> 5/15</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> 7/15</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> 8/15</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> 12/15</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Method 1:</strong> Count non-green marbles directly</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">Non-green = red + blue = 5 + 3 = 8</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">Total = 5 + 3 + 7 = 15</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">P(not green) = 8/15</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Method 2:</strong> Use complement</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">P(green) = 7/15, so P(not green) = 1 - 7/15 = 8/15</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: D</strong> — Both methods work equally well!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Compound Events and the Multiplication Rule
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Compound events</strong> involve two or more simple events occurring together. For <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">independent events</strong> (where one outcome doesn''t affect another), we multiply probabilities. For <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">dependent events</strong> (where one outcome affects another), we adjust probabilities as we go. Understanding when to multiply versus when to add probabilities is crucial for solving complex probability problems.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Multiplication Rule for Independent Events
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>If events A and B are independent:</strong> P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B)
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> What is the probability of flipping heads twice in a row?
<br><br>
<strong>First flip:</strong> P(heads) = 1/2
<br>
<strong>Second flip:</strong> P(heads) = 1/2
<br>
<strong>Both heads:</strong> P(H and H) = 1/2 × 1/2 = 1/4 = 0.25 or 25%
<br><br>
The flips are independent because the first flip doesn''t affect the second.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Multiplication Rule for Dependent Events
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>For dependent events:</strong> P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B given A happened)
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A box has 4 red and 6 blue balls. Two balls are drawn without replacement. What is the probability both are red?
<br><br>
<strong>First draw:</strong> P(red) = 4/10 = 2/5
<br>
<strong>Second draw:</strong> P(red | first was red) = 3/9 = 1/3
<br>
(Only 3 red balls remain out of 9 total)
<br><br>
<strong>Both red:</strong> P(R and R) = 2/5 × 1/3 = 2/15 ≈ 0.133 or about 13.3%
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Addition Rule for Mutually Exclusive Events
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mutually exclusive events</strong> cannot happen at the same time. For these events:
<br>
P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B)
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> What is the probability of rolling a 2 or a 5 on a die?
<br><br>
P(2) = 1/6
<br>
P(5) = 1/6
<br>
P(2 or 5) = 1/6 + 1/6 = 2/6 = 1/3
<br><br>
These are mutually exclusive because you can''t roll both 2 and 5 on a single die roll.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Addition Rule for Non-Mutually Exclusive Events
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>When events can overlap:</strong> P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A and B)
<br>
We subtract P(A and B) to avoid counting the overlap twice.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> In a class of 30 students, 18 play soccer, 12 play basketball, and 6 play both. What is the probability a randomly selected student plays soccer or basketball?
<br><br>
P(soccer) = 18/30
<br>
P(basketball) = 12/30
<br>
P(both) = 6/30
<br><br>
P(soccer or basketball) = 18/30 + 12/30 - 6/30 = 24/30 = 4/5 = 0.8 or 80%
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 2: Compound Probability
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    A coin is flipped three times. What is the probability of getting exactly two heads?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> 1/8</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> 1/4</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> 3/8</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> 1/2</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> 5/8</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> List all possible outcomes with exactly 2 heads</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">HHT, HTH, THH (3 outcomes)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Each sequence has probability (1/2)³ = 1/8</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Total probability = 3 × (1/8) = 3/8</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: H</strong> — Count arrangements, multiply by each probability!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Conditional Probability
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Conditional probability</strong> measures the probability of an event occurring given that another event has already occurred. Written as <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">P(A|B)</strong> (read as "probability of A given B"), it represents how our knowledge of one event changes the probability of another. This concept is crucial for understanding dependent events and making predictions based on partial information. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Two-way tables</strong> are often used to organize conditional probability problems.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Conditional Probability Formula
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> P(A|B) = P(A and B) / P(B)
<br><br>
This tells us: "What fraction of times that B occurs does A also occur?"
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Two cards are drawn without replacement. What is the probability the second card is a heart given that the first card was a heart?
<br><br>
<strong>After first heart is drawn:</strong>
<br>
• 12 hearts remain (out of 13 original)
<br>
• 51 total cards remain (out of 52 original)
<br><br>
P(second is heart | first is heart) = 12/51 = 4/17
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Two-Way Tables
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Survey of 100 students
<br><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Own Car&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No Car&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Total
<br>
Junior&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;25&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;15&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;40
<br>
Senior&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;45&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;15&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;60
<br>
Total&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;70&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;30&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;100
<br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> What is P(owns car | senior)?
<br><br>
<strong>Solution:</strong> Look only at the senior row
<br>
45 seniors own cars out of 60 total seniors
<br>
P(owns car | senior) = 45/60 = 3/4 = 0.75 or 75%
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Testing for Independence
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Events A and B are independent if:</strong> P(A|B) = P(A)
<br>
In other words, knowing B occurred doesn''t change the probability of A.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Are flipping a coin and rolling a die independent?
<br><br>
P(heads) = 1/2
<br>
P(heads | rolled a 6) = 1/2
<br><br>
Since these are equal, the events are independent—rolling a die doesn''t affect the coin flip.
<br><br>
<strong>Counterexample:</strong> Drawing cards without replacement
<br>
P(second card is ace) = 4/52
<br>
P(second is ace | first was ace) = 3/51
<br><br>
Since these differ, the events are dependent.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Conditional Probability in Context
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Medical testing
<br><br>
A disease affects 1% of the population. A test is 95% accurate for those with the disease and 90% accurate for those without it. If someone tests positive, what''s the probability they actually have the disease?
<br><br>
<strong>This is asking:</strong> P(disease | positive test)
<br><br>
<strong>Setup:</strong> Out of 10,000 people:
<br>
• 100 have disease (1%)
<br>
• Of 100 with disease: 95 test positive (95% accuracy)
<br>
• 9,900 don''t have disease (99%)
<br>
• Of 9,900 without disease: 990 test positive (10% false positive rate)
<br><br>
<strong>Total positive tests:</strong> 95 + 990 = 1,085
<br>
<strong>True positives:</strong> 95
<br><br>
P(disease | positive) = 95/1,085 ≈ 8.8%
<br><br>
This surprisingly low probability shows the importance of base rates!
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 3: Conditional Probability
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    In a class, 60% of students are girls. Of the girls, 40% play sports. Of the boys, 70% play sports. If a randomly selected student plays sports, what is the probability the student is a girl?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> 24%</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> 40%</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> 46%</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> 52%</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> 60%</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Assume 100 students:</strong> 60 girls, 40 boys</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">Girls who play sports: 60 × 0.40 = 24</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">Boys who play sports: 40 × 0.70 = 28</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">Total athletes: 24 + 28 = 52</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">P(girl | plays sports) = 24/52 ≈ 46%</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: C</strong> — Use concrete numbers to organize the information!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Expected Value and Long-Run Probabilities
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Expected value</strong> represents the average outcome you''d expect over many trials. It''s calculated by multiplying each possible outcome by its probability and summing these products. Expected value is crucial for making decisions involving <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">risk and reward</strong>, analyzing games of chance, and predicting long-term results. Understanding expected value helps you determine whether a probabilistic situation is favorable or unfavorable over time.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Calculating Expected Value
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> E(X) = Σ [x × P(x)]
<br>
Sum of (each outcome × its probability)
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> You roll a die. You win $10 if you roll a 6, otherwise you win $0. What is the expected value?
<br><br>
<strong>Outcomes:</strong>
<br>
• Win $10 with probability 1/6
<br>
• Win $0 with probability 5/6
<br><br>
E(winnings) = 10 × (1/6) + 0 × (5/6) = 10/6 ≈ $1.67
<br><br>
<strong>Interpretation:</strong> On average, you''d expect to win about $1.67 per roll over many games.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Expected Value in Games and Gambling
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A raffle sells 100 tickets at $5 each. First prize is $300, second prize is $100. What is the expected value of buying one ticket?
<br><br>
<strong>Outcomes:</strong>
<br>
• Win $300 with probability 1/100 (net gain: $300 - $5 = $295)
<br>
• Win $100 with probability 1/100 (net gain: $100 - $5 = $95)
<br>
• Win $0 with probability 98/100 (net loss: -$5)
<br><br>
E(net gain) = 295 × (1/100) + 95 × (1/100) + (-5) × (98/100)
<br>
E(net gain) = 2.95 + 0.95 - 4.90 = -$1.00
<br><br>
<strong>Interpretation:</strong> On average, you lose $1 per ticket. This is not a favorable game!
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Fair Games vs. Unfair Games
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Fair game:</strong> Expected value = 0 (break even on average)
<br>
<strong>Favorable game:</strong> Expected value > 0 (gain on average)
<br>
<strong>Unfavorable game:</strong> Expected value < 0 (lose on average)
<br><br>
<strong>Example of fair game:</strong>
<br>
Flip a coin. Heads you win $10, tails you lose $10.
<br>
E(winnings) = 10 × (1/2) + (-10) × (1/2) = 5 - 5 = $0
<br><br>
<strong>To make this favorable:</strong> You''d need to win more than $10 on heads, or have better than 50% chance of winning.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Expected Value with Multiple Events
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> You flip a coin 100 times. What is the expected number of heads?
<br><br>
<strong>For each flip:</strong> E(heads) = 1 × (1/2) + 0 × (1/2) = 0.5
<br>
<strong>For 100 flips:</strong> E(total heads) = 100 × 0.5 = 50 heads
<br><br>
<strong>Property:</strong> E(aX + b) = aE(X) + b
<br>
This allows us to scale and shift expected values easily.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Decision Making with Expected Value
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> You can choose between two options:
<br>
<strong>Option A:</strong> Guaranteed $50
<br>
<strong>Option B:</strong> 40% chance of $100, 60% chance of $20
<br><br>
<strong>Expected value of A:</strong> $50 (certain)
<br>
<strong>Expected value of B:</strong> 100 × 0.4 + 20 × 0.6 = 40 + 12 = $52
<br><br>
<strong>Conclusion:</strong> Option B has slightly higher expected value, but Option A has no risk. The choice depends on your risk tolerance!
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 4: Expected Value
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    A spinner has 3 equal sections: one showing 5, one showing 10, and one showing 20. What is the expected value of one spin?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> 10</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> 11</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> 11⅔</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> 12</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> 15</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Each section has probability 1/3</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> E(spin) = 5×(1/3) + 10×(1/3) + 20×(1/3)</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> E(spin) = (5 + 10 + 20)/3 = 35/3 = 11⅔</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: H</strong> — Multiply each outcome by its probability!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Basic probability = (favorable outcomes) / (total outcomes), always between 0 and 1
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Complement rule: P(not A) = 1 - P(A), useful when it''s easier to calculate what doesn''t happen
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Independent events: P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B); outcome of one doesn''t affect the other
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Dependent events: adjust probabilities after each event (drawing without replacement)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Mutually exclusive events: P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B); can''t happen simultaneously
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Overlapping events: P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A and B) to avoid double-counting
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Conditional probability P(A|B) asks "what''s the probability of A in the world where B happened?"
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Two-way tables help organize conditional probability; focus on the relevant row or column
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Expected value = Σ(outcome × probability); represents long-run average
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Fair game has E(V) = 0; favorable has E(V) > 0; unfavorable has E(V) < 0
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-16T01:11:47.612303+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (3f6fc608-54c0-4124-aa29-3e47be64b3fa, caedee73-b99d-46fc-9202-9cfc40a2caf6, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Working with fractions</strong> efficiently requires mastering <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">arithmetic operations</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">simplification techniques</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">algebraic fraction manipulation</strong>. These skills appear in approximately 15% of ACT Math questions and are essential for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">rational expressions</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">proportion problems</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">complex calculations</strong>.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Simplifying and Comparing Fractions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Reducing Fractions to Lowest Terms
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
To simplify a fraction, divide both numerator and denominator by their <strong>greatest common factor (GCF)</strong>.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Simplify 24/36.
<br><br>
GCF of 24 and 36 is 12
<br>
24 ÷ 12 = 2
<br>
36 ÷ 12 = 3
<br>
Result: 2/3
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Simplify 45/75.
<br><br>
GCF is 15
<br>
45 ÷ 15 = 3
<br>
75 ÷ 15 = 5
<br>
Result: 3/5
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Converting Between Mixed Numbers and Improper Fractions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mixed number to improper fraction:</strong> Multiply the whole number by the denominator, add the numerator, place over the original denominator.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Improper fraction to mixed number:</strong> Divide numerator by denominator; quotient is the whole number, remainder is the new numerator.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Convert 3 2/5 to an improper fraction.
<br><br>
3 × 5 + 2 = 17
<br>
Result: 17/5
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Convert 23/4 to a mixed number.
<br><br>
23 ÷ 4 = 5 remainder 3
<br>
Result: 5 3/4
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Comparing Fractions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
To compare fractions with different denominators, find a common denominator or cross-multiply.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Which is larger: 3/4 or 5/7?
<br><br>
<strong>Method 1 (Common denominator):</strong>
<br>
LCD of 4 and 7 is 28
<br>
3/4 = 21/28
<br>
5/7 = 20/28
<br>
21/28 > 20/28, so 3/4 > 5/7
<br><br>
<strong>Method 2 (Cross-multiply):</strong>
<br>
3 × 7 = 21
<br>
5 × 4 = 20
<br>
21 > 20, so 3/4 > 5/7
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Equivalent Fractions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Equivalent fractions</strong> represent the same value. Create them by multiplying or dividing both numerator and denominator by the same nonzero number.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find three fractions equivalent to 2/3.
<br><br>
2/3 = 4/6 (multiply by 2/2)
<br>
2/3 = 6/9 (multiply by 3/3)
<br>
2/3 = 8/12 (multiply by 4/4)
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Adding and Subtracting Fractions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Same Denominator
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
When fractions have the same denominator, add or subtract the numerators and keep the denominator.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Examples:</strong>
<br>
3/7 + 2/7 = 5/7
<br>
5/8 - 1/8 = 4/8 = 1/2 (simplified)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Different Denominators
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Find the <strong>least common denominator (LCD)</strong>, convert both fractions, then add or subtract.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Calculate 1/4 + 2/3.
<br><br>
LCD of 4 and 3 is 12
<br>
1/4 = 3/12
<br>
2/3 = 8/12
<br>
3/12 + 8/12 = 11/12
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Calculate 5/6 - 1/4.
<br><br>
LCD of 6 and 4 is 12
<br>
5/6 = 10/12
<br>
1/4 = 3/12
<br>
10/12 - 3/12 = 7/12
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Adding Mixed Numbers
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Add the whole numbers separately, then add the fractions. If the fraction sum is improper, convert it.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Add 2 1/3 + 1 2/5.
<br><br>
Whole numbers: 2 + 1 = 3
<br>
Fractions: 1/3 + 2/5 = 5/15 + 6/15 = 11/15
<br>
Result: 3 11/15
<br><br>
<strong>Example with carrying:</strong> Add 3 3/4 + 2 5/8.
<br><br>
Whole numbers: 3 + 2 = 5
<br>
Fractions: 3/4 + 5/8 = 6/8 + 5/8 = 11/8 = 1 3/8
<br>
Result: 5 + 1 3/8 = 6 3/8
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Subtracting with Borrowing
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
When the first fraction is smaller, borrow 1 from the whole number.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Subtract 5 1/4 - 2 3/4.
<br><br>
Since 1/4 < 3/4, borrow 1 from 5
<br>
5 1/4 = 4 + 1 + 1/4 = 4 5/4
<br>
Now: 4 5/4 - 2 3/4 = 2 2/4 = 2 1/2
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Multiplying and Dividing Fractions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Multiplying Fractions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Multiply numerators together and denominators together, then simplify.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>a/b × c/d = (a × c)/(b × d)</strong>
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Multiply 2/3 × 4/5.
<br><br>
(2 × 4)/(3 × 5) = 8/15
<br><br>
<strong>Example with simplification:</strong> Multiply 3/8 × 4/9.
<br><br>
(3 × 4)/(8 × 9) = 12/72 = 1/6
<br><br>
<strong>Tip:</strong> Cancel before multiplying when possible:
<br>
3/8 × 4/9 = (3 × 4)/(8 × 9)
<br>
Cancel 3 and 9 (divide by 3): 1/(8) × 4/(3)
<br>
Cancel 4 and 8 (divide by 4): 1/(2) × 1/(3) = 1/6
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Dividing Fractions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
To divide by a fraction, multiply by its <strong>reciprocal</strong> (flip the second fraction).
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>a/b ÷ c/d = a/b × d/c</strong>
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Divide 2/3 ÷ 4/5.
<br><br>
2/3 × 5/4 = 10/12 = 5/6
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Divide 5/8 ÷ 3.
<br><br>
First write 3 as 3/1
<br>
5/8 ÷ 3/1 = 5/8 × 1/3 = 5/24
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Multiplying Mixed Numbers
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Convert mixed numbers to improper fractions first, then multiply.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Multiply 2 1/2 × 1 1/3.
<br><br>
Convert: 2 1/2 = 5/2 and 1 1/3 = 4/3
<br>
Multiply: 5/2 × 4/3 = 20/6 = 10/3 = 3 1/3
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Complex Fractions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
A <strong>complex fraction</strong> has a fraction in the numerator, denominator, or both. Simplify by treating the entire numerator divided by the entire denominator.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Simplify (2/3)/(4/5).
<br><br>
This means 2/3 ÷ 4/5
<br>
= 2/3 × 5/4 = 10/12 = 5/6
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Simplify (3 + 1/2)/(2 - 1/4).
<br><br>
Numerator: 3 + 1/2 = 7/2
<br>
Denominator: 2 - 1/4 = 7/4
<br>
(7/2)/(7/4) = 7/2 × 4/7 = 28/14 = 2
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Algebraic Fractions
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Simplifying Algebraic Fractions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Factor the numerator and denominator, then cancel common factors.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Simplify (6x²)/(9x).
<br><br>
= (6x · x)/(9x)
<br>
= (6x)/9 = 2x/3
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Simplify (x² - 4)/(x + 2).
<br><br>
Factor numerator: x² - 4 = (x + 2)(x - 2)
<br>
= (x + 2)(x - 2)/(x + 2)
<br>
= x - 2
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Adding Algebraic Fractions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Find a common denominator, just like with numeric fractions.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Add 1/x + 2/(3x).
<br><br>
LCD is 3x
<br>
1/x = 3/(3x)
<br>
3/(3x) + 2/(3x) = 5/(3x)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Multiplying and Dividing Algebraic Fractions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Use the same rules as numeric fractions.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Multiply (x/4) × (8/x²).
<br><br>
= (x × 8)/(4 × x²)
<br>
= 8x/(4x²)
<br>
= 2/x
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Common Mistakes and Tips
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 1: Adding denominators.</strong> When adding fractions, denominators don''t add: 1/4 + 1/4 = 2/4, not 2/8.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 2: Forgetting to flip when dividing.</strong> Division requires multiplying by the reciprocal.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 3: Canceling incorrectly.</strong> Can only cancel common factors, not common terms: (x + 2)/2 ≠ x + 1.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Tip 1: Always simplify your final answer.</strong>
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Tip 2: Convert mixed numbers to improper fractions before multiplying or dividing.</strong>
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Tip 3: Find the LCD systematically.</strong> List multiples of each denominator until you find the smallest common one.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0rem; font-weight: 400; visibility: hidden;">
Hidden Section Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 0rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.9;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Simplify fractions by dividing numerator and denominator by their GCF
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> To add/subtract fractions: find LCD, convert to equivalent fractions, then add/subtract numerators
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> To multiply fractions: multiply numerators together and denominators together, then simplify
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> To divide fractions: multiply by the reciprocal (flip the second fraction)
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Convert mixed numbers to improper fractions before multiplying or dividing
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> When adding mixed numbers, add whole numbers and fractions separately; carry if needed
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> For complex fractions, treat as division: numerator ÷ denominator
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> For algebraic fractions, factor completely before canceling common factors
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Can only cancel factors, not terms: (x + 2)/2 cannot be simplified by canceling the 2
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Always check if your final answer can be simplified further
</li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-16T01:11:43.634143+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (b9a54b78-d34e-48d4-ba37-f12ef24250f0, ccf1327b-50dc-4add-aa6a-c9c93fc7b39c, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Math
Topic: Areas, Volumes & Triangles
Lesson Key: 2.2
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Understanding <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">area</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">volume</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">surface area</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">triangle properties</strong> is essential for ACT Math success. These concepts appear in 8-12 questions per test—that''s nearly 20% of all math questions! This lesson will teach you the essential formulas, how to apply them quickly, and tricks to avoid common mistakes that cost students points.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Area Formulas for Common Shapes
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The ACT tests your ability to calculate <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">area</strong> for basic shapes. You must memorize these formulas—they are NOT provided on the test. The most common shapes tested are rectangles, triangles, circles, and trapezoids.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Rectangle and Square
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
For rectangles, use <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">A = length × width</strong>. For squares, since all sides are equal, use <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">A = s²</strong> where s is the side length. Remember: if you''re given the perimeter, divide by 4 for a square or by 2 and solve for individual sides for a rectangle.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Triangle
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The fundamental triangle formula is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">A = ½ × base × height</strong>. The height must be perpendicular to the base! Many students make the mistake of using a slant height instead. For right triangles, the two legs can serve as base and height since they''re already perpendicular.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Circle
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Circle area is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">A = πr²</strong> where r is the radius. If given the diameter, remember to divide by 2 to get the radius first. The ACT often leaves answers in terms of π, so don''t approximate unless specifically asked to do so.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Trapezoid
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A trapezoid has two parallel bases. The formula is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">A = ½(b₁ + b₂) × h</strong> where b₁ and b₂ are the parallel sides and h is the perpendicular height between them. Think of it as the average of the two bases, multiplied by the height.
</p>

<!-- Example 1 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Triangle Properties and Special Types
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Beyond calculating area, the ACT frequently tests special triangle properties. Understanding <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">right triangles</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">isosceles triangles</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">equilateral triangles</strong>, and the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Pythagorean theorem</strong> will help you solve problems quickly.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Right Triangles and Pythagorean Theorem
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
For any right triangle with legs a and b and hypotenuse c, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">a² + b² = c²</strong>. The ACT loves testing common Pythagorean triples: 3-4-5, 5-12-13, 8-15-17, and their multiples (6-8-10, 9-12-15, etc.). Recognizing these can save time instead of calculating from scratch.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Special Right Triangles: 45-45-90
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
In a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">45-45-90 triangle</strong>, the sides are in the ratio <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">x : x : x√2</strong>. If each leg has length x, the hypotenuse is x√2. This appears frequently when dealing with squares or when triangles are formed by diagonals.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Special Right Triangles: 30-60-90
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
In a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">30-60-90 triangle</strong>, the sides are in the ratio <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">x : x√3 : 2x</strong>. The shortest side (opposite the 30° angle) is x, the middle side (opposite 60°) is x√3, and the hypotenuse is 2x. These often appear in problems involving equilateral triangles.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Isosceles and Equilateral Triangles
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
An <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">isosceles triangle</strong> has two equal sides and two equal angles. An <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">equilateral triangle</strong> has all three sides equal and all angles equal to 60°. For equilateral triangles, if the side length is s, the area is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">A = (s²√3)/4</strong>.
</p>

<!-- Example 2 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Volume Formulas for 3D Shapes
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Volume</strong> measures the space inside a three-dimensional object. The ACT provides some volume formulas on the reference sheet, but you should memorize them anyway to save time during the test.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Rectangular Prism and Cube
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
For a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">rectangular prism</strong> (box), use <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">V = length × width × height</strong>. For a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">cube</strong> with side length s, use <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">V = s³</strong>. Remember that all edges of a cube are equal.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Cylinder
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">cylinder</strong> is like stacking circles. The formula is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">V = πr²h</strong> where r is the radius of the circular base and h is the height. Think of it as the area of the base (πr²) multiplied by how tall it is (h).
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Sphere
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The volume of a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">sphere</strong> is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">V = (4/3)πr³</strong>. Make sure you cube the radius (r³), not square it. This formula IS on the ACT reference sheet, but memorizing it speeds up your work.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Cone and Pyramid
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Both <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">cones</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">pyramids</strong> use the formula <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">V = (1/3) × base area × height</strong>. For a cone, the base is a circle, so V = (1/3)πr²h. For a pyramid, multiply by the area of the base shape (often a square or triangle).
</p>

<!-- Example 3 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Surface Area and Advanced Applications
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Surface area</strong> is the total area of all faces of a 3D shape. The ACT sometimes tests this concept, especially for rectangular prisms and cylinders. Understanding how to break down shapes into their faces makes these problems manageable.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Surface Area of Rectangular Prisms
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A rectangular prism has 6 faces. The formula is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">SA = 2lw + 2lh + 2wh</strong> where l, w, and h are length, width, and height. For a cube with side s, this simplifies to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">SA = 6s²</strong> since all faces are identical squares.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Surface Area of Cylinders
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A cylinder has two circular bases and one rectangular side (when "unrolled"). The formula is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">SA = 2πr² + 2πrh</strong>. The first term (2πr²) accounts for the top and bottom circles, and the second term (2πrh) is the lateral surface area.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Composite Shapes
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The ACT loves <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">composite shapes</strong>—shapes made by combining or subtracting basic shapes. The strategy is to break them into recognizable pieces, calculate each piece separately, then add or subtract as needed. For example, finding the area of a rectangular garden with a circular pond means calculating the rectangle''s area and subtracting the circle''s area.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Scale Factor and Area/Volume Relationships
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
If you scale a shape by a factor of k, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">area scales by k²</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">volume scales by k³</strong>. This is a powerful shortcut: if you double all dimensions of a box (k=2), the surface area increases by 4× and the volume increases by 8×.
</p>

<!-- Example 4 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Memorize all area and volume formulas—they''re NOT all on the reference sheet
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For triangles, always use perpendicular height, not slant height
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Recognize Pythagorean triples (3-4-5, 5-12-13) to save calculation time
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Know special right triangles: 45-45-90 (x:x:x√2) and 30-60-90 (x:x√3:2x)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For composite shapes, break into simple pieces, calculate separately, then combine
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>When dimensions scale by k, area scales by k² and volume scales by k³
  </li>
</ul>
', 1, '2025-10-16T06:12:18.584762+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (8e1f57da-9781-4e76-848d-bb43934f8026, cd6bed23-9114-4579-8a4e-1c134eb00a71, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Understanding lines and linear equations</strong> is essential for success on the ACT Math section, requiring mastery of <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">slope calculations</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">equation forms</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">graphing techniques</strong>. These concepts appear in approximately 12% of ACT Math questions and connect to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">coordinate geometry</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">systems of equations</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">function analysis</strong>.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Slope and Rate of Change
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Calculating Slope from Two Points
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The <strong>slope</strong> of a line measures its steepness and direction. Given two points (x₁, y₁) and (x₂, y₂), the slope formula is:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>m = (y₂ - y₁)/(x₂ - x₁)</strong>
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
This formula represents "rise over run"—the vertical change divided by the horizontal change.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find the slope of the line passing through (2, 5) and (8, 17).
<br><br>
m = (17 - 5)/(8 - 2) = 12/6 = 2
<br><br>
<strong>Interpretation:</strong> For every 1 unit you move right, the line rises 2 units.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Positive, Negative, Zero, and Undefined Slopes
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The sign and value of slope tell you about a line''s behavior:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Positive slope (m > 0):</strong> Line rises from left to right. As x increases, y increases.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Negative slope (m < 0):</strong> Line falls from left to right. As x increases, y decreases.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Zero slope (m = 0):</strong> Horizontal line. y-value never changes, regardless of x.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Undefined slope:</strong> Vertical line. x-value never changes; division by zero in slope formula.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Examples:</strong>
<br>
Points (3, 4) and (7, 10): m = (10-4)/(7-3) = 6/4 = 3/2 (positive slope)
<br>
Points (1, 8) and (5, 2): m = (2-8)/(5-1) = -6/4 = -3/2 (negative slope)
<br>
Points (2, 6) and (9, 6): m = (6-6)/(9-2) = 0/7 = 0 (horizontal line)
<br>
Points (4, 3) and (4, 9): m = (9-3)/(4-4) = 6/0 = undefined (vertical line)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Slope as Rate of Change
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
In word problems, slope represents <strong>rate of change</strong>. The units of slope are (units of y)/(units of x).
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A car travels 150 miles in 3 hours and 270 miles in 6 hours. What is the rate of change (speed)?
<br><br>
Points: (3, 150) and (6, 270) where x = hours and y = miles
<br>
m = (270 - 150)/(6 - 3) = 120/3 = 40 miles per hour
<br><br>
<strong>Interpretation:</strong> The car travels at 40 mph.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Parallel and Perpendicular Lines
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Parallel lines</strong> have the same slope: If line 1 has slope m₁ and line 2 has slope m₂, then lines are parallel when m₁ = m₂.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Perpendicular lines</strong> have slopes that are negative reciprocals: If m₁ × m₂ = -1, the lines are perpendicular.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A line has slope 2/3. What is the slope of a line parallel to it? Perpendicular to it?
<br><br>
<strong>Parallel slope:</strong> 2/3 (same slope)
<br>
<strong>Perpendicular slope:</strong> -3/2 (negative reciprocal)
<br><br>
<strong>Verification:</strong> (2/3) × (-3/2) = -6/6 = -1 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Equation Forms of Lines
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Slope-Intercept Form
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>y = mx + b</strong>
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
This is the most common form. Here, <strong>m</strong> is the slope and <strong>b</strong> is the y-intercept (where the line crosses the y-axis).
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Write the equation of a line with slope 3 and y-intercept 5.
<br><br>
y = 3x + 5
<br><br>
<strong>Reading from the equation:</strong> m = 3, b = 5
<br>
The line crosses the y-axis at (0, 5) and rises 3 units for every 1 unit right.
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Point-Slope Form
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>y - y₁ = m(x - x₁)</strong>
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Use this form when you know the slope m and a point (x₁, y₁) on the line. It''s especially useful for writing equations quickly.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Write the equation of a line with slope -2 passing through (3, 7).
<br><br>
y - 7 = -2(x - 3)
<br><br>
<strong>Converting to slope-intercept form:</strong>
<br>
y - 7 = -2x + 6
<br>
y = -2x + 13
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Standard Form
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Ax + By = C</strong>
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
In standard form, A, B, and C are integers, and typically A is positive. This form is useful for finding intercepts quickly.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
To find intercepts from standard form:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>x-intercept:</strong> Set y = 0 and solve for x</li>
<li><strong>y-intercept:</strong> Set x = 0 and solve for y</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find the intercepts of 3x + 4y = 12.
<br><br>
<strong>x-intercept:</strong> Set y = 0
<br>
3x + 4(0) = 12 → 3x = 12 → x = 4
<br>
Point: (4, 0)
<br><br>
<strong>y-intercept:</strong> Set x = 0
<br>
3(0) + 4y = 12 → 4y = 12 → y = 3
<br>
Point: (0, 3)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Converting Between Forms
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
You should be comfortable converting between all three forms:
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Convert 2x + 3y = 15 to slope-intercept form.
<br><br>
3y = -2x + 15
<br>
y = (-2/3)x + 5
<br><br>
<strong>Reading the equation:</strong> slope = -2/3, y-intercept = 5
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Graphing Lines
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Graphing from Slope-Intercept Form
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Given y = mx + b:
</p>

<ol style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Plot the y-intercept at (0, b)</li>
<li>Use the slope m to find a second point: move "rise" units up/down and "run" units right</li>
<li>Draw a line through the two points</li>
</ol>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Graph y = (3/4)x - 2.
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Plot y-intercept at (0, -2)
<br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Slope = 3/4 means rise 3, run 4
<br>
From (0, -2), move up 3 and right 4 to get (4, 1)
<br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Draw line through (0, -2) and (4, 1)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Graphing from Two Points
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
If you''re given two points:
</p>

<ol style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li>Plot both points on the coordinate plane</li>
<li>Draw a straight line connecting them</li>
<li>Extend the line in both directions</li>
</ol>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
If you need the equation, first calculate the slope, then use point-slope form with either point.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Graphing Horizontal and Vertical Lines
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Horizontal lines:</strong> Form y = k (where k is a constant). All points have the same y-coordinate.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Vertical lines:</strong> Form x = h (where h is a constant). All points have the same x-coordinate.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Examples:</strong>
<br>
y = 3 is a horizontal line through (0, 3), parallel to the x-axis
<br>
x = -2 is a vertical line through (-2, 0), parallel to the y-axis
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Reading Information from Graphs
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
When given a graph of a line, you can determine:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>y-intercept:</strong> Where the line crosses the y-axis</li>
<li><strong>x-intercept:</strong> Where the line crosses the x-axis</li>
<li><strong>Slope:</strong> Pick two clear points and use the slope formula</li>
<li><strong>Direction:</strong> Positive slope rises left to right; negative slope falls</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A line passes through (0, 4) and (2, 8). What is its equation?
<br><br>
y-intercept: b = 4
<br>
Slope: m = (8 - 4)/(2 - 0) = 4/2 = 2
<br>
Equation: y = 2x + 4
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Applications and Problem-Solving
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Writing Equations from Word Problems
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Many ACT problems describe a linear relationship in words. Look for:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>Initial value:</strong> This is the y-intercept (b)</li>
<li><strong>Rate of change:</strong> This is the slope (m)</li>
<li><strong>Variable relationships:</strong> Identify what x and y represent</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> A phone plan costs $25 per month plus $0.10 per text message. Write an equation for total cost C based on number of texts t.
<br><br>
Initial value (monthly fee): b = 25
<br>
Rate of change (per text): m = 0.10
<br>
Equation: C = 0.10t + 25
<br><br>
<strong>Interpretation:</strong> With 100 texts, C = 0.10(100) + 25 = $35
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Finding Where Lines Intersect
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The intersection point of two lines satisfies both equations simultaneously. This is a system of equations (covered more in Unit 4).
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Where do y = 2x + 1 and y = -x + 7 intersect?
<br><br>
Set the equations equal:
<br>
2x + 1 = -x + 7
<br>
3x = 6
<br>
x = 2
<br><br>
Substitute back: y = 2(2) + 1 = 5
<br>
Intersection point: (2, 5)
<br><br>
<strong>Verification:</strong> Check in second equation: y = -(2) + 7 = 5 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Distance and Midpoint on Lines
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Distance formula</strong> between points (x₁, y₁) and (x₂, y₂):
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>d = √[(x₂ - x₁)² + (y₂ - y₁)²]</strong>
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Midpoint formula:</strong>
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>M = ((x₁ + x₂)/2, (y₁ + y₂)/2)</strong>
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find the distance and midpoint between (1, 2) and (7, 10).
<br><br>
<strong>Distance:</strong>
<br>
d = √[(7-1)² + (10-2)²] = √[36 + 64] = √100 = 10
<br><br>
<strong>Midpoint:</strong>
<br>
M = ((1+7)/2, (2+10)/2) = (8/2, 12/2) = (4, 6)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Linear Inequalities
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Linear inequalities like y > 2x + 3 represent regions on the coordinate plane:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>Solid line:</strong> Use for ≤ or ≥ (points on the line are included)</li>
<li><strong>Dashed line:</strong> Use for < or > (points on the line are excluded)</li>
<li><strong>Shading:</strong> Shade above the line for y > or y ≥; below for y < or y ≤</li>
</ul>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Graph y ≤ -x + 4.
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Graph y = -x + 4 with a solid line (because of ≤)
<br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Shade below the line (y is less than or equal to)
<br>
<strong>Test point:</strong> Check (0, 0): Is 0 ≤ 4? Yes, so (0, 0) should be in the shaded region ✓
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Common Mistakes and Tips
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 1: Calculating slope incorrectly.</strong> Always use (y₂ - y₁)/(x₂ - x₁), not (x₂ - x₁)/(y₂ - y₁).
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 2: Confusing slope and y-intercept.</strong> In y = mx + b, m is slope and b is y-intercept.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 3: Forgetting negative reciprocals for perpendicular lines.</strong> If slope is 3, perpendicular slope is -1/3, not -3.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Tip 1: Use point-slope form for quick equation writing.</strong> It saves time when you know a point and the slope.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Tip 2: Check your answer.</strong> Plug one of the given points into your equation to verify.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Tip 3: Memorize special cases.</strong> Horizontal lines: y = k, slope = 0. Vertical lines: x = h, slope = undefined.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0rem; font-weight: 400; visibility: hidden;">
Hidden Section Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 0rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.9;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Slope = (y₂ - y₁)/(x₂ - x₁) measures steepness; positive slopes rise, negative slopes fall
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Parallel lines have equal slopes; perpendicular lines have slopes that are negative reciprocals (m₁ × m₂ = -1)
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Slope-intercept form y = mx + b shows slope m and y-intercept b directly
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Point-slope form y - y₁ = m(x - x₁) is fastest when you know a point and slope
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Standard form Ax + By = C makes finding x and y intercepts easy
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Horizontal lines have equation y = k and slope 0; vertical lines have equation x = h and undefined slope
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> To graph from slope-intercept form: plot y-intercept, use slope to find second point, draw line
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Distance formula: d = √[(x₂-x₁)² + (y₂-y₁)²]; Midpoint: ((x₁+x₂)/2, (y₁+y₂)/2)
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> In word problems, initial value is y-intercept and rate of change is slope
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Two lines intersect where their equations are simultaneously true—solve the system to find the point
</li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-16T01:15:38.834185+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (0a860181-7b46-49d6-b220-155d1308dad5, ce1a39a3-0f96-434f-ab56-97743f9e77b9, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Reading
Topic: 7 Most Common Types of Questions
Lesson Key: question-types
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The ACT Reading section tests comprehension through seven distinct question types, each requiring specific strategies and skills: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Main Idea questions</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Detail questions</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Inference questions</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Vocabulary-in-Context questions</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Function and Purpose questions</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Author''s Attitude and Tone questions</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Comparison questions</strong>. Understanding these question types helps you quickly identify what each question asks, apply appropriate strategies, and avoid common traps specific to each type. This lesson provides comprehensive coverage of all seven question types, explaining their characteristics, offering targeted strategies for each, and teaching you how to recognize and efficiently answer every question type you''ll encounter on test day.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Main Idea and Detail Questions
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Main Idea questions</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Detail questions</strong> together comprise approximately 55-60% of all Reading questions, making them the most common question types. While both test your understanding of passage content, they differ significantly in scope and approach.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Main Idea Questions: Understanding the Big Picture
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Main Idea questions ask about the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">overall purpose</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">primary theme</strong>, or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">central argument</strong> of the entire passage or a significant portion. Common question stems include: "The main idea of the passage is...", "The primary purpose of this passage is to...", "Which of the following best describes the passage as a whole?", "The passage can best be described as...", or "The author''s main point is that..." To answer these questions, you need holistic comprehension—understanding not just individual paragraphs but how they work together to convey an overall message. The correct answer will be broad enough to encompass the entire passage but specific enough to capture its unique focus. Wrong answers are typically too narrow (focusing on one paragraph''s content rather than the whole passage), too broad (so general they could describe any passage on the topic), or distorted (misrepresenting the passage''s emphasis or purpose).
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Strategies for Main Idea Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
To tackle Main Idea questions effectively: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read the introduction and conclusion carefully</strong>—passages often state their main idea explicitly in these sections. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Track the topic</strong> as you read—what subject appears in every paragraph? That''s likely central to the main idea. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify the author''s purpose</strong>—are they explaining something, arguing for a position, telling a story, or analyzing a phenomenon? The main idea should reflect this purpose. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Eliminate answers</strong> that focus on supporting details, examples, or tangents rather than the central point. If you''re unsure, ask yourself: "If I had to explain this passage in one sentence, what would I say?" Your answer should align with the correct choice. Some students find it helpful to answer Main Idea questions last, after detail questions have forced them to reread and reinforce their understanding of the passage''s content and structure.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Detail Questions: Finding Specific Information
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Detail questions ask about <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">specific facts</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">events</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">statements</strong>, or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">examples</strong> explicitly mentioned in the passage. They often include line references or paragraph references to guide you. Common question stems include: "According to the passage...", "The passage states that...", "The author indicates that...", "Which of the following is mentioned in the passage?", or "In lines 34-38, the author describes..." Detail questions test whether you can locate and accurately understand specific information. Unlike Main Idea questions that require big-picture thinking, Detail questions reward careful, focused reading of particular sections. The correct answer will closely paraphrase what the passage says, while wrong answers often distort the passage''s information, confuse similar-sounding details, or bring in plausible but unsupported claims.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Strategies for Detail Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
For Detail questions: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use line references</strong> to locate the relevant section quickly—read the referenced lines plus 1-2 sentences before and after for context. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read carefully</strong>—detail questions often hinge on small distinctions, so pay attention to exact wording. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Match answer choices</strong> to the passage text—the correct answer should align closely in meaning even if the wording differs. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Eliminate choices</strong> that introduce information not mentioned in the passage or that contradict what the passage says. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Watch for distortions</strong>—wrong answers might use vocabulary from the passage but twist its meaning. Never answer detail questions from memory alone; always verify against the passage. Even if you think you remember the detail clearly, check it—memory can be unreliable under time pressure.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Main Idea vs. Detail Question</strong><br><br>
<strong>Main Idea Question:</strong> "The primary purpose of the passage is to..."<br>
Correct answer: "explain how a scientific discovery changed medical treatment" (captures overall focus of entire passage)<br>
Wrong answer: "describe the structure of antibiotics" (too narrow—just one paragraph''s content)<br><br>
<strong>Detail Question:</strong> "According to lines 23-25, the scientist''s initial experiment..."<br>
Correct answer: "produced unexpected results that contradicted previous findings" (accurately paraphrases those lines)<br>
Wrong answer: "definitively proved the new theory" (distortion—passage says results were "suggestive" not "definitive")
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Inference and Vocabulary-in-Context Questions
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Inference questions</strong> require you to read between the lines and draw logical conclusions based on what the passage implies, while <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Vocabulary-in-Context questions</strong> test whether you understand how specific words function within the passage''s meaning. Together, these make up approximately 25-30% of Reading questions.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Inference Questions: Reading Between the Lines
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Inference questions ask you to draw <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">logical conclusions</strong> from information the passage suggests but doesn''t explicitly state. Question stems include: "The passage suggests that...", "It can reasonably be inferred that...", "The author implies that...", "Based on the passage, one can conclude that...", or "Which of the following statements is most strongly supported by the passage?" These questions test critical thinking—your ability to combine multiple pieces of information, recognize implications, and identify what must be true based on what the passage says. However, "inference" doesn''t mean "wild speculation." Correct inferences are <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">strongly supported</strong> by textual evidence even if not stated outright. Wrong answers often make logical leaps too far from what the passage actually supports or confuse reasonable possibilities with what the passage actually suggests.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Strategies for Inference Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
To answer Inference questions effectively: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Locate relevant evidence</strong>—even though the answer isn''t stated directly, it will be based on specific passage sections. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for clues</strong> in descriptive language, comparisons, contrasts, cause-effect relationships, or the author''s tone. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Stay close to the text</strong>—the correct inference should require only one small logical step from what''s stated, not a huge imaginative leap. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Eliminate extreme answers</strong>—inferences using "always," "never," or "must" are usually wrong unless the passage strongly supports such certainty. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Test each answer</strong>—ask "Does the passage actually support this conclusion, or am I bringing in outside assumptions?" For difficult inference questions, work backwards: consider what evidence would support each answer choice, then check if that evidence exists in the passage.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Vocabulary-in-Context Questions: Word Meaning in Passage
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Vocabulary-in-Context questions test your understanding of how a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">specific word</strong> is used within the passage, not your knowledge of the word''s dictionary definition in isolation. Question stems typically follow this format: "As it is used in line X, the word ''Y'' most nearly means..." The word tested might be relatively simple (like "run" or "charged") but used in an unusual way, or it might be a more sophisticated term whose meaning becomes clear from context. The key is that you must determine the word''s meaning <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">as used in this specific passage</strong>, not its general meaning. Wrong answers often include other definitions of the word that don''t fit the passage''s context, synonyms that are close but not quite right, or words that sound similar but have different meanings.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Strategies for Vocabulary-in-Context Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
For Vocabulary questions: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read the sentence containing the word</strong> plus the sentences before and after to understand context fully. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Substitute answer choices</strong> into the sentence—which one preserves the sentence''s meaning and sounds natural? <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Ignore other meanings</strong> you know the word can have—focus only on how it works in this passage. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for context clues</strong> like synonyms, antonyms, examples, or explanations in surrounding sentences. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Eliminate answers</strong> that don''t make sense in the sentence''s context. A helpful technique: cover the word in the passage and predict what word should go there based on context, then find the answer choice closest to your prediction. Don''t overthink these questions—the correct answer should feel natural when substituted into the sentence.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Inference vs. Vocabulary Question</strong><br><br>
Passage: "Though the experiment yielded promising preliminary results, Dr. Martinez cautioned against drawing definitive conclusions until additional trials could be conducted with larger sample sizes."<br><br>
<strong>Inference Question:</strong> "The passage suggests that Dr. Martinez believes..."<br>
Correct answer: "further research is needed to confirm the findings" (logical inference from "cautioned against definitive conclusions" and "additional trials")<br>
Wrong answer: "the experiment was a complete failure" (goes too far—passage says results were "promising")<br><br>
<strong>Vocabulary Question:</strong> "As used in line 42, ''yielded'' most nearly means..."<br>
Correct answer: "produced" (fits context: experiment produced results)<br>
Wrong answer: "surrendered" (another meaning of yield, but doesn''t fit this context)
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Function/Purpose and Author''s Attitude Questions
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Function and Purpose questions</strong> ask why the author included specific content or how it serves the passage''s overall goals, while <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Author''s Attitude and Tone questions</strong> test your ability to identify the author''s perspective, feelings, or stance on the topic. These question types test sophisticated reading skills beyond basic comprehension.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Function and Purpose Questions: Understanding "Why"
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Function and Purpose questions ask about the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">rhetorical purpose</strong> of specific paragraphs, examples, quotations, or sections. Common stems include: "The primary function of the third paragraph is to...", "The author most likely includes the description of X in order to...", "The example in lines 45-50 primarily serves to...", or "The author discusses Y mainly to..." These questions test whether you understand not just what the passage says but <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">why the author chose to include specific content</strong>. Authors include information to support arguments, provide examples, offer contrasts, explain background, transition between ideas, or illustrate concepts. The correct answer will identify the strategic purpose of the content in relation to the passage''s overall argument or narrative. Wrong answers might accurately describe what the content is about without explaining its function, or misidentify the role it plays in the passage''s structure.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Strategies for Function and Purpose Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
To answer these questions: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read before and after</strong> the referenced section—purpose often becomes clear from how content connects to surrounding paragraphs. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Ask "why"</strong>—why would the author include this example, description, or detail? What does it add to the argument or narrative? <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify relationships</strong>—does the content provide evidence, contrast an idea, explain background, transition topics, or illustrate a point? <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Match purpose to structure</strong>—if a paragraph presents a problem then a solution, its purpose is likely to show how something was resolved. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Eliminate "what" answers</strong>—choices that only describe the content without explaining its function are usually wrong. Think about the passage as a deliberate construction where every part serves a specific architectural purpose in building the author''s overall message.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Author''s Attitude and Tone Questions: Reading the Author''s Perspective
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
These questions ask you to identify the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">author''s feelings</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">perspective</strong>, or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">stance</strong> toward the subject. Question stems include: "The author''s tone in discussing X can best be described as...", "The author''s attitude toward Y is primarily one of...", "The author views Z as...", or "The author would most likely describe the subject as..." Tone might be objective, enthusiastic, critical, admiring, skeptical, concerned, nostalgic, analytical, or neutral. These questions test your ability to detect <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">subtle clues</strong> about the author''s stance through word choice, descriptive language, and rhetorical techniques. The correct answer will be supported by specific language in the passage, while wrong answers often are too extreme (describing the tone as "outraged" when it''s merely "concerned") or misread neutral analysis as emotional response.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Strategies for Author''s Attitude Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
For these questions: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for emotionally loaded words</strong>—adjectives like "remarkable," "unfortunate," "brilliant," or "problematic" reveal the author''s stance. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Notice what the author emphasizes</strong>—spending extensive time praising something suggests admiration; focusing on limitations suggests skepticism. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Distinguish fact from opinion</strong>—factual, balanced presentation suggests objective tone; evaluative language suggests a subjective stance. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check for consistency</strong>—the author''s tone should be relatively consistent throughout unless there''s a clear shift. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Eliminate extremes</strong>—unless the passage uses very strong language, avoid tone words like "hostile," "ecstatic," or "contemptuous." Most ACT passages have moderate, measured tones even when the author clearly favors one side of an issue.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Function vs. Tone Question</strong><br><br>
Passage includes a paragraph describing how a painter''s early struggles with poverty shaped his later work''s themes of social inequality.<br><br>
<strong>Function Question:</strong> "The primary function of paragraph 3 is to..."<br>
Correct answer: "explain how personal experience influenced the artist''s thematic choices" (identifies the rhetorical purpose)<br>
Wrong answer: "describe the artist''s childhood" (what it does, not why—this misses the function)<br><br>
<strong>Tone Question:</strong> "The author''s attitude toward the artist can best be described as..."<br>
Passage uses words like "admirably persevered," "profound empathy," "remarkable insight"<br>
Correct answer: "respectful and appreciative" (matches the positive language)<br>
Wrong answer: "neutral and objective" (misses the clear admiration in the descriptive language)
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Comparison Questions and Question Type Integration
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Comparison questions</strong> appear when passages include dual texts or when questions ask you to compare elements within a single passage. Understanding how to integrate your knowledge of all question types creates a comprehensive approach to the Reading section.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Comparison Questions: Analyzing Relationships
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Comparison questions ask you to identify <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">similarities</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">differences</strong>, or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">relationships</strong> between two passages, two perspectives within a passage, or two elements discussed in the passage. Common stems include: "Both passages suggest that...", "Unlike Passage A, Passage B emphasizes...", "The two authors would most likely agree about...", "How does the author''s view of X differ from their view of Y?", or "Compared to the description of A, the description of B is more..." These questions test your ability to hold multiple perspectives in mind simultaneously and analyze their relationships. The correct answer will accurately characterize the nature of the similarity or difference, while wrong answers often overstate agreement, exaggerate differences, or misidentify which passage holds which view.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Strategies for Comparison Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
To tackle comparison questions: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Create a mental comparison chart</strong>—note what each passage or element says about the topic being compared. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for explicit contrasts</strong>—passages often use transition words like "however," "in contrast," or "unlike" to signal differences. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify areas of overlap</strong>—where both passages discuss the same subtopic, how do their perspectives differ? <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Be precise</strong>—the correct answer will accurately reflect the specific nature of the similarity or difference, not just that one exists. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check both passages</strong>—verify that the answer accurately represents what each passage says, not just one. For dual passage questions, annotate Passage A with "A" and Passage B with "B" to avoid confusion when questions reference specific passages.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Recognizing Question Types Quickly
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Developing the ability to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">instantly identify question types</strong> saves valuable time and helps you apply appropriate strategies automatically. Create mental associations: "main idea" or "primary purpose" → think big picture, entire passage. "According to" or line references → detail question, locate and verify. "Suggests" or "implies" → inference question, read between lines carefully. "As used in line" → vocabulary question, substitute and check context. "Function of" or "primarily serves to" → purpose question, ask why the author included it. "Tone" or "attitude" → look for emotionally loaded language. "Both passages" or "compared to" → comparison question, analyze relationships. With practice, this recognition becomes instantaneous, allowing you to transition immediately into the appropriate strategy without wasting time figuring out what the question asks.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Practicing Question Type Identification
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
To build question type recognition skills: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Create flashcards</strong> with question stems on one side and the question type plus key strategy on the other. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Practice categorizing</strong> questions from official practice tests before answering them—this builds recognition speed. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Track your performance</strong> by question type to identify which types give you the most trouble, then focus practice there. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Time yourself</strong> on each question type separately to understand where you need to speed up. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Review explanations</strong> for wrong answers to see if you misidentified the question type or used the wrong strategy. Many students find that their accuracy improves dramatically simply by recognizing question types correctly and applying type-specific strategies, even if their overall reading ability hasn''t changed. This strategic approach to question types is one of the highest-leverage ways to improve your Reading score.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Quick Question Type Recognition</strong><br><br>
<strong>Question 1:</strong> "The main idea of the passage is..." → Main Idea (think big picture, eliminate too-narrow answers)<br><br>
<strong>Question 2:</strong> "According to lines 23-25..." → Detail (locate lines, verify exact meaning, match to choices)<br><br>
<strong>Question 3:</strong> "The passage suggests that..." → Inference (read between lines, stay close to text, avoid wild leaps)<br><br>
<strong>Question 4:</strong> "As used in line 42, ''promising'' most nearly means..." → Vocabulary (substitute choices, check context)<br><br>
<strong>Question 5:</strong> "The primary function of paragraph 3 is to..." → Function/Purpose (ask why included, identify role)<br><br>
<strong>Question 6:</strong> "The author''s attitude toward the subject is..." → Tone (look for loaded language, check consistency)<br><br>
<strong>Question 7:</strong> "Both passages agree that..." → Comparison (check both passages, identify overlap)<br><br>
By instantly recognizing each type, you apply the right strategy immediately.
</p>
</div>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Main Idea questions ask about overall purpose or theme—eliminate answers that are too narrow or too broad
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Detail questions ask about specific facts—always verify your answer against the passage, never rely solely on memory
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Inference questions require reading between the lines, but correct inferences stay close to what the passage supports
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Vocabulary-in-Context questions test word meaning in the passage—substitute answer choices to see what fits
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Function and Purpose questions ask why the author included content—identify the rhetorical role it plays
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Author''s Attitude questions test tone and perspective—look for emotionally loaded language and evaluative terms
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Comparison questions ask about similarities or differences—verify the answer accurately represents both elements
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Learn to identify question types instantly by recognizing key words in question stems
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Each question type requires specific strategies—apply the appropriate technique based on what''s being asked
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Track your performance by question type during practice to identify weaknesses and focus improvement efforts
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T18:09:19.214163+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (c50531ea-0cb1-4151-b2e4-a0270a915169, d01719a5-ef05-41c3-aac8-0766044fe327, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Science
Topic: Cannot Be Determined Questions
Lesson Key: cannot-be-determined
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Cannot-be-determined questions test your ability to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">recognize when data is insufficient</strong> to answer a question, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">identify what information is missing</strong> from figures or passages, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">distinguish between answerable and unanswerable questions</strong> based on given data, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">avoid making assumptions beyond what the data supports</strong>. Unlike standard questions where you extract specific values or identify trends from available data, these questions specifically assess whether you understand the limitations of the provided information and can recognize when extrapolation, assumptions, or additional data would be required. This lesson teaches you how to identify when "cannot be determined" is the correct answer, explains common scenarios where data is insufficient despite appearing complete, provides strategies for distinguishing between difficult-to-find information and genuinely missing information, and shows you how to avoid incorrectly selecting "cannot be determined" when the answer is actually present in the figures or passage.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Understanding When Information Is Genuinely Missing
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Cannot-be-determined scenarios</strong> occur when the data provided is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">legitimately insufficient</strong> to answer the question, regardless of how carefully you analyze the figures or passage.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Scenario 1: Data Outside the Measured Range
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The most common <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">cannot-be-determined scenario</strong> involves questions asking about values outside what was actually measured: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Example</strong>: A graph shows data from 0-100°C. Question asks: "What would the pressure be at 150°C?" Since 150°C is beyond the measured range and you don''t know if the trend continues linearly, exponentially, or changes direction entirely, you cannot determine the answer from the given data. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Why it''s undeterminable</strong>: Extrapolation beyond measured data requires assumptions about how trends continue, which may or may not be valid. Without additional information confirming the trend continues, you cannot definitively answer. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Key distinction</strong>: Questions asking for reasonable estimates within a small extension of the range may be answerable ("Based on the trend, which is most likely at 110°C?"), but questions far outside the range or asking for exact values beyond the data cannot be determined. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Red flags</strong>: Questions mentioning values clearly outside all measured ranges, asking about conditions not tested, or requesting information about experimental setups not described.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Scenario 2: Variables Not Measured or Reported
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Questions asking about <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">variables that weren''t measured</strong> cannot be answered: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Example</strong>: Passage describes measuring temperature and pressure but doesn''t mention volume. Question asks: "What was the volume at t=30 min?" Since volume was never measured or reported, you cannot determine it. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Subtle variations</strong>: Sometimes a variable is mentioned in the passage but data for it isn''t provided in figures. The passage might say "Students also noted the color" but no figure shows color data. Questions about color cannot be answered. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Indirect measurement questions</strong>: "What was the pH?" when only temperature and pressure are graphed, and no formula or relationship is provided to calculate pH from those variables. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">How to verify</strong>: Check all figures and tables. If the variable mentioned in the question doesn''t appear in any axis label, column header, or data row, it likely cannot be determined.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Scenario 3: Ambiguous or Unlabeled Data
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">data exists but isn''t clearly identified</strong>, determination may be impossible: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Example</strong>: A graph shows three unlabeled lines. Passage mentions Trial 1, 2, and 3 but doesn''t specify which line corresponds to which trial, and there''s no way to deduce it from the data patterns. Question asks: "What was the temperature in Trial 2 at t=20?" You can''t answer because you don''t know which line is Trial 2. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Missing legends or keys</strong>: Symbols, colors, or abbreviations used in figures without explanation and not defined in the passage. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check carefully</strong>: Before concluding data is ambiguous, thoroughly check figure captions, legends, passage text, and pattern clues. Sometimes the identification is subtle but present. Only if truly no identification exists is it undeterminable. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ACT typically provides identifiable data</strong>, so this scenario is rarer than the others, but it''s worth recognizing.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Scenario 4: Questions Requiring Unknown Intermediate Steps
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Some questions cannot be answered because they require <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">information or calculations for which necessary data is missing</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Example</strong>: Question asks "What was the density?" but the data only provides mass, not volume (and density = mass/volume). Without volume, you cannot calculate density. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Missing formulas or constants</strong>: "Calculate the energy" when energy formula isn''t provided and data doesn''t directly show energy values. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Missing conversion factors</strong>: Data in one unit, question asks for answer in different unit, but conversion factor isn''t provided. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Important note</strong>: Basic scientific formulas and common conversions are sometimes assumed knowledge (like °F to °C conversion), but obscure or complex calculations requiring specific constants won''t be required without data. If the question seems to require advanced calculations with missing components, "cannot be determined" is likely correct.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Genuinely Missing Information</strong><br><br>
<strong>Scenario 1 (Outside Range):</strong><br>
Data provided: Temperature measured from 0-100°C, pressure values from 1-5 atm<br>
Question: "What would pressure be at 200°C?"<br>
Analysis: 200°C is far outside the measured range (0-100°C)<br>
Conclusion: Cannot be determined—would require assumptions about trend continuation<br><br>
<strong>Scenario 2 (Variable Not Measured):</strong><br>
Data provided: Figure 1 shows temperature vs time, Figure 2 shows pressure vs time<br>
Question: "What was the volume at t=30 min?"<br>
Analysis: Volume never measured or reported anywhere in passage or figures<br>
Conclusion: Cannot be determined—volume data doesn''t exist<br><br>
<strong>Scenario 3 (Ambiguous Data):</strong><br>
Data provided: Three unlabeled lines on a graph<br>
Passage: Mentions Trial A, B, C but doesn''t specify which line is which<br>
Question: "What was the value for Trial B at t=20?"<br>
Analysis: Can''t identify which line corresponds to Trial B<br>
Conclusion: Cannot be determined—line identification missing<br><br>
<strong>Scenario 4 (Missing Intermediate Data):</strong><br>
Data provided: Mass values for different samples<br>
Question: "What was the density of Sample 1?"<br>
Analysis: Density = mass/volume, but only mass is provided, not volume<br>
Conclusion: Cannot be determined—missing volume data needed for calculation
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Distinguishing "Cannot Be Determined" from "Difficult to Find"
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A critical skill is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">distinguishing between information that''s genuinely absent</strong> versus information that''s present but requires careful search or analysis to find.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Before Selecting "Cannot Be Determined," Exhaust All Sources
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Before concluding information is missing, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">systematically check every possible source</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">All figures and tables</strong>: Check every graph, table, and diagram. The information might be in a figure you didn''t initially think relevant. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Figure captions and notes</strong>: Read small print, footnotes, and captions carefully. Critical information is sometimes tucked in these locations. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Passage text</strong>: Scan the passage for keywords from the question. Information might be stated in text rather than shown in figures. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Answer choices</strong>: Sometimes answer choices provide clues. If three choices give specific values and one says "cannot be determined," check whether those specific values actually appear in the data. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Only after thoroughly checking all sources</strong> should you conclude the information is missing. Many students prematurely select "cannot be determined" when the information is actually present but requires more careful searching.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Information That Requires Integration or Calculation
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Some questions require <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">combining data from multiple sources</strong> or performing calculations—this doesn''t mean it can''t be determined: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Multi-figure integration</strong>: If Figure 1 shows temperature at different times and Figure 2 shows pressure at different times, you CAN determine temperature and pressure at the same time by cross-referencing—it''s not "cannot be determined" just because you need both figures. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Simple calculations</strong>: If data provides initial and final values and the question asks for the change, you CAN calculate change by subtraction—this is determinable. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Using provided formulas</strong>: If the passage provides a formula and all variables in that formula have values in the data, you CAN calculate the result—it''s determinable. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Don''t confuse "complex" with "undeterminable."</strong> If the information exists (even if finding it requires multiple steps), it CAN be determined. Only select "cannot be determined" when data is genuinely absent, not when the solution is multi-step.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Information That Can Be Inferred or Deduced
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Sometimes information isn''t directly stated but can be <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reasonably inferred</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Pattern deduction</strong>: If Figure 1 shows that Trial 1 always has the highest values across all measurements, and the question asks which trial had the highest value at a specific point, you can infer Trial 1 even if that exact point isn''t explicitly labeled. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Logical elimination</strong>: If the passage says three trials were run (A, B, C) and two are clearly identified in a figure, the unlabeled third line must be the remaining trial. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Interpolation</strong>: Values between measured points can be reasonably estimated by interpolation—this is determinable, not "cannot be determined." (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Boundary</strong>: Reasonable inference is acceptable. Wild speculation is not. If inference requires multiple assumptions or logical leaps, it may genuinely be undeterminable. But straightforward deductions from available data don''t qualify as "cannot be determined."
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Common Student Errors Leading to False "Cannot Be Determined"
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Students sometimes <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">incorrectly select "cannot be determined"</strong> when: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">They didn''t search carefully enough</strong>. The information is present but in a different figure or in passage text, not where they expected. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">They gave up too quickly</strong>. The question is challenging or requires multiple steps, so they assume it''s unanswerable rather than working through it. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">They confused unfamiliarity with impossibility</strong>. The question asks about a concept or variable they don''t understand, so they think it can''t be answered, when actually the data is there. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">They misread what''s being asked</strong>. They looked for the wrong variable or checked the wrong conditions. To avoid these errors: Always do a thorough, systematic search before selecting "cannot be determined." Treat it as a last resort, not a first response to difficulty. If you''re considering "cannot be determined," ask yourself: "Have I checked every figure? Every table? The passage text? Figure captions?" Only if the answer is yes and you still haven''t found the information should you select it.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Distinguishing Difficult from Impossible</strong><br><br>
<strong>Difficult but CAN Be Determined:</strong><br>
Question: "What was the temperature when pressure was 2.5 atm?"<br>
Figure 1: Shows temperature vs time<br>
Figure 2: Shows pressure vs time<br>
Process: Find t when P=2.5 atm in Figure 2 (say t=25 min), then find temperature at t=25 in Figure 1<br>
Conclusion: CAN be determined—requires two-figure integration but data exists<br><br>
<strong>Appears Difficult but CAN Be Determined:</strong><br>
Question: "What was the increase in volume from t=10 to t=30?"<br>
Table shows: V=20 mL at t=10, V=45 mL at t=30<br>
Process: Calculate 45-20=25 mL<br>
Conclusion: CAN be determined—simple calculation from available data<br><br>
<strong>Actually CANNOT Be Determined:</strong><br>
Question: "What was the pH at t=30 min?"<br>
Figures show: Temperature vs time, pressure vs time<br>
Passage: Never mentions pH or provides any relationship between pH and the measured variables<br>
Process: Check all figures—pH not shown. Check passage—pH not mentioned. No way to derive it.<br>
Conclusion: CANNOT be determined—pH data genuinely absent<br><br>
The key difference: In the first two, all necessary data exists and can be found or calculated. In the third, the data simply doesn''t exist anywhere.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Strategic Approaches for "Cannot Be Determined" Questions
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Systematic strategies</strong> help you accurately identify when "cannot be determined" is correct versus when the answer is present but challenging to find.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Systematic Elimination Checklist
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When facing a question where you''re struggling to find information, use this <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">checklist</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Identify exactly what the question asks</strong>. What variable? At what condition? (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check Figure 1</strong>: Does it show this variable or provide data to calculate it? (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check Figure 2, Figure 3, etc.</strong>: Systematically check each figure. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check any tables</strong>: Look for the variable in column or row headers. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Read passage text</strong>: Scan for keywords related to the question. The information might be stated in words rather than shown in data. (6) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check if it can be calculated</strong>: Do you have all components needed for a calculation or formula? (7) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Check if it can be inferred</strong>: Can you deduce it from patterns or elimination? (8) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Only if all checks fail</strong>, select "cannot be determined." This systematic approach ensures you don''t miss information that''s present but not where you expected.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Recognizing "Cannot Be Determined" Answer Choice Patterns
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ACT answer choices provide clues</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If three choices are specific values</strong> (20, 40, 60) and one is "cannot be determined," check whether those specific values actually appear in or can be derived from the data. If they can, "cannot be determined" is likely wrong. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If "cannot be determined" is an option</strong>, the question is testing whether you recognize data limitations. Be extra careful to verify whether information is truly missing. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ACT doesn''t frequently use "cannot be determined"</strong> as correct answers—most questions are designed to be answerable from the data. Don''t assume it''s correct just because a question seems hard. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">When it IS correct</strong>, it''s usually clearly correct—the data is obviously missing, not subtly absent. If you''re debating whether information is available, it probably is available and you just haven''t found it yet. Use the presence of "cannot be determined" as a signal to search extra carefully, not as an easy way out of a difficult question.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Time Management Strategy for These Questions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Balance thoroughness with efficiency</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Spend 30-45 seconds searching</strong> before considering "cannot be determined." Check all major sources systematically. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If after thorough search you haven''t found the information</strong>, assess whether the data genuinely seems missing. If the variable isn''t in any figure, isn''t mentioned in the passage, and doesn''t appear derivable, it probably is undeterminable. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Don''t waste 2+ minutes</strong> desperately searching for information that may not exist. If systematic searching for 45 seconds reveals no information and the data genuinely appears absent, select "cannot be determined" and move on. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Mark for review if unsure</strong>. If you''re truly uncertain whether information is missing or just hard to find, mark the question and return to it if time permits. Fresh eyes on the second pass might spot information you missed initially. Balance between thoroughness (don''t give up too easily) and efficiency (don''t waste excessive time on a question designed to test recognition of missing data).
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Practicing Recognition of Data Limitations
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Developing skill with these questions requires <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">practice recognizing limitations</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">When reviewing practice passages</strong>, after answering normal questions, ask yourself: "What questions COULDN''T be answered from this data? What variables weren''t measured? What ranges weren''t covered?" (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Develop awareness of data boundaries</strong>: What''s the minimum and maximum x-value? What variables are shown versus not shown? What relationships are demonstrated versus assumed? (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Compare passages that provide complete data versus those with gaps</strong>. Notice the difference between comprehensive experiments and limited studies. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Build confidence</strong> in distinguishing "I can''t find it" from "it''s not there." This skill improves with practice and reduces anxiety when encountering these questions on test day. The goal is developing intuition for what data supports and what it doesn''t.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Strategic Approach</strong><br><br>
<strong>Question:</strong> "What was the conductivity of Solution A at 50°C?"<br><br>
<strong>Systematic Checklist:</strong><br>
✓ Figure 1: Shows temperature vs volume for Solutions A, B, C → No conductivity<br>
✓ Figure 2: Shows pH vs time for Solutions A, B, C → No conductivity<br>
✓ Table 1: Shows initial concentrations of A, B, C → No conductivity<br>
✓ Passage text: Scan for "conductivity" → Not mentioned anywhere<br>
✓ Can it be calculated? No formula relating conductivity to measured variables<br>
✓ Can it be inferred? No patterns or relationships suggest conductivity values<br><br>
<strong>Conclusion:</strong> After systematic check, conductivity was never measured or discussed<br>
<strong>Answer:</strong> Cannot be determined<br>
<strong>Time spent:</strong> 40 seconds (efficient, systematic search)<br><br>
<strong>Contrast with:</strong><br>
Question: "What was the volume of Solution A at 50°C?"<br>
Systematic check: Figure 1 shows temperature vs volume → Find 50°C on x-axis, trace to Solution A line, read volume from y-axis → CAN be determined<br><br>
The difference: Volume data exists and is findable. Conductivity data genuinely doesn''t exist anywhere. Systematic checking reveals which scenario applies.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Traps and Advanced Considerations
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Understanding subtle traps</strong> and advanced scenarios helps you navigate these questions with greater accuracy and confidence.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Trap #1: Confusing "Not Directly Shown" with "Cannot Be Determined"
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Many students think if information isn''t <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">directly visible in a single figure</strong>, it cannot be determined: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Example trap</strong>: "What was the ratio of Variable A to Variable B at t=20?" Figure 1 shows Variable A, Figure 2 shows Variable B. Students think "I don''t see a ratio anywhere" and select "cannot be determined." But you CAN determine it by reading A from Figure 1, reading B from Figure 2, and calculating A/B. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Avoiding the trap</strong>: If all components needed for an answer are available (even if in different places or requiring calculation), it CAN be determined. Only select "cannot be determined" if one or more necessary components are truly absent. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Mental shift</strong>: Think of data as building blocks. If you have all the blocks needed to construct the answer (even if assembly required), it''s determinable. Only if a block is missing is it undeterminable. Don''t confuse "requires work" with "impossible."
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Trap #2: Assuming Extrapolation Equals "Cannot Be Determined"
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Not all extrapolation is undeterminable</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Small, reasonable extrapolation</strong>: If data goes from 0-100 and the question asks about 110 "based on the trend," you can reasonably extend the line slightly and estimate. This is determinable as an approximation. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Large or extreme extrapolation</strong>: If data goes from 0-100 and the question asks about 500, this is too far beyond the measured range for reasonable prediction. This likely cannot be determined. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Question wording matters</strong>: "Based on the trend, which value would most likely..." suggests approximation is acceptable (determinable). "What exactly would the value be..." for far extrapolation suggests impossibility (cannot be determined). (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use judgment</strong>: Small extensions of clear trends with "most likely" language are usually determinable. Large extensions or questions asking for precision beyond the data range are usually undeterminable. Context and question wording guide which applies.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Advanced Scenario: Partial Information That''s Insufficient
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Sometimes <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">some information is present but not enough</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Example</strong>: Question asks "What was the final temperature of the mixture?" Passage says two liquids were mixed, one at 20°C and one at 40°C, but doesn''t provide volumes, masses, or heat capacities. You know initial temperatures but can''t calculate final temperature without additional data. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Another example</strong>: Data shows several data points, but the question asks which mathematical model (linear, exponential, logarithmic) best fits, yet not enough data points are provided to distinguish between models statistically. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Recognition</strong>: You have some relevant information but not all necessary information. It''s tempting to guess or make assumptions, but if key data is missing, it cannot be determined. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Test skill</strong>: These scenarios test whether you recognize what information is sufficient versus insufficient for answering a question.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
When to Trust Your Instinct vs. Keep Searching
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Developing <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">good judgment</strong> about when to conclude "cannot be determined": (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Trust your instinct if</strong>: After systematic searching, the variable isn''t mentioned anywhere, isn''t in any figure axis or table header, and you''ve checked all sources thoroughly. If it''s obviously absent, trust that assessment. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Keep searching if</strong>: The question seems very straightforward for a passage that otherwise provides detailed data. If the passage is comprehensive and only this one piece seems missing, double-check—it might be there in an unexpected location. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Context clues</strong>: If the passage is clearly incomplete or limited (described as a "preliminary study" or "partial data"), missing information is more likely. If the passage describes a thorough experiment, comprehensive data is more likely. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Balance</strong>: Don''t be so determined to find information that you waste time searching for data that truly isn''t there. But also don''t give up so easily that you select "cannot be determined" when the information is present but requires effort to find. Experience and practice develop this balanced judgment.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Avoiding Traps</strong><br><br>
<strong>Trap 1 - "Not Directly Shown" ≠ "Cannot Be Determined":</strong><br>
Question: "What was the change in temperature from t=10 to t=30?"<br>
Student thinking: "I don''t see ''change'' anywhere in the figures"<br>
Wrong: Selects "cannot be determined"<br>
Correct approach: Figure shows T=45°C at t=10, T=70°C at t=30<br>
Calculate: 70-45=25°C change<br>
Answer: 25°C (CAN be determined through simple calculation)<br><br>
<strong>Trap 2 - Extrapolation:</strong><br>
Data range: 0-100°C<br>
Question 1: "Based on the trend, which value would most likely occur at 110°C: 15, 20, 25, 30?"<br>
Answer: Determinable—small extrapolation with "most likely" language and answer choices to guide<br>
Question 2: "What would the exact value be at 500°C?"<br>
Answer: Cannot be determined—far outside range, asking for exact value<br><br>
<strong>Partial Information:</strong><br>
Question: "What was the density of the mixture?"<br>
Data provided: Mass of component A, mass of component B<br>
Data missing: Volumes (density = mass/volume)<br>
Analysis: Have masses but not volumes needed for density calculation<br>
Answer: Cannot be determined—insufficient data for required calculation<br><br>
These examples show the nuances between genuinely missing data and data that requires some work to find or derive.
</p>
</div>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Select "cannot be determined" only when data is genuinely missing, not when it''s difficult to find
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Common undeterminable scenarios: values outside measured range, variables never measured, missing calculation components
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Before selecting "cannot be determined," systematically check all figures, tables, captions, and passage text
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Information requiring multi-figure integration or simple calculations CAN be determined if all components exist
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Values that can be reasonably inferred, deduced, or interpolated CAN be determined
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Don''t confuse "complex" or "multi-step" with "undeterminable"—difficulty doesn''t equal impossibility
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>ACT rarely uses "cannot be determined" as correct answers—treat it as a last resort after thorough searching
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Small, reasonable extrapolations with "most likely" language are usually determinable; large extrapolations often aren''t
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Spend 30-45 seconds on systematic searching before concluding data is missing
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>When "cannot be determined" IS correct, it''s usually obviously correct—the data absence is clear, not subtle
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T18:09:19.214163+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (4f17f226-7a3a-411b-91cf-bda4ad76c641, d05b44a9-77a8-4b3e-8b42-9276c8aff115, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Science
Topic: Equations as Answers
Lesson Key: equations-as-answers
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Equations-as-answers questions test your ability to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">translate scientific relationships into mathematical form</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">identify which equation correctly represents observed data patterns</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">distinguish between direct and inverse proportionality</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">recognize how variables relate algebraically</strong> based on experimental results. These questions present data in tables or graphs and ask you to select which equation best models the relationship between variables. This lesson teaches you systematic techniques for analyzing data patterns, explains how to test equations against data points, provides strategies for identifying mathematical relationships from trends, and shows you how to eliminate incorrect equations by checking specific values or understanding the form of different relationship types.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Understanding Common Scientific Relationship Types
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Before testing equations against data, you need to recognize the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">common types of mathematical relationships</strong> that appear in science and understand their <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">characteristic patterns</strong>.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Direct Proportionality (Linear Through Origin)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Direct proportionality</strong> means two variables are related by y = kx where k is a constant: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Characteristic pattern</strong>: When x doubles, y doubles. When x triples, y triples. The ratio y/x is constant for all data points. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Equation form</strong>: y = kx (or variations like F = ma, d = vt). The equation is linear with no constant term. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Graph appearance</strong>: A straight line passing through the origin (0,0). (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Testing method</strong>: Calculate y/x for several data points. If the ratio is constant, the relationship is directly proportional, and k equals that constant ratio. For example, if a table shows x values of 2, 4, 6 with corresponding y values of 10, 20, 30, calculate 10/2 = 5, 20/4 = 5, 30/6 = 5. The constant ratio confirms y = 5x. Direct proportionality is common in physics (force and acceleration, distance and time at constant speed) and chemistry (concentration and absorbance in spectroscopy). The key identifier is that doubling the input doubles the output.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Inverse Proportionality (Reciprocal Relationship)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Inverse proportionality</strong> means y = k/x where k is a constant: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Characteristic pattern</strong>: When x doubles, y is halved. When x triples, y becomes one-third. The product x·y is constant for all data points. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Equation form</strong>: y = k/x (or variations like P = nRT/V, λ = c/f). The independent variable appears in the denominator. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Graph appearance</strong>: A hyperbolic curve that approaches but never reaches the axes. As x increases, y decreases but never becomes zero. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Testing method</strong>: Calculate x·y for several data points. If the product is constant, the relationship is inversely proportional, and k equals that constant product. For example, if x values of 2, 4, 8 correspond to y values of 12, 6, 3, calculate 2×12 = 24, 4×6 = 24, 8×3 = 24. The constant product confirms y = 24/x. Inverse relationships are common in gas laws (pressure and volume), wave physics (frequency and wavelength), and optics (distance and intensity). The key identifier is that increasing the input decreases the output in a specific reciprocal way.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Quadratic Relationships (Square Proportionality)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Quadratic relationships</strong> involve one variable being proportional to the square of another: y = kx²: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Characteristic pattern</strong>: When x doubles, y quadruples (increases by factor of 4). When x triples, y increases nine-fold. The ratio y/x² is constant. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Equation form</strong>: y = kx² (or variations like KE = ½mv², A = πr²). The independent variable is squared. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Graph appearance</strong>: A parabola. The curve increases more steeply as x increases, showing accelerating growth. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Testing method</strong>: Calculate y/x² for several data points. If this ratio is constant, the relationship is quadratic, and k equals that constant. For example, if x values of 2, 3, 4 correspond to y values of 8, 18, 32, calculate 8/4 = 2, 18/9 = 2, 32/16 = 2. The constant ratio confirms y = 2x². Quadratic relationships appear in kinetic energy (proportional to velocity squared), gravitational force at large distances, area calculations, and projectile motion. The key identifier is that doubling the input quadruples the output.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Linear with Y-Intercept (Non-Proportional Linear)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Linear relationships with y-intercepts</strong> follow y = mx + b where m is the slope and b is the y-intercept: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Characteristic pattern</strong>: Equal increases in x produce equal increases in y, but the relationship doesn''t pass through the origin. When x = 0, y = b (not zero). (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Equation form</strong>: y = mx + b. The presence of the constant term b means it''s linear but not proportional. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Graph appearance</strong>: A straight line that intersects the y-axis above or below the origin. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Testing method</strong>: Calculate the change in y divided by change in x (slope) between data points. If this ratio is constant but y/x is not constant (because b ≠ 0), the relationship is linear with an intercept. For example, if (x,y) pairs are (0,5), (2,9), (4,13), the slope is (9-5)/(2-0) = 2 and the y-intercept is 5, giving y = 2x + 5. These relationships appear when there''s a baseline value (b) plus a variable component (mx)—for example, rental costs with a flat fee plus per-day charges, or temperature conversions between scales. The key identifier is constant change rate but non-zero starting value.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Identifying Relationship Types</strong><br><br>
<strong>Data Set 1:</strong> x: 1, 2, 3, 4 → y: 7, 14, 21, 28<br>
Test: y/x = 7/1=7, 14/2=7, 21/3=7, 28/4=7 (constant)<br>
Relationship: Direct proportion y = 7x<br><br>
<strong>Data Set 2:</strong> x: 2, 4, 6, 8 → y: 12, 6, 4, 3<br>
Test: x·y = 2×12=24, 4×6=24, 6×4=24, 8×3=24 (constant)<br>
Relationship: Inverse proportion y = 24/x<br><br>
<strong>Data Set 3:</strong> x: 1, 2, 3, 4 → y: 3, 12, 27, 48<br>
Test: y/x² = 3/1=3, 12/4=3, 27/9=3, 48/16=3 (constant)<br>
Relationship: Quadratic y = 3x²<br><br>
<strong>Data Set 4:</strong> x: 0, 1, 2, 3 → y: 5, 8, 11, 14<br>
Test: Slope = (8-5)/(1-0) = 3, y-intercept = 5<br>
Relationship: Linear with intercept y = 3x + 5
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Systematic Approach to Testing Equations Against Data
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Once you understand relationship types, you need a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">systematic method</strong> for testing which equation correctly represents the data when given answer choices.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Substitution Testing Method
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The most reliable method is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">direct substitution</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Select one or two data points from the table or graph</strong>. Choose points with simple values to make calculation easier. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">For each answer choice equation, substitute the x-value</strong> and calculate what y-value the equation predicts. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Compare the predicted y to the actual y from the data</strong>. If they match, the equation is consistent with that data point. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Eliminate answer choices that don''t match</strong>. If an equation fails even one data point, it''s incorrect. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Test remaining equations with a second data point</strong> if needed to confirm or eliminate. For example, given data (2, 6) and (3, 9) and answer choices y = 3x, y = x², y = 2x + 2, test with x = 2: First equation: 3(2) = 6 ✓; Second equation: 2² = 4 ✗; Third equation: 2(2) + 2 = 6 ✓. Test remaining with x = 3: First equation: 3(3) = 9 ✓; Third equation: 2(3) + 2 = 8 ✗. The correct answer is y = 3x. This method is foolproof if done carefully.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Using Extreme or Special Values for Quick Elimination
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Strategic value selection</strong> can speed elimination: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Test x = 0 if available</strong>. This immediately reveals the y-intercept. If data shows (0, 0), eliminate equations with non-zero constants. If data shows (0, b), eliminate equations without that constant. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Test x = 1 if available</strong>. When x = 1, equations simplify: y = kx becomes y = k, y = kx² becomes y = k, y = k/x becomes y = k. This helps identify the constant quickly. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use the largest or smallest values</strong> to magnify differences between equations. Equations that look similar for small x-values may differ dramatically for large x-values. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for easy numbers</strong> where calculations are simple. If data includes (4, 16), test whether y = x² works immediately. For example, if data includes point (0, 3) and answer choices are y = 2x, y = 2x + 3, y = x² + 3, testing x = 0 immediately eliminates the first two (they give y = 0) and confirms the third (y = 3). Using strategic values reduces calculation time significantly.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Checking Trend Direction and Behavior
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Before detailed testing, quickly check if equations match the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">qualitative trend</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Increasing or decreasing</strong>: Does y increase as x increases (positive relationship) or decrease (negative relationship)? Eliminate equations with the wrong trend direction. For example, if data clearly shows y increasing with x, eliminate y = -2x or y = 12/x. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Rate of change</strong>: Does y increase linearly (constant rate), faster than linearly (accelerating, suggesting x² or exponential), or slower than linearly (decelerating, suggesting square root or logarithm)? Match equation form to trend curvature. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Approaching limits</strong>: Does y approach zero as x increases (suggesting y = k/x), or does y grow without bound (suggesting x² or exponential)? (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Sign considerations</strong>: Are all y-values positive? If so, eliminate equations that could produce negative outputs for the given x range. This qualitative screening eliminates wrong answers immediately, before you calculate anything, making the remaining substitution testing faster.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Dealing with Proportionality Constants
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Many equations have <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">constants</strong> that you need to determine: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If answer choices include the constant</strong>, test which constant value fits the data. For example, if choices are y = 2x, y = 3x, y = 4x, calculate y/x from data to identify the correct constant. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If answer choices show only variable relationships</strong> (like "y is proportional to x²"), determine the relationship type without worrying about the specific constant. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Use simple data points to find constants</strong>. If you know the relationship is y = kx², use a simple point like (2, 12) to solve: 12 = k(2²) → 12 = 4k → k = 3. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Verify the constant with other data points</strong>. Calculate the constant from one point, then check that it works for other points to confirm the equation. For example, if you determine k = 5 from one point in y = 5x, verify that k = 5 works for at least one other point. Constants are determined by the specific data, so finding them correctly is essential for choosing or verifying equations.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Testing Equations Systematically</strong><br><br>
<strong>Data provided:</strong> (1, 4), (2, 7), (3, 10), (4, 13)<br>
<strong>Answer choices:</strong><br>
A) y = 4x<br>
B) y = 3x + 1<br>
C) y = x² + 3<br>
D) y = 16/x<br><br>
<strong>Step 1 - Qualitative check:</strong> y increases as x increases (eliminates nothing, all could be increasing)<br><br>
<strong>Step 2 - Test with x=1:</strong><br>
A) y = 4(1) = 4 ✓<br>
B) y = 3(1) + 1 = 4 ✓<br>
C) y = 1² + 3 = 4 ✓<br>
D) y = 16/1 = 16 ✗ (should be 4, eliminate D)<br><br>
<strong>Step 3 - Test remaining with x=2:</strong><br>
A) y = 4(2) = 8 ✗ (should be 7, eliminate A)<br>
B) y = 3(2) + 1 = 7 ✓<br>
C) y = 2² + 3 = 7 ✓<br><br>
<strong>Step 4 - Test remaining with x=3:</strong><br>
B) y = 3(3) + 1 = 10 ✓<br>
C) y = 3² + 3 = 12 ✗ (should be 10, eliminate C)<br><br>
<strong>Answer: B) y = 3x + 1</strong><br>
Verification: Check x=4: 3(4) + 1 = 13 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Recognizing Equations from Graphical Patterns
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When data is presented in <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">graph form</strong> rather than tables, you need to identify equations by recognizing <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">characteristic curve shapes</strong>.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Identifying Linear Relationships from Straight-Line Graphs
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Straight-line graphs</strong> indicate linear relationships: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If the line passes through (0,0)</strong>, the equation is y = mx where m is the slope. Calculate slope using rise/run between any two points. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">If the line has a y-intercept b ≠ 0</strong>, the equation is y = mx + b. Read b from where the line crosses the y-axis. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Positive slope</strong> (line rises left to right) means positive m; negative slope (line falls left to right) means negative m. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Steep lines</strong> have large |m|; gentle lines have small |m|. For example, if a line passes through (0, 0) and (4, 12), the slope is 12/4 = 3, giving y = 3x. If a line passes through (0, 5) and (2, 11), the slope is (11-5)/(2-0) = 3 and intercept is 5, giving y = 3x + 5. Linear graphs are the easiest to identify and quantify because you can directly measure slope and intercept from the graph.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Recognizing Quadratic and Power Relationships from Parabolic Curves
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Upward-curving parabolas</strong> suggest quadratic or higher power relationships: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Parabola passing through origin</strong> with accelerating upward curve suggests y = kx² (quadratic). The curve becomes steeper as x increases. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Even steeper acceleration</strong> might indicate higher powers like y = kx³ (cubic). (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">To distinguish</strong>: Check if doubling x quadruples y (x²) or increases y eight-fold (x³). (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Downward-opening parabolas</strong> indicate negative coefficients like y = -kx². For example, if a graph shows a curve through (0,0), (1,2), (2,8), (3,18), test the ratio y/x²: 2/1=2, 8/4=2, 18/9=2 (constant), confirming y = 2x². The characteristic feature of quadratic relationships is that the rate of increase itself increases—the curve gets progressively steeper. This differs from linear relationships where the rate is constant, creating a straight line.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Identifying Inverse Relationships from Hyperbolic Curves
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Hyperbolic curves</strong> indicate inverse relationships: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Shape characteristics</strong>: The curve starts high when x is small, drops steeply initially, then levels off as x increases, approaching but never reaching the x-axis. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Asymptotic behavior</strong>: The curve approaches zero as x approaches infinity, and approaches infinity as x approaches zero. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Equation form</strong>: y = k/x (simple inverse) or y = k/x² (inverse square). (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">To distinguish between inverse types</strong>: Calculate x·y (if constant → y = k/x) or x²·y (if constant → y = k/x²). For example, if a graph shows a curve through (1,24), (2,12), (4,6), (8,3), calculate products: 1×24=24, 2×12=24, 4×6=24, 8×3=24 (constant), confirming y = 24/x. Inverse relationships are common in physics (gravitational force decreases with distance squared, gas pressure decreases with volume increase) and always produce this distinctive hyperbolic shape.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Special Cases: Exponential and Logarithmic Patterns
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Less common but important patterns include <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">exponential</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">logarithmic</strong> relationships: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Exponential growth</strong> (y = abˣ where b > 1): The curve starts slowly then increases explosively. Equal increases in x produce multiplicative increases in y. The curve accelerates upward more dramatically than any polynomial. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Exponential decay</strong> (y = abˣ where 0 < b < 1): The curve starts high and drops rapidly, then levels off approaching zero. Similar shape to y = k/x but with different mathematical properties. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Logarithmic growth</strong> (y = a + b·ln(x)): The curve increases rapidly at first, then progressively slower, eventually appearing almost flat. It''s like exponential growth reversed. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Recognition test for exponential growth</strong>: Check if equal increases in x produce equal multiplication factors in y. For example, if increasing x by 1 always doubles y, the relationship is exponential with base 2. These relationships appear in radioactive decay, population growth, pH calculations, and compound interest problems.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Identifying Equations from Graph Shapes</strong><br><br>
<strong>Graph A:</strong> Straight line through (0,0) with slope = 2<br>
Shape: Linear through origin<br>
Equation: y = 2x<br><br>
<strong>Graph B:</strong> Straight line crossing y-axis at (0,-3) with slope = 4<br>
Shape: Linear with y-intercept<br>
Equation: y = 4x - 3<br><br>
<strong>Graph C:</strong> Upward parabola through origin, accelerating curve<br>
Test points (1,3), (2,12), (3,27): y/x² = 3/1=3, 12/4=3, 27/9=3<br>
Equation: y = 3x²<br><br>
<strong>Graph D:</strong> Hyperbolic curve starting high, approaching x-axis<br>
Test points (2,18), (3,12), (6,6): x·y = 36, 36, 36<br>
Equation: y = 36/x<br><br>
<strong>Graph E:</strong> Explosive upward curve, slow start then rapid increase<br>
Test points (0,2), (1,4), (2,8), (3,16): Each x increase doubles y<br>
Equation: y = 2·(2ˣ) or y = 2^(x+1)
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Advanced Strategies and Common Pitfalls
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Beyond basic equation identification, you need strategies for handling <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">complex scenarios</strong> and avoiding <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">common mistakes</strong>.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Handling Multiple Variables and Combined Relationships
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Some questions involve <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">multiple independent variables</strong> or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">combined effects</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Equations with two variables</strong> like z = kxy or z = k(x/y) require you to hold one variable constant while examining the other. If data shows how z changes with x when y is held constant, determine the relationship between z and x. Then check how z changes with y when x is constant. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Product relationships</strong>: z = kxy means z is proportional to the product. If doubling either x or y doubles z, and doubling both quadruples z, the relationship is a product. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Ratio relationships</strong>: z = k(x/y) means z is proportional to the ratio. If doubling x doubles z (when y is constant) and doubling y halves z (when x is constant), the relationship is a ratio. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Test systematically</strong>: Examine rows where only one variable changes to isolate its effect. For example, in an ideal gas law scenario (PV = nRT), holding temperature constant makes P inversely proportional to V, while holding volume constant makes P directly proportional to T.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Avoiding Calculation Errors and Unit Confusion
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Common mistakes</strong> include: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Arithmetic errors in testing</strong>: Double-check calculations, especially with squares, reciprocals, and negative numbers. 3² = 9 (not 6), 1/4 = 0.25 (not 0.4). (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Confusing x and y</strong>: Make sure you''re substituting the independent variable correctly. If the equation is given as y = f(x), x is the input and y is the output. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Ignoring negative signs</strong>: Negative relationships (y = -2x) decrease rather than increase. Don''t confuse y = -2x with y = 2/x—they''re completely different. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Unit inconsistency</strong>: If x is in meters and y is in centimeters, the constant k will incorporate the conversion factor. Pay attention to units when they''re different. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Rounding too early</strong>: Keep extra precision in intermediate steps to avoid accumulating rounding errors. Round only the final answer. For example, if calculating y/x² and getting 2.97, 3.01, 3.04, recognize these are close to 3 (relationship is y = 3x²) rather than concluding the relationship doesn''t exist.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Distinguishing Between Similar-Looking Equations
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Answer choices often include <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">similar equations</strong> that differ subtly: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Proportionality constant differences</strong>: y = 2x versus y = 3x. These both show direct proportionality but with different slopes. Calculate the actual ratio y/x to determine which constant is correct. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Intercept presence</strong>: y = 2x versus y = 2x + 1. Test with x = 0 or check if the relationship passes through the origin. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Power differences</strong>: y = 3x versus y = 3x². Test with x = 2: First gives y = 6, second gives y = 12. These diverge quickly for x > 1. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Reciprocal location</strong>: y = 2/x versus y = x/2. These are completely different—one is inverse, one is direct. For x = 4: First gives y = 0.5, second gives y = 2. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Negative sign placement</strong>: y = -2x versus y = 2(-x) versus y = -(2x). While these are algebraically equivalent in this case, watch for how negatives affect different parts of more complex equations. Always test with actual numbers rather than trying to reason abstractly about small differences.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
When Data Has Experimental Error or Variation
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Real scientific data includes <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">measurement uncertainty</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">natural variation</strong>: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Perfect fit not required</strong>: The equation should be approximately correct for all data points, not necessarily exact. If an equation gives y = 9.8 and the data shows y = 10, that''s close enough given experimental error. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Look for consistent patterns</strong>: If calculating y/x gives 2.97, 3.02, 2.99, 3.01, the relationship is likely y = 3x despite variation. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Best fit wins</strong>: Choose the equation that fits most data points reasonably well, even if one or two points deviate. (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Outliers exist</strong>: One aberrant data point might be an experimental error. Don''t reject an otherwise excellent fit because of one outlier. (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Answer choices account for error</strong>: ACT questions with noisy data typically have answer choices that differ substantially, so small variations won''t prevent you from identifying the correct equation. Focus on the overall pattern and majority of points rather than demanding perfect agreement for every single data point.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Handling Complex Scenarios</strong><br><br>
<strong>Scenario 1: Multiple variables</strong><br>
Data shows force F for various mass m and acceleration a combinations<br>
When m doubles (a constant): F doubles<br>
When a doubles (m constant): F doubles<br>
When both double: F quadruples<br>
Conclusion: F = kma (product relationship)<br><br>
<strong>Scenario 2: Data with variation</strong><br>
Data: (1, 5.1), (2, 9.8), (3, 15.2), (4, 19.9)<br>
Test y = 5x: Predictions are 5, 10, 15, 20<br>
Actual values: 5.1, 9.8, 15.2, 19.9 (all very close)<br>
Conclusion: y = 5x despite small variations<br><br>
<strong>Scenario 3: Similar equations</strong><br>
Choices: A) y = 4x  B) y = x⁴  C) y = 4x²  D) y = 4/x<br>
Data point: (2, 16)<br>
Test: A) 8 ✗  B) 16 ✓  C) 16 ✓  D) 2 ✗<br>
Next point: (3, 81)<br>
Test: B) 81 ✓  C) 36 ✗<br>
Answer: B) y = x⁴<br><br>
This demonstrates the importance of testing multiple points when equations give similar results for initial values.
</p>
</div>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Direct proportionality (y = kx): constant ratio y/x, straight line through origin, doubling x doubles y
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Inverse proportionality (y = k/x): constant product x·y, hyperbolic curve, doubling x halves y
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Quadratic relationships (y = kx²): constant ratio y/x², parabolic curve, doubling x quadruples y
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Linear with intercept (y = mx + b): constant slope but non-zero y-intercept, straight line not through origin
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Test equations by substituting data point values and comparing predicted y to actual y
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use strategic values (x=0, x=1, extremes) for quick elimination of wrong equations
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Check qualitative trend direction and behavior before detailed calculation to eliminate incompatible equations
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Graph shapes reveal equation types: straight line (linear), parabola (quadratic), hyperbola (inverse)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For multiple variables, isolate one variable at a time by examining data where others are held constant
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Real data has variation—choose the equation that best fits overall pattern, not necessarily every point exactly
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T18:09:19.214163+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (4ad47bb8-6342-4461-bb90-566d7dbcdb7f, d1326f87-0df4-4eb2-a1c7-2ee98ad2aca2, '<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Statistics</h3>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">2. You can see how this is set up below:</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">3. Tables with poor stability</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Pp ~ Total tables in the sample 120 = 0.075</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The total number of tables built in 2022 is irrelevant to finding the sample proportion. The answer is C.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">4. Box and Whisker Plot</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">A box and whisker plot is another way that a data set can be visually displayed. The box and whisker plot</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">gives a five-number summary of the data: the minimum, the maximum, the first quartile, the median, and the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The whiskers display the minimum and maximum of the data. For the example plot, the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">minimum is at 30 and the maximum is at 160.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The box ranges from the first quartile (25 percentile) to the third quartile (75" percentile) of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the data. In other words, the middle 50% of the data points, those from the 25" to 75" percentiles, all</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">fall within the box. The first quartile, the lowest 25% of data points, is from the minimum to the left</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">edge of the box. The fourth quartile, the largest 25% of data points, is from the right side of the box to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The middle line in the box displays the median for the data. For the example plot, the median is</p>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;"></li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">§=©The interquartile range (IQR) is the difference between the third quartile and the first quartile. The</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">width of the box shows IQR. The IQR is equal to the value for the right side of the box (the third</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">quartile) minus the value for the left side of the box (the first quartile). For the example plot, the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">third quartile is 130 and the first quartile is 80, so the IQR is 50 (130 — 80 = 50).</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 7: Ms. Pearson’s first and second period classes each sold brownies to raise money for charity</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">after a forest fire destroyed many local businesses. There are 24 students in the first period class and 29 in</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the second period class. Each student in the class sold brownies and then reported the number of brownies</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">they sold to Ms. Pearson. The data for the number of brownies sold by each student are displayed in the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">box and whisker plot below. If a represents the median for the first period class and b represents the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">median for the second period class, what is the value of b — a?</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">5. Bo Sil</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">6. Class 2</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">7. Class 1</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">8. I</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">9. Brownies</h3>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D.</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">class 2, the median is 60, so b = 60. So, we know that b — a = 60 — 80 = —20. The answer is A.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">10. Normal Distribution and The Empirical Rule</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">For a data set that is normally distributed, we need to know the empirical rule. This rule is very rarely tested,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">but, if it does appear on the ACT, it appears in the hardest questions at the end of the test and are usually pretty</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">easy to solve as long as you have the rule below memorized.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">11. The Empirical Rule</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">standard deviation</strong> of the mean.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">e 95% of the data is within two</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">standard deviations of the mean.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">e 99.7% of the data is within three</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">standard deviations of the mean.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">12. Z</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.5;">
  <li style="margin: 0.15rem 0;">7%</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">13. SN</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">14. JI</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">15. Standard Deviations</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Looking at the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">normal distribution</strong> shown above, the mean is the very middle line. The empirical rule tells us</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">that 68% of the data points lie within 1 <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">standard deviation</strong> of the mean. In other words, 68% of the data points</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">are between the -1 and +1 on the graph above. 95% of the data points lie within 2 standard deviations of the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">mean, which tells us that 95% of the data points are between the -2 and +2 on the graph above. Finally, 99.7%</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">of the data points lie within 3 standard deviations of the mean, so 99.7% of the data points are between the -3</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">As we already said, this is very rarely tested. When this has appeared on the ACT, you have just needed to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">have the empirical rule memorized. The example below shows how this has been tested in the past. There are</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">a few more advanced examples in the problem set for you to complete in case the ACT presents this is a more</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 8: The scores on a fitness test are normally distributed. The mean score was 110 and the</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">standard deviation</strong> was 10. What percentage of the scores on the fitness test are between 90 and 130?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C.</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D.</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">which is 20 points below 110, is exactly 2 standard deviations below the mean, and the score of 130, which is</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">20 points above 110, is exactly 2 standard deviations above the mean.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The empirical rule tells us that 95% of the data points lie within 2 standard deviations of the mean. Therefore,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">95% of the scores are between 90 and 130. The answer is C.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">16. Chapter 34: Statistics</h3>

<p style="height: 1px; margin: 0; padding: 0;"></p>

