<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Quadratics are mathematical expressions containing a term to the second degree with a standard form of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">For quadratics on the ACT, you need to be able to multiply binomials (FOIL), factor, interpret quadratics on a</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">graph, use the quadratic formula, and find the vertex.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">In order to multiply binomials, you will need to FOIL, which stands for First, Outer, Inner, Last. You are</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">likely very familiar with how to multiply binomials by now, but just in case you can use the example below to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">so we get: (2x + 3)(x + 6) = 2x? +12x+ 3x+18 = 2x7+15x+18</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Multiplying Perfect Squares — Don’t Forget to FOIL</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">When multiplying perfect squares, make sure to avoid the common mistake of forgetting to FOIL.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To help avoid this mistake, you can write the perfect square as two expressions and then FOIL.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">(x +5)? =(x+5)(x +5) = x2 4+5x+5x4</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 1: Which of the following is equivalent to (2x + 3)? + 4x ?</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
