INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (eaba7cea-b766-4bfb-9af8-01d1b0497a0a, ee2c4c21-3b49-497b-b99b-c6eb269991a2, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Percentages</strong> are a fundamental concept on the ACT. You need to handle simple percentages and percentage increases/decreases efficiently.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Simple Percentages</h3>

<div style="text-align: center; font-size: 20px; margin: 1.5rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: #f3f4f6; border-radius: 8px;">
  <strong>Proportion: new/original = %/100<br><br>Or: new = original × (% / 100)</strong>
</div>', 1, '2025-10-14T00:42:33.385519+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (3a557367-6e88-4f2c-a7fb-87f53d20b777, ef31a321-1bdf-440a-aa15-f43ba8ac31d5, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Science
Topic: How to Approach the Passages
Lesson Key: passage-approach
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Developing an efficient <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">passage navigation strategy</strong> is crucial for success on the ACT Science section, where you must balance <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reading comprehension</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">data analysis</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">time management</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">question-answering efficiency</strong>. Unlike the Reading section where you must engage deeply with narrative or expository text, Science passages require a different approach that prioritizes visual data interpretation over linear reading. This lesson provides a comprehensive framework for approaching Science passages strategically, explains the optimal order for processing information, introduces techniques for efficient figure analysis, and teaches you how to extract maximum value from minimal reading.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. The Optimal Passage Reading Sequence
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The most efficient approach to Science passages follows a specific <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">strategic sequence</strong> rather than simply reading from top to bottom. Understanding this sequence and practicing it consistently will help you work faster while maintaining high accuracy, allowing you to complete all passages within the 35-minute time limit.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Step 1: Read the Introduction Quickly
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Begin by reading the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">introductory paragraph</strong> or first few sentences to understand <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">what is being studied</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">why</strong>. This gives you essential context about the scientific phenomenon, question, or hypothesis being investigated. For example, an introduction might explain that scientists are studying how temperature affects the rate of a chemical reaction, or that researchers are investigating factors that influence bird migration patterns. This context helps you understand what the variables in subsequent figures represent and why certain measurements were taken. However, don''t spend more than 15-20 seconds on this initial reading—you just need the general topic and purpose, not detailed understanding. If the introduction contains complex terminology or detailed background, don''t worry about understanding every word. Focus on grasping the big picture: What phenomenon or question is being studied?
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Step 2: Examine All Figures and Tables First
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
After the introduction, go directly to the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">figures and tables</strong>—this is where most of the important information lives. For each figure, identify: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">what variables</strong> are being shown (read axis labels and column headers carefully), (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">what units</strong> are used (meters, grams, seconds, degrees Celsius, etc.), (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">what general trends</strong> are visible (do values increase, decrease, stay constant, or show a pattern?), and (4) what <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">different lines, symbols, or categories</strong> represent (check the legend or key). Don''t try to memorize specific data points—you can return to find those when answering questions. Instead, develop a general understanding of what each figure shows and what relationships exist between variables. This figure-first approach is efficient because 60-70% of Science questions require you to reference figures directly, and understanding the data helps you answer questions even without reading all the text.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Step 3: Skim Experimental Procedures and Descriptions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
After examining the figures, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">skim</strong> any paragraphs that describe experimental procedures, setups, or methods. Your goal is to understand <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">how trials differ from each other</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">what variables were manipulated</strong>, but you don''t need to memorize step-by-step procedures. For example, if an experiment has three trials, note what changed between Trial 1, Trial 2, and Trial 3 (was it temperature? concentration? time?). This understanding helps you interpret results and answer questions about experimental design. However, avoid reading detailed procedural descriptions word-for-word unless a question specifically asks about them. Paragraphs explaining how equipment was set up, how measurements were taken, or what specific materials were used often contain more detail than necessary for most questions. You can always return to read these sections carefully if a question requires that information.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Step 4: Move to Questions and Reference Back as Needed
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Once you''ve completed your initial passage review (introduction + figures + skim of procedures), move directly to the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">questions</strong>. For each question, identify what information is being asked for, then <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reference back to the specific figure, table, or text</strong> that contains the answer. Don''t try to answer questions from memory—even if you think you remember the data, check the passage to confirm. This approach prevents careless errors and is actually faster than trying to memorize all details upfront. Many questions will direct you to specific figures (e.g., "According to Figure 2..."), making it easy to know where to look. For questions without explicit references, use the question number as a guide—early questions typically relate to early parts of the passage, while later questions often address later sections. This question-focused approach ensures you''re spending time on information that actually matters for points rather than reading details that won''t be tested.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Optimal Reading Sequence in Action</strong><br><br>
<strong>Passage Preview:</strong> A Research Summaries passage with 3 experiments testing how pH, temperature, and concentration affect enzyme activity.<br><br>
<strong>Step 1 (20 seconds):</strong> Read intro → "Scientists studied factors affecting enzyme activity"<br>
<strong>Step 2 (45 seconds):</strong> Examine all three figures → Note that Figure 1 shows pH vs. activity, Figure 2 shows temperature vs. activity, Figure 3 shows concentration vs. activity<br>
<strong>Step 3 (30 seconds):</strong> Skim experiment descriptions → Trial 1 varied pH, Trial 2 varied temperature, Trial 3 varied concentration<br>
<strong>Step 4 (3-4 minutes):</strong> Answer all 6 questions, referencing specific figures and text as needed<br><br>
Total time: approximately 5 minutes per passage
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Figure-First vs. Text-First Reading Approaches
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
One of the most important strategic decisions you''ll make is whether to adopt a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">figure-first approach</strong> or a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">text-first approach</strong>. While most high-scoring students favor the figure-first method, understanding both approaches and their variations helps you identify what works best for your learning style and adapt to different passage types.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Figure-First Approach (Recommended for Most Students)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">figure-first approach</strong> prioritizes examining graphs, tables, and diagrams before reading detailed text. This method works well because Science questions primarily test data interpretation skills, and most answers can be found by analyzing figures. After a brief intro reading, you spend the majority of your initial passage time studying figures to understand what variables are present, what trends exist, and how different trials or conditions compare. Then you skim text only as needed to clarify what the figures show or to understand experimental differences. This approach is particularly effective for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Data Representation passages</strong> where figures dominate and text is minimal, but it also works well for many Research Summaries passages. The main advantage is <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">time efficiency</strong>—you focus on the information that matters most. The potential disadvantage is that you might miss important context or definitions that would make figure interpretation easier, though this is rare since figures are usually self-explanatory with proper labels.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Text-First Approach (Better for Some Conflicting Viewpoints Passages)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">text-first approach</strong> involves reading the passage more thoroughly before examining figures in depth. This method can be effective for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Conflicting Viewpoints passages</strong>, which contain substantial text describing different scientific perspectives and may have fewer or simpler figures. When different scientists or students present competing theories, understanding the logic and evidence behind each viewpoint often requires careful reading of the arguments presented. In these cases, reading the text first provides context that makes subsequent figure analysis more meaningful. However, even with this approach, you should still <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">skim rather than read every word</strong>, focusing on understanding the main claims and differences between viewpoints. The main disadvantage of text-first for Data Representation and Research Summaries passages is that it often wastes time on details that won''t be tested, causing you to run short on time for later passages.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Hybrid Approach (Questions-First Method)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Some students prefer a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">hybrid approach</strong> where they quickly preview the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">questions first</strong> to know what information they''ll need, then strategically read only the relevant parts of the passage. For example, if you see that questions 1-3 all reference Figure 1, you might examine Figure 1 carefully while only glancing at Figures 2 and 3. Or if a question asks specifically about what was held constant in Trial 2, you know to focus on that experimental description. This approach can be highly efficient because it ensures you''re never reading irrelevant information. However, it requires strong mental organization to track what you''ve looked for and what you still need to find. It can also be disruptive if you''re constantly jumping between questions and passage sections. This method works best for students who are comfortable with non-linear reading and have already developed strong figure-reading skills through practice.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Adapting Your Approach by Passage Type
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The most effective strategy is often to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">adapt your approach</strong> based on passage type and complexity. For straightforward <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Data Representation passages</strong> with simple graphs and minimal text, a strict figure-first approach usually works best. For <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Research Summaries passages</strong> with multiple experiments, you might spend more time reading experimental descriptions to understand how trials differ, though you should still prioritize figures. For <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Conflicting Viewpoints passages</strong>, you may need to read the text more carefully to understand each scientist''s reasoning, though you should still examine any accompanying figures. Some students also adjust their strategy based on passage difficulty—spending more time on initial reading for complex passages and less for straightforward ones. Flexibility is valuable, but make sure you''re making conscious strategic decisions rather than just reading randomly or inconsistently.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Choosing Your Approach</strong><br><br>
<strong>Data Representation Passage:</strong> 3 figures showing temperature vs. pressure relationships → Use figure-first approach, spend 60+ seconds examining graphs, minimal text reading<br><br>
<strong>Research Summaries Passage:</strong> 3 experiments with detailed procedures and result tables → Use figure-first but allocate more time to skimming experimental descriptions<br><br>
<strong>Conflicting Viewpoints Passage:</strong> Scientists A and B debate climate change mechanisms → Read text more thoroughly to understand each perspective, but still check figures for supporting evidence<br><br>
Experiment with different approaches during practice to find what maximizes your accuracy and speed.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Efficient Figure and Table Analysis Techniques
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Since figures and tables contain the majority of information needed to answer Science questions, developing <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">systematic figure analysis skills</strong> is essential. Learning to extract key information quickly and accurately from visual data representations will dramatically improve both your speed and accuracy on the Science section.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Five-Element Figure Analysis Framework
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When you look at any figure, systematically check five elements: (1) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Variables</strong> - What is being measured or manipulated? Read all axis labels and table headers. (2) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Units</strong> - What units are used for each variable? (meters, grams, seconds, etc.) Pay attention to unit prefixes like "k" for kilo or "m" for milli. (3) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scale</strong> - What range of values is shown? Does the axis start at zero or some other value? Is the scale linear or logarithmic? (4) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Trends</strong> - How do the variables relate to each other? Do values increase together (positive correlation), move in opposite directions (inverse relationship), or show no clear pattern? (5) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Legend/Key</strong> - What do different lines, symbols, colors, or categories represent? Making this five-element check habitual ensures you never miss important details that could cause errors.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Common Figure Types and How to Read Them
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
ACT Science passages use several standard figure types, each requiring slightly different reading strategies. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Line graphs</strong> show how one variable changes with another; focus on the overall trend (increasing, decreasing, constant) and whether the relationship is linear or curved. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Bar graphs</strong> compare values across categories; look for which category has the highest or lowest value and how much they differ. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scatter plots</strong> show relationships between two variables with individual data points; look for general patterns or clusters. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Data tables</strong> organize values in rows and columns; identify what each row and column represents and notice patterns as you move across rows or down columns. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Diagrams</strong> illustrate experimental setups or scientific processes; understand what each labeled component represents and how they interact. Recognizing these common types helps you quickly orient yourself and know what to look for.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Identifying Trends and Relationships
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Many Science questions ask about <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">trends and relationships</strong> between variables. When examining figures, actively ask yourself: How do the variables relate? Common relationship types include: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">positive/direct relationship</strong> (both variables increase together), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">negative/inverse relationship</strong> (one increases while the other decreases), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">no relationship</strong> (changes in one variable don''t affect the other), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">linear relationship</strong> (the relationship forms a straight line), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">non-linear relationship</strong> (the relationship is curved), and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">exponential relationship</strong> (the rate of change accelerates). Being able to quickly identify these relationship types allows you to answer trend questions without needing to read specific values. You should also notice whether trends are <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">consistent</strong> across the entire range shown or whether the relationship <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">changes</strong> at certain points.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Avoiding Common Figure-Reading Mistakes
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Several common errors can lead to wrong answers even when you understand the science conceptually. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Confusing x and y variables</strong> is extremely common—always check which variable is on which axis. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Misreading scales</strong> causes many errors, especially when axes don''t start at zero or use non-standard intervals (like going 0, 50, 100, 200, 500 instead of evenly spaced values). <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Ignoring units</strong> can lead to errors when comparing values from different figures or when units change within a passage. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Misidentifying which line or symbol</strong> represents which condition is another frequent mistake—always double-check the legend. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Extrapolating too far beyond the data</strong> shown can also cause errors—be cautious when predicting values outside the measured range. Slowing down for just 2-3 extra seconds to verify these details prevents careless mistakes that cost points.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Systematic Figure Analysis</strong><br><br>
<strong>Figure 1: Graph showing "Temperature (°C)" on x-axis and "Reaction Rate (mol/sec)" on y-axis</strong><br><br>
<strong>Variables:</strong> Temperature and Reaction Rate<br>
<strong>Units:</strong> Temperature in °C, Reaction Rate in mol/sec<br>
<strong>Scale:</strong> x-axis goes from 0-80°C in intervals of 20; y-axis goes from 0-5 mol/sec in intervals of 1<br>
<strong>Trend:</strong> As temperature increases, reaction rate increases (positive relationship, appears to be exponential)<br>
<strong>Legend:</strong> One line shown, labeled "Enzyme A"<br><br>
This 15-second analysis prepares you to answer most questions about this figure without needing to re-examine it repeatedly.
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Maximizing Efficiency Through Strategic Passage Selection
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Not all Science passages are equally difficult, and you don''t have to complete them in the order they appear. Strategic passage selection—choosing which passages to tackle first based on your strengths and passage characteristics—can significantly improve your score by ensuring you <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">maximize points earned</strong> within the time limit and maintain <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">confidence and momentum</strong> throughout the section.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Identifying Your Strongest Passage Types
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Through practice, you should identify which passage types you find easiest and most time-efficient. Many students find <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Data Representation passages</strong> quickest because they have minimal text and straightforward graph-reading questions. Others prefer <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Research Summaries passages</strong> because they enjoy the logical structure of experimental design. Some students find <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Conflicting Viewpoints passages</strong> most accessible because they involve reading comprehension skills similar to the Reading section. Understanding your preferences allows you to develop a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">personalized passage order strategy</strong>. For example, if you''re strongest at Data Representation, you might quickly flip through the section at the start, identify the 2-3 Data Representation passages by their figure-heavy layouts, and complete those first. This approach ensures you secure easy points quickly and build confidence before tackling more challenging passages.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Quick Passage Previewing Technique
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
At the start of the Science section, consider spending 30-45 seconds doing a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">quick preview</strong> of all passages to identify which look most straightforward. Flip through and quickly assess: (1) How many figures does each passage have? Passages with more complex or dense figures may take longer. (2) How much text is present? Text-heavy passages (usually Conflicting Viewpoints) may require more reading time. (3) Do any passages cover topics you''re familiar with? While outside knowledge isn''t required, comfort with a topic can boost confidence. (4) Are there any passages with particularly simple-looking graphs or tables? These might be quick wins. Based on this preview, mentally rank the passages from most to least approachable and tackle them in that order. However, be careful not to spend too much time previewing—if this takes more than 45 seconds, it''s probably not worth it. Some students prefer to just start with the first passage rather than risk wasting time on decision-making.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Banking Time with Faster Passages
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The strategy of completing easier passages first has another advantage: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">banking time</strong> for more difficult passages. If you can complete a straightforward Data Representation passage in 3.5 minutes instead of 5 minutes, you''ve saved 1.5 minutes that you can apply to a more complex Research Summaries or Conflicting Viewpoints passage later. This flexibility is crucial because some passages genuinely do take longer than others due to complexity, and rigid pacing (exactly 5 minutes per passage) doesn''t account for this variability. By working efficiently on easier passages, you create a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">time buffer</strong> that reduces stress and allows you to think more carefully about challenging questions. However, don''t rush through easier passages so quickly that you make careless errors—the time you save isn''t worth it if you miss questions you should have gotten right. Aim for efficient accuracy, not just speed.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Managing Difficult Passages Strategically
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When you encounter a particularly challenging passage—whether due to complex figures, unfamiliar terminology, or confusing experimental design—have a strategy for managing it without letting it derail your entire section. First, recognize that <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">not all questions within a passage are equally difficult</strong>. Even in a challenging passage, there are usually 2-3 straightforward questions that ask for simple data reading or basic trends. Tackle those first to secure easy points. For genuinely difficult questions that would require extensive time, consider <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">strategic guessing</strong>—if you''ve spent 60 seconds on a question and still aren''t sure, make your best guess and move on rather than spending 2-3 minutes agonizing over one question. You can also employ the strategy of <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">saving one passage for last</strong>—if you reach the final passage with only 3 minutes remaining, answer the easiest questions you can identify and guess on the rest rather than running out of time completely.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Example: Strategic Passage Selection</strong><br><br>
<strong>Your Science section contains:</strong><br>
- Passage 1: Research Summaries (3 experiments, dense text) - MEDIUM DIFFICULTY<br>
- Passage 2: Data Representation (simple line graphs) - EASY<br>
- Passage 3: Conflicting Viewpoints (lots of text) - HARD<br>
- Passage 4: Data Representation (multiple tables) - EASY<br>
- Passage 5: Research Summaries (2 experiments) - MEDIUM<br>
- Passage 6: Data Representation (scatter plots) - MEDIUM<br><br>
<strong>Optimal order:</strong> 2 → 4 → 6 → 1 → 5 → 3 (easy passages first, hardest last)<br><br>
This ensures you secure maximum points on straightforward passages before tackling the time-consuming Conflicting Viewpoints passage.
</p>
</div>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Follow the optimal sequence: brief intro reading → examine all figures → skim procedures → answer questions
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Prioritize figures and tables over text—60-70% of questions can be answered primarily from visual data
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use the figure-first approach for Data Representation and most Research Summaries passages
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Read text more carefully for Conflicting Viewpoints passages to understand different scientific perspectives
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Systematically analyze every figure: variables, units, scale, trends, and legend/key
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Identify relationships between variables: positive, negative, linear, non-linear, or exponential
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Avoid common mistakes: confusing x/y variables, misreading scales, ignoring units, and wrong legend interpretation
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Complete passages in strategic order—identify and tackle your strongest passage types first
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Bank time by working efficiently on easier passages, giving yourself extra time for complex ones
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Don''t spend more than 60 seconds struggling with one question—guess and move on if necessary
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T18:09:19.214163+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (e57b367a-965c-4f80-a259-62a1c4dca0a7, ef8262e4-47f9-4d64-89b3-f2475a1eb6ab, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 2rem 0;">
<strong>Working backwards</strong> means testing answer choices instead of solving algebraically. Plug in each answer to see which one works—it''s often faster than setting up equations.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 6rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; font-size: 20px;">
1. When to Use This Strategy
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 1rem 0 3rem 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Problem asks for a specific number ("What is the value of x?")</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Answer choices are concrete numbers (not variables)</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Algebraic setup is unclear or complex</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Time pressure—plugging in is faster</li>
</ul>

<div style="border: 1px solid #d1d5db; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0 3rem 0; background: #fafafa;">
<p style="font-size: 15px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0 0 1rem 0;">
Example
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0;">
When 5 is added to twice a number, the result is 23. What is the number?
</p>
<p style="margin: 0;">
<strong>Solution:</strong> Test choice C (9) → 2(9) + 5 = 23 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-weight: 600; font-size: 18px;">
Smart Testing Strategy
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 1rem 0 3rem 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Always start with C</strong> – If C is too big/small, eliminate half the answers instantly</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Stop when one works</strong> – No need to test remaining choices</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Test easy numbers first</strong> – If one choice is 0, 1, or 10, try it first</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 6rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; font-size: 20px;">
2. The Process
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 1rem 0 3rem 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Understand what you''re solving for</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Pick an answer choice (usually start with C)</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Plug it into the problem</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Step 4:</strong> Check if it works—if yes, done; if no, eliminate and try another</li>
</ul>

<div style="border: 1px solid #d1d5db; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0 3rem 0; background: #fafafa;">
<p style="font-size: 15px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0 0 1rem 0;">
Example
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0;">
Sarah spends $15, then triples what remains. She has $60. How much did she start with?
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Test C ($30):</strong> $30 - $15 = $15, then $15 × 3 = $45 ✗ (need $60)
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
Too small → eliminate A, B, C
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Test D ($35):</strong> $35 - $15 = $20, then $20 × 3 = $60 ✓
</p>
<p style="margin: 0;">
<strong>Answer: D</strong>
</p>
</div>

<div style="border: 1px solid #dc2626; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0 3rem 0; background: #fef2f2;">
<p style="font-size: 15px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; color: #991b1b;">
Practice Problem
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
When 8 is subtracted from three times a number, the result is 22. What is the number?
</p>
<p style="margin: 0; font-size: 15px;">
A. 8  |  B. 10  |  C. 12  |  D. 14  |  E. 16
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 6rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; font-size: 20px;">
3. Common Problem Types
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-weight: 600; font-size: 18px;">
Age Problems
</h4>

<div style="border: 1px solid #d1d5db; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0 3rem 0; background: #fafafa;">
<p style="font-size: 15px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0 0 1rem 0;">
Example
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0;">
Marcus is 3 years older than twice his sister''s age. If Marcus is 19, how old is his sister?
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Test H (9):</strong> 2(9) + 3 = 21 ✗ (too big)
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Test G (8):</strong> 2(8) + 3 = 19 ✓
</p>
<p style="margin: 0;">
<strong>Answer: G</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-weight: 600; font-size: 18px;">
Consecutive Integers
</h4>

<div style="border: 1px solid #d1d5db; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0 3rem 0; background: #fafafa;">
<p style="font-size: 15px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0 0 1rem 0;">
Example
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0;">
Three consecutive even integers sum to 84. What is the smallest?
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Test C (28):</strong> 28 + 30 + 32 = 90 ✗ (too big)
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Test A (26):</strong> 26 + 28 + 30 = 84 ✓
</p>
<p style="margin: 0;">
<strong>Answer: A</strong>
</p>
</div>

<div style="border: 1px solid #dc2626; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0 3rem 0; background: #fef2f2;">
<p style="font-size: 15px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; color: #991b1b;">
Practice Problem
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
Four consecutive integers sum to 34. What is the largest?
</p>
<p style="margin: 0; font-size: 15px;">
A. 7  |  B. 8  |  C. 9  |  D. 10  |  E. 11
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-weight: 600; font-size: 18px;">
Percent & Money
</h4>

<div style="border: 1px solid #d1d5db; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0 3rem 0; background: #fafafa;">
<p style="font-size: 15px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0 0 1rem 0;">
Example
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0;">
After a 20% discount, a jacket costs $64. What was the original price?
</p>
<p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Test B ($80):</strong> $80 × 0.80 = $64 ✓
</p>
<p style="margin: 0;">
<strong>Answer: B</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 6rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; font-size: 20px;">
4. Pro Tips
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 1rem 0 3rem 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Estimate first</strong> – Narrow down choices before testing</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Watch order of operations</strong> – "5 less than twice x" means 2x - 5, not 5 - 2x</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Check what you''re solving for</strong> – Don''t test current age if question asks for age in 5 years</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Be flexible</strong> – Switch to algebra if testing takes too long</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;"><strong>Stay organized</strong> – Write which choice you''re testing and mark eliminated answers</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 6rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; font-size: 20px; color: #059669;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 1rem 0 3rem 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2.2;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; color: #059669; font-weight: 600;">Start with choice C to eliminate half the answers if it''s too large or too small</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; color: #059669; font-weight: 600;">Best for word problems where answer choices are simple numbers and algebraic setup is complex</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; color: #059669; font-weight: 600;">Stop testing as soon as you find an answer that works—no need to check remaining choices</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; color: #059669; font-weight: 600;">Common types: age problems, consecutive integers, percent/money problems</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 1rem; color: #059669; font-weight: 600;">Stay organized by marking which choice you''re testing and crossing out eliminated answers</li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T18:09:19.214163+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (9ec40384-4aa8-4488-9932-5ee29e81a44f, f450efd1-e9b0-4381-842c-7425db770ae2, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Number substitution</strong> is a powerful test-taking strategy that transforms abstract algebraic problems into concrete arithmetic by <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">plugging in your own numbers</strong> for variables. Instead of manipulating variables and expressions symbolically, you choose simple, strategic numbers to substitute, work through the problem with those numbers, and then test which answer choice produces the same result. This technique is particularly effective for problems with <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">variables in answer choices</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">complex expressions</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">word problems</strong> where the algebraic setup is unclear.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. When to Use Number Substitution
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Identifying the Right Problems
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Number substitution is most effective when:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Answer choices contain variables:</strong> If all answer choices include x, y, n, or other variables, this is the clearest signal to use number substitution.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example answer choices:</strong>
<br>
A. 2x + 3<br>
B. 3x + 2<br>
C. 2x - 3<br>
D. 3x - 2<br>
E. x + 5
<br><br>
Since all choices contain x, pick a value for x, work through the problem, and see which expression gives you the correct result.
</p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>The problem involves complex expressions:</strong> When the problem requires manipulating complicated algebraic expressions, substituting numbers can simplify the work.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>The algebraic approach is unclear:</strong> If you''re unsure how to set up the algebra, number substitution provides a concrete alternative.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>The problem asks "which expression":</strong> Questions asking you to identify an equivalent expression or formula are perfect for this strategy.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
When NOT to Use Number Substitution
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
This strategy is less effective when:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>Answer choices are all numbers:</strong> Use working backwards instead</li>
<li><strong>The algebraic solution is straightforward:</strong> Simple one-step or two-step algebra is faster than substitution</li>
<li><strong>The problem involves geometric reasoning:</strong> Unless it''s asking for an algebraic expression, geometry problems need direct solving</li>
<li><strong>Testing would require extensive calculation:</strong> If substituting numbers creates complicated arithmetic, algebra may be more efficient</li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Golden Rule: Choose Strategic Numbers
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
The success of number substitution depends on choosing good numbers to substitute. Follow these principles:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Use simple, easy-to-calculate numbers:</strong> Numbers like 2, 3, 5, 10, or 100 make arithmetic quick and reduce errors.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Avoid 0 and 1 (usually):</strong> These numbers have special properties (0 times anything is 0, 1 times anything is itself) that can make different expressions produce the same result, preventing you from distinguishing answer choices.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Respect problem constraints:</strong> If the problem says "positive integer" or "even number," choose a number that fits. If it mentions "price in dollars," use a reasonable price.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Use 100 for percent problems:</strong> When dealing with percentages, 100 is often the simplest choice because calculating percentages of 100 is easy.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>For multiple variables, choose different values:</strong> If the problem has x and y, make them different numbers (like x = 3 and y = 5) so you can track them separately.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Step-by-Step Process
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Five-Step Method
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 1: Choose your number(s).</strong> Select simple, strategic values for the variable(s) in the problem, respecting any constraints.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 2: Work through the problem with your numbers.</strong> Substitute your chosen values into the problem and solve it using arithmetic to get a concrete numerical answer. This is your "target value."
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 3: Label your target.</strong> Write down or circle this result—it''s what you''re looking for in the answer choices.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 4: Test each answer choice.</strong> Substitute your chosen number(s) into each answer choice expression and calculate the result.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Step 5: Find the match.</strong> The answer choice that produces your target value is correct.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Complete example:</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>Problem:</strong> If the cost of n notebooks is 3n + 5 dollars, what is the cost of 7 more notebooks than n?
<br><br>
A. 3n + 12<br>
B. 3n + 26<br>
C. 10n + 5<br>
D. 21n + 35<br>
E. 3n + 7
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1: Choose a number for n.</strong> Let n = 4 (simple number, easy to work with).
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2: Work through the problem.</strong>
<br>
- n notebooks cost 3n + 5 = 3(4) + 5 = 12 + 5 = $17
<br>
- "7 more notebooks than n" means 4 + 7 = 11 notebooks total
<br>
- Cost of 11 notebooks: 3(11) + 5 = 33 + 5 = $38
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3: Label target.</strong> We''re looking for $38.
<br><br>
<strong>Step 4 & 5: Test answer choices (where n = 4):</strong>
<br>
A. 3(4) + 12 = 12 + 12 = 24 ❌
<br>
B. 3(4) + 26 = 12 + 26 = 38 ✓
<br>
C. 10(4) + 5 = 40 + 5 = 45 ❌
<br>
D. 21(4) + 35 = 84 + 35 = 119 ❌
<br>
E. 3(4) + 7 = 12 + 7 = 19 ❌
<br><br>
<strong>Answer: B</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Staying Organized
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
To avoid errors, maintain clear organization:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>Write down your substitution:</strong> Note "Let x = 3" clearly so you don''t forget what value you''re using</li>
<li><strong>Show your arithmetic:</strong> Work through calculations step-by-step rather than doing everything mentally</li>
<li><strong>Circle your target value:</strong> Make it easy to see what you''re looking for when testing answer choices</li>
<li><strong>Test choices systematically:</strong> Go through A, B, C, D, E in order to avoid missing the correct answer</li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
What If Two Choices Match?
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Occasionally, two answer choices might produce your target value. This usually means you chose an unfortunate number (often 0, 1, or a number that makes certain terms cancel). If this happens:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>Pick a different number:</strong> Choose a new value for the variable and test only the two remaining answer choices with this new number</li>
<li><strong>Choose a more complex number:</strong> Use a number like 3, 5, or 7 rather than 2, or use a larger number like 10</li>
<li><strong>Only one will match with the new number:</strong> That''s your answer</li>
</ul>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
In practice, choosing good numbers from the start (avoiding 0 and 1) usually prevents this issue.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Common Problem Types
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Expression Translation Problems
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
These problems describe a situation in words and ask which expression represents it:
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Problem:</strong> Sam has x dollars. He spends $8 and then doubles what remains. Which expression represents the amount he has now?
<br><br>
F. 2x - 8<br>
G. 2x - 16<br>
H. 2(x - 8)<br>
J. x - 16<br>
K. 8 - 2x
<br><br>
<strong>Using substitution:</strong>
<br>
Let x = 20 (Sam starts with $20)
<br>
- He spends $8: 20 - 8 = 12 remaining
<br>
- Doubles what remains: 12 × 2 = 24
<br>
- Target: $24
<br><br>
<strong>Testing choices (where x = 20):</strong>
<br>
F. 2(20) - 8 = 40 - 8 = 32 ❌
<br>
G. 2(20) - 16 = 40 - 16 = 24 ✓
<br>
H. 2(20 - 8) = 2(12) = 24 ✓
<br><br>
Two choices match! Choose a new number.
<br><br>
Let x = 10
<br>
- He spends $8: 10 - 8 = 2 remaining
<br>
- Doubles what remains: 2 × 2 = 4
<br>
- Target: $4
<br><br>
G. 2(10) - 16 = 20 - 16 = 4 ✓
<br>
H. 2(10 - 8) = 2(2) = 4 ✓
<br><br>
Still matching! Let x = 15
<br>
- He spends $8: 15 - 8 = 7 remaining
<br>
- Doubles what remains: 7 × 2 = 14
<br>
- Target: $14
<br><br>
G. 2(15) - 16 = 30 - 16 = 14 ✓
<br>
H. 2(15 - 8) = 2(7) = 14 ✓
<br><br>
<strong>Note:</strong> G and H are actually algebraically equivalent: 2(x - 8) = 2x - 16. Both are correct! The test would not present both as options. If you encounter this, either could be the answer.
<br><br>
<strong>Answer: H (or G if H weren''t available)</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Percent Problems
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
For percent problems, using 100 as your base value makes calculations simple:
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Problem:</strong> A store increases the price of an item by 20% and then decreases it by 20%. If the original price was p dollars, which expression represents the final price?
<br><br>
A. p<br>
B. 0.96p<br>
C. 1.04p<br>
D. 0.80p<br>
E. 1.20p
<br><br>
<strong>Using substitution with p = 100:</strong>
<br>
- Original price: $100
<br>
- Increase by 20%: $100 + $20 = $120
<br>
- Decrease by 20% (of the new price): $120 - (0.20 × $120) = $120 - $24 = $96
<br>
- Target: $96
<br><br>
<strong>Testing choices (where p = 100):</strong>
<br>
A. 100 ❌
<br>
B. 0.96(100) = 96 ✓
<br>
C. 1.04(100) = 104 ❌
<br>
D. 0.80(100) = 80 ❌
<br>
E. 1.20(100) = 120 ❌
<br><br>
<strong>Answer: B</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Average Problems
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Problems involving averages and unknowns work well with number substitution:
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Problem:</strong> The average of three numbers is x. If two of the numbers are 15 and 21, what is the third number in terms of x?
<br><br>
F. x - 36<br>
G. 3x - 36<br>
H. x - 12<br>
J. 3x - 12<br>
K. x + 36
<br><br>
<strong>Using substitution:</strong>
<br>
Let x = 20 (average is 20)
<br>
- Average of three numbers is 20, so sum = 20 × 3 = 60
<br>
- Two numbers are 15 and 21: 15 + 21 = 36
<br>
- Third number: 60 - 36 = 24
<br>
- Target: 24
<br><br>
<strong>Testing choices (where x = 20):</strong>
<br>
F. 20 - 36 = -16 ❌
<br>
G. 3(20) - 36 = 60 - 36 = 24 ✓
<br>
H. 20 - 12 = 8 ❌
<br>
J. 3(20) - 12 = 60 - 12 = 48 ❌
<br>
K. 20 + 36 = 56 ❌
<br><br>
<strong>Answer: G</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Problems with Multiple Variables
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
When the problem involves two or more variables, choose different values for each:
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Problem:</strong> If a rectangle has length x and width y, which expression represents the perimeter?
<br><br>
A. xy<br>
B. 2xy<br>
C. x + y<br>
D. 2x + 2y<br>
E. x² + y²
<br><br>
<strong>Using substitution:</strong>
<br>
Let x = 5 and y = 3
<br>
- Perimeter = 2(length) + 2(width) = 2(5) + 2(3) = 10 + 6 = 16
<br>
- Target: 16
<br><br>
<strong>Testing choices (where x = 5, y = 3):</strong>
<br>
A. 5 × 3 = 15 ❌
<br>
B. 2 × 5 × 3 = 30 ❌
<br>
C. 5 + 3 = 8 ❌
<br>
D. 2(5) + 2(3) = 10 + 6 = 16 ✓
<br>
E. 5² + 3² = 25 + 9 = 34 ❌
<br><br>
<strong>Answer: D</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Advanced Strategies and Tips
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Special Number Considerations
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Certain problem types benefit from specific number choices:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>For fraction problems:</strong> Choose numbers that are multiples of the denominators to avoid messy arithmetic.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> If the problem involves "one-third of x," choose x = 6, 9, 12, or another multiple of 3 to get whole number results.
</p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>For consecutive integer problems:</strong> Use actual consecutive integers like 5, 6, 7 or 10, 11, 12.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>For even/odd problems:</strong> Respect the constraint—if x must be even, use 2, 4, 6, etc.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>For digit problems:</strong> If the problem discusses digits of a number, choose a two-digit number like 23 where you can easily identify which digit is which.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
When 0 and 1 Are Actually Useful
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
While generally avoided, there are rare cases where 0 or 1 is appropriate:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>Use 0 when testing for constant terms:</strong> If you suspect an expression has a constant (like the "+5" in "3x + 5"), substituting 0 isolates that constant</li>
<li><strong>Use 1 when checking coefficients:</strong> Substituting 1 can help you see the coefficient structure of an expression</li>
<li><strong>Never use them as your first choice:</strong> Only use 0 or 1 if you''re testing a specific hypothesis or if you''ve already found the answer with another number and want to verify</li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Combining Number Substitution with Other Strategies
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Number substitution can work alongside other techniques:
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>With estimation:</strong> After substituting and finding your target, you can often estimate which answer choices are in the right range before calculating all of them.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>With elimination:</strong> If answer choices have obviously wrong forms (wrong operations, wrong signs), eliminate those before testing.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>With algebraic reasoning:</strong> You can use number substitution to check an algebraic solution or to guide your algebraic setup.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Common Mistakes to Avoid
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 1: Choosing numbers that violate constraints.</strong> Always check if the problem specifies "positive," "even," "integer," etc., and choose accordingly.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 2: Forgetting what you substituted.</strong> Write down "x = 3" or "p = 100" clearly so you don''t mix up values mid-problem.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 3: Making arithmetic errors.</strong> Double-check your calculations, especially when testing answer choices. A small error can lead you to select the wrong answer.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Mistake 4: Stopping after finding one match without checking others.</strong> While you should find only one match, occasionally an arithmetic error makes you think you''ve found it when you haven''t. If time permits, verify by testing one more choice.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Time Management
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
Number substitution is generally quick, but optimize your efficiency:
</p>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7;">
<li><strong>Choose numbers you can work with mentally:</strong> If you can do most arithmetic in your head, you''ll save significant time</li>
<li><strong>Use scratch paper effectively:</strong> Write your substitution, target value, and testing clearly to avoid confusion</li>
<li><strong>Skip complicated answer choices initially:</strong> If one answer choice looks much more complicated than others, test the simpler ones first</li>
<li><strong>Budget 30-60 seconds:</strong> Most number substitution problems should take under a minute once you''re practiced</li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Practice Example: Complex Multi-Variable Problem
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Problem:</strong> A painter charges a flat fee of f dollars plus h dollars per hour. If she works for n hours, what is her total charge in dollars?
<br><br>
A. fhn<br>
B. f + h + n<br>
C. f + hn<br>
D. fn + h<br>
E. n(f + h)
<br><br>
<strong>Using substitution:</strong>
<br>
Let f = 50 (flat fee = $50)
<br>
Let h = 20 (hourly rate = $20/hour)
<br>
Let n = 3 (works 3 hours)
<br><br>
- Flat fee: $50
<br>
- Hourly charge: $20 × 3 hours = $60
<br>
- Total charge: $50 + $60 = $110
<br>
- Target: $110
<br><br>
<strong>Testing choices (where f = 50, h = 20, n = 3):</strong>
<br>
A. 50 × 20 × 3 = 3,000 ❌
<br>
B. 50 + 20 + 3 = 73 ❌
<br>
C. 50 + (20 × 3) = 50 + 60 = 110 ✓
<br>
D. (50 × 3) + 20 = 150 + 20 = 170 ❌
<br>
E. 3(50 + 20) = 3(70) = 210 ❌
<br><br>
<strong>Answer: C</strong>
</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0rem; font-weight: 400; visibility: hidden;">
Hidden Section Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="margin-top: 0rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.9;">
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Number substitution works by choosing your own numbers for variables, solving the problem with those numbers, then testing which answer choice produces the same result
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Use this strategy when answer choices contain variables—it''s the clearest signal that number substitution will be effective
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Choose simple, easy-to-calculate numbers like 2, 3, 5, or 10 to minimize arithmetic errors and save time
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Avoid using 0 or 1 (usually) because their special properties can make different expressions produce the same result
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Always respect problem constraints—if it says "positive integer" or "even number," choose accordingly
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Use 100 for percent problems because calculating percentages of 100 is quick and easy
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> For multiple variables, choose different values for each (like x = 3, y = 5) so you can track them separately
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Follow the five-step method: choose numbers, work through the problem, label your target, test each answer choice, find the match
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #2e7d32; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> If two answer choices match your target, choose a different number and test only those two choices again with the new value
</li>
<li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
<span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Stay organized by writing down your substitution, showing arithmetic steps, and circling your target value
</li>
</ul>', 0, '2025-10-16T00:55:54.473642+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (97923502-ddec-49e7-9f07-39b38df6b5f8, f4c01a56-ea69-468c-83e7-274e499ad1f1, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Circles, ellipses, and hyperbolas</strong> are conic sections that appear regularly on the ACT. You can almost guarantee at least one circle question, and ellipses are commonly tested in questions 35-45. While hyperbolas appear less frequently, they have been showing up more in recent years. Understanding these equations and how to graph them will give you a significant advantage.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">1. Circle Equations</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Circles are one of the most commonly tested conic sections. To answer circle questions efficiently, you need to know the equation for a circle and how to identify its center and radius.</p>', 1, '2025-10-14T00:11:25.024469+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (497fceb0-b993-4ccb-bb9d-d7b0c4b5050e, f6fc4e26-6e8b-4e77-95ab-14bb3ea14787, '<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Point-<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Slope</strong> Form: y — Vy = M(x — x)</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Distance = J (%1 — X%2)? + O41 — 2)?</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Integers are whole numbers (Ex: —4, 3,102).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Prime Numbers are integers that are only divisible by 1 and itself (Ex: 2,3,5,7,11...). Note that</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">1 is not a prime number and 2 1s the only prime even number.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Rational numbers are any number that can be expressed as a fraction (Ex: =, — ), Any integer</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">is also a rational number (Ex: —22, 3,600, 12).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Irrational numbers are any numbers that cannot be expressed as a fraction (Ex: 7, V5).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Undefined numbers are numbers with a zero in the denominator (Ex: =, a ~),</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Imaginary numbers are real numbers multiplied by the imaginary unit i (Ex: —3i, 87).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Greatest Common Factor: The greatest common factor of a set of numbers is the largest positive integer</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">that divides evenly into all numbers in the set with no remainder. For example, for the set of numbers 12,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">18, and 30, the greatest common factor Is 6.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Least Common Multiple: The least common multiple is the smallest positive integer that 1s divisible by all</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">numbers in the set. For example, the least common multiple of 2 and 3 is 6.</p>

