<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Do you prefer working with numbers or variables? We would guess your answer is numbers! On the ACT,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">some questions have many unknown variables and few or no numbers at all. Students often find these</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">questions more difficult. If you prefer to work with numbers, let’s work with numbers! With substitution, we</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">substitute simple numbers in for variables and solve the question using numbers instead of relying on more</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">complex algebra with variables.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Substitution can be done with these four steps:</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Pick a number for the variable(s) in the question.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Pick easy numbers...avoid using 0 and 1. Use 2, 3, 4 or other easy numbers. Use 10 for</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">percent problems, 10 or 20 for group size, etc.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Select different numbers for each variable. For example, if a question has an x and a y, pick</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Follow any rules in the question. For example, if a question says x is a number that is</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">negative and even, pick x = —2.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Write down the number(s) that you have picked.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Use your number(s) to work your way through the question and find your answer.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Plug your number(s) into the answer choices. The correct answer will be the one that matches</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Substitution may seem a bit confusing just reading the steps, so let’s take a look at some example questions to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">see how useful this technique can be.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 1: Jeremy has n boxes of candy bars. Each box contains m bars of candy. Jeremy has to sell</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">70% of his candy bars to make enough money for rent. Which of the following expresses the number of</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">candy bars Jeremy must sell in terms of m and n?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 70nm</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 0.7nm</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">let’s plug in numbers. We can say that Jeremy has 2 boxes of candy, so n = 2, and that each box contains 5</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">bars of candy, som = 5. With our numbers, Jeremy has a total of 10 candy bars. He needs to sell 70% to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">make enough money for rent, so we can find the total candy bars that he must sell by finding 70% of 10.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">With our numbers, Jeremy must sell 7 candy bars, so our answer is 7. Now, we can plug in the values we</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">selected for n and m into the answer choices and see which one is equal to 7. Here, we find that D works.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">None of the other answer choices are equal to 7 when we plug in our values for n and m. No matter what</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">numbers you pick for n and m, you will find that D is the answer.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 2: If cos (2x°) = a, which of the following must be true for all values of x, in degrees?</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A. sin(2x°)=a_</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. sin(x°+90°)=a_</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. cos(90°—2x°)=a _</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. sin(90° — 2x°) =a</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">x = 10°. First, we need to find out what a equals if x = 10°.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Now that we know what a equals, we can plug in x = 10° for the x-values in the answer choices to see which</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">is equal to 0.9397. Here, we can see how the correct answer choice of D works.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">sin(90° — 20°) = sin(70°) = 0.9397</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">This trick will work for any value of x that we pick. The answer is D. Note that since we are solving in</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">degrees, your calculator must be in degree mode. If you get a value other than cos(20) = 0.9397 when you</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">input cos(20) in your calculator, your calculator is in radian mode.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 3: If the length of a rectangle is tripled and the width is halved, how many times larger is the</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">area of the new rectangle than the area of the original rectangle?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 2</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 3</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 4</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">make the length 3 and the width 2. Now, we just follow the steps in the questions.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The length is tripled: 3(3) =9 The new length is 9.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The width is halved: 2(-) =1 The new widthis 1.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Next, we find the areas of the rectangles and compare. The new rectangle has an area of 9. The original</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">rectangle has an area of 6, so we find that the new rectangle is 1.5 times as large. The answer is A</p>

