<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">104. Taking Square Roots in Algebraic Equations</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">When solving an algebra question, you may need to find the value of a variable that is squared. For example,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">we need to take the square root of both sides to solve. Many students take the square root and get x = 3,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">which is WRONG! To take the square root properly, we need to use the following rule</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">When taking the square root of a squared variable (x*), add a + in front of the number.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">For the example equation above, we should solve using the following steps to solve properly.</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">105. Take square root of both sides.</h3>

