<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Two Solutions for Algebraic Expressions</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">For a challenge question, the ACT can also include an algebraic expression that has two solutions. For an</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">algebraic expression to have 2 solutions, the equation must either (1) have an x*-term or (2) have an</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">x-term inside absolute value bars.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Let’s say we are given the algebraic expression x* — 6 = —2. To solve, we could add 6 to both sides and</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Taking the square root of both sides we get.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">So, we get 2 solutions! Remember that in Chapter 7 (pg. 56) we learned that when we take the square root</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">of both sides with x2, we must put a + in front of the number.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Two Solutions with Absolute Value</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Let’s say we are given the expression |x| + 3 = 10. To solve, we subtract 3 from both sides and get</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">When we have a variable inside the absolute value bars, there will be 2 solutions. If you are not</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">familiar with this topic, we will learn more about algebra with absolute values bars in Chapter 18.</p>

