<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">A function is defined as a mathematical relationship between a variable x and the function f(x). For every</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">value of x, there is exactly one value of f(x). For any function, there will be an input, which appears as the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">term in the parentheses of a function, and an output, which will be the value that f(x) equals.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">In order to solve functions questions on the ACT, we first need to know where to properly plug in the input to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">we plug in the input for x. You are likely used to the input being a number, but the input can include variables</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">as well. No matter what the input is, we plug it in for the x in the equation:</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 1: If f(x) = 3Vx + 11, what is the value for f(25) ?</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 26</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 34</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 64</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">f(25) = 3V25 4-11 = 3(5) +11 =154+11 = 26</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 2: A function, f, is defined by f(x,y) = 4x — y?. What is the value of f (5, 2) ?</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 9</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 24</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">we are given a value for x and y. To solve, plug in 5 for x and 2 for y.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 3: If f(x) = — for what value of x does f(x) =5?</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 2</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 4</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">output for f(x) and solve for the input x.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Quite often, the ACT will ask you to solve composite functions. A composite function is a function that is</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">written inside of another function. We will use the examples below to learn how to solve composite functions</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 4: If f(x) = 3x + 10 and g(x) = x — 5, what is the value of f(g(8)) ?</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 9</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 29</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">composite function or (2) work inside out. Both methods are shown below.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Method #1 - Solve for the composite function: In this question, we want to solve for the function f(g(x)).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To do so, we plug the entire g(x) function in for the x in the f(x) function.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">f(g(x)) = 3( -—5) +10 = 3x-15+4+10 = 3x-5</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Now that we know the composite function f ( g (x)) = 3x — 5, we can plug in 8 for x and solve.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Method #2 - Work inside out: Rather than solve for the composite function, we can also work from the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">f(g(8)). To start, we can solve for g(8).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We now know that g(8) = 3, so we can simplify the function we are solving for.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Both of these methods work for any composite function questions on the ACT, so you should use the one that</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 5: If f(x) = 2x? — 7 and g(x) = x + 3, what is f(g(x —1))?</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A. 2x? +2</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 2x2 -3</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">this as a composite function. Both of the methods outlined in Example 4 will work to solve. Below, we will</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">use the inside out method. First, we can solve for g(x — 1):</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We now know that g(x — 1) = x + 2, so we can simplify what we are solving for.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">f(«+2) =2(« +2)? -—7 = 2007 4+4x44)-7 = 2x7 4+8x4+8-7 = 2x74+8x41</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">**Common Mistake to Avoid: Remember that (x + 2)? # x* + 4. You need to multiply out the term</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">because (x + 2)? is the same as (x + 2)(x + 2).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Do you know what (f ° g)(x) or (fg)(x) means? If not, you are not alone. Most students we work with see</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">these other function notations and are confused about what to do. No need to worry though! All of the other</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">function notations that can come up on test day are in the table below. If you memorize what these notations</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">mean, you will be prepared to solve any questions with them on test day.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 6: If f(x) = 2x? + 1 and g(x) = x? — 1, which of the following expressions represents</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 2x?2-1</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 2x*-1</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 2x*-x?-1</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To solve, we need to multiply these quadratics together by FOIL (First, Outer, Inner, Last). If you need to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">review how this works, you can go to Chapter 16.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">(fg)(x) = (2x? +1)(x* -1) = 2x*- 2x72? +x%-1= 2x4*-x%-1</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 7: Let (f ° g)(x) = (2x + 1)? — 3 and g(x) = 2x + 1. Which of the following expressions</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 2x2-—5</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. v2x+1+3</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">challenging to solve and normally appear in the last 10 questions of the test.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To solve this question, we first need to remember that (f ° g)(x) = f(g(x)). We also know that</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">g(x) = 2x + 1, so we can plug in 2x + 1 for g(x) and get</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The input of 2x + 1 is plugged in for x in the function f(x) we are trying to find. Since we know that</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">°g)(x) = (2x + 1)? — 3, we can replace 2x + 1 with x to work backwards and find f(x). We get</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Now that we know f (x), we can find (g ° f)(x). Again, remember that (g ° f)(x) is the same as g( f (x)).</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To solve, we need to plug f (x), which is x* — 3, into g(x)</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">When a function is graphed, the input, x, is on the x-axis and the output, f(x), is on the y-axis. Another</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">way to better understand how functions appear on a graph is to remember that for any linear function</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">When graphing a function f(x), you can think of f(x) as the y-coordinate and x as the x-coordinate. Using</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the input as x and the output as y, we can find points in the standard (x, y) plane and graph any function.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 8:</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The function f(x) is shown in the standard (x, y) coordinate plane above. What is the minimum value of</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. -1</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 6</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. 1</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the function above, the minimum value is where y = —2, so the answer is A.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">What if this question instead asked for the maximum value of the function? Well, now we just look for the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">highest point on the graph, which is at y = 6.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Easy right? For any questions asking for the minimum or maximum value of a function, you just need to look</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">at the graph and find the smallest or largest y-value.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 9:</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The function f(x) = 4 cos(7x) + 1 is graphed in the standard (x, y) coordinate plane above. How many</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">x-intercepts does the graph of the function have on the interval 0 << x <4?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. 2</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 3</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">function crosses the x-axis. We see the function crossing the x-axis 4 times, so the answer is D.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Another common type of common functions question will ask you about the domain or range of a function.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Domain: The set of all possible input, x, values to a function.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Range: The set of all output, y, values to a function.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">If you are looking at the graph of a function, the domain is all the x-values that appear on the graph and</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">the range is all the y-values that appear on the graph.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To see how this works, let’s find the domain and range of the graph below.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We see x-values on the graph from x = —1 to x = 3, so for the graph above the domain is {-1 < x < 3}.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Since the dots on the graph are solid, we include —1 and 3 in the domain and use the less than or equal to and</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">greater than or equal to signs. If the dots were open, the domain would instead use the greater than and less</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">than signs and would be {—1 < x < 3}. .</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We see y-values on the graph from y = —2 to y = 4, so for the graph above the range is {—2 < y < 4}.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 10:</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The graph of f(x) = 3sin(27x) — 3 is shown above. What is the range of f(x) ?</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">of f(x) is -—6 < y <0. The answer is A.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 11:</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">is shown above. What is the range of f(x) ?</p>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">A. fyly #1}</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. fyly #4}</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. {y| #0andy #1}</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">approaches but never crosses. We call this a horizontal asymptote at y = 1. Because there are no points</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">on the graph where y = 1, the range of the function will not include y = 1. All points above the horizontal</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">asymptotes y = 1 appear on the graph, but what about below?</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Do you see that open dot at the point (2,—2)? We call this point a hole in the graph. Holes occur when the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">numerator and denominator of a function both equal 0. If we plug in x = 2 to f(x), we will get f(2) = =.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We can also spot that there is going to be a hole at x = 2 because we see (x — 2) in the numerator and</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">denominator. When the same term appears in the numerator and denominator, it always creates a</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">hole. Holes in the graph are undefined and are never included in the domain.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">But a hole does not automatically mean the value is not included in the range, as there could be another point</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">with the y-value elsewhere on the graph. In the graph above, however, there is no point where y = 2, so it</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">is also not included in the range.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">As a result, we see that the function includes all y-values except at y = 1 (the horizontal asymptote) and</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">y = —2 (the hole). In fancy math terms, this would appear as {y|y # —2 and y ¥ 1}, which means all</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">values of y except y = —2 and y = 1. The answer is C.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Horizontal asymptotes are rarely tested on the ACT, but you should still know how to solve for them just in</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">case. If you need to review asymptotes, the rules for solving them are covered in Chapter 35.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Continuing to look at the graph in Example 11, you can see there is a vertical invisible line at x = 1 that the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">graph approaches but never crosses. There is no point on the graph when x = 1. We call this a vertical</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">asymptote at x = 1. Because there is no point on the graph where x = 1, the domain of the function will</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">not include x = 1. We will also cover the rules for vertical asymptotes in Chapter 35.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">There is also an open dot at x = 2. We call this point a hole in the graph. Holes are not included in the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">domain since there 1s no point where x = 2 on the graph. All other values for x appear on the graph, so the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">domain is all values of x except x # 1 and x # 2. Mathematically, the domain could be written as</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Vertical asymptotes occur when the denominator of a function is equal to 0. If we plug in x = 1 to</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">f(x), we get f(1) = =, which is undefined. Again, since vertical asymptotes are points where the function</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">is undefined, they are never included in the domain.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">What if you are not given a picture graph in the question? To solve for vertical asymptotes, you set the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">denominator equal to zero and solve. If there is a hole in the graph, such as the one at x = 2 in example</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">11, we cancel those terms. So for the graph in example 11, the only term left in the denominator is x — 1.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To find the vertical asymptote, we set x — 1 equal to 0 and solve.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">We see there is a vertical asymptote at x = 1. Even if we were not given the graph, we could easily solve</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">for any vertical asymptotes. Remember vertical asymptotes are points where the graph is undefined and are</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 12: The domain of f(x) = —— is the set of all real numbers EXCEPT:</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. —3</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. 2 and</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. —2 and</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">function is undefined. To make the function undefined, set the denominator equal to 0 and solve for x.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">f(x) is undefined when x = 2 and x = 3, so these points are not included in the domain of the function. If</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">we graphed f(x), we would see vertical asymptotes at x = 2 and x = 3. The answer is C.</p>

<h4 style="margin: 0 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 0.75rem; border-left: 4px solid #b91c1c; color: #000000; font-weight: 700;">Example 13: Two real-valued functions are defined as f(x) = Vx + 1 and g(x) = x — 3. What is the</h4>

<p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0.5rem 0;">
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">B. [3, 0)</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">C. [5, 0)</span><br>
<span style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, Georgia, serif;">D. [—©, co)</span><br>
</p>

<p style="margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem 0;"><strong>Solution:</strong></p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">Now, we need to learn how the domain is restricted with a square root. Values underneath a square root</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">must be greater than or equal to 0. Any value of x that makes the term underneath the square root negative</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">cannot be included in the domain. To find the domain with a square root, set the term underneath the</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">square root greater than or equal to zero and solve for x.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">The domain of f(g(x)) is x = 3. Written in interval notation, this is [ 3,00). The answer is B.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">To illustrate why the domain is restricted, let’s plug in x = 1, which is not part of the domain, to f(g(x))</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">You cannot have a negative term underneath the square root, so x = 1 has no real number output and</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">therefore cannot be included in the domain.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">If you need to review vertical and horizontal asymptotes or just want more practice, go to Chapter 35.</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">f~1(x), are rarely tested on the ACT, but they are pretty easy to solve, so let’s go</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">over them just in case you see an inverse functions question on test day. To find the inverse of any function,</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">switch the input x and the output f(x) and solve for f(x). Let’s see how this works in the example below.</p>

