INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (2e1fe75b-811a-4ac1-87c5-d606a2a5038e, f7071006-05ab-4162-9b7f-627535004bea, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: English
Topic: Building Complete Sentences
Lesson Key: sentence-structure
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Understanding <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">sentence structure</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">clauses</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">fragments</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">run-on sentences</strong> is essential for ACT English success. These concepts appear in 12-15 questions per test—that''s 20% of all English questions! This lesson will teach you how to identify complete sentences, recognize common errors like fragments and run-ons, and master the techniques to fix them quickly and confidently.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Independent and Dependent Clauses
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Every sentence is built from <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">clauses</strong>—groups of words containing a subject and verb. Understanding the difference between <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">independent clauses</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">dependent clauses</strong> is the foundation of sentence structure mastery.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Independent Clauses (Complete Thoughts)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
An <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">independent clause</strong> expresses a complete thought and can stand alone as a sentence. It must have both a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">subject</strong> (who or what) and a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">predicate</strong> (what the subject does). Examples: "The dog barked." "She studied all night." "They won the championship." Each of these can stand alone and makes complete sense.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Dependent Clauses (Incomplete Thoughts)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">dependent clause</strong> has a subject and verb but cannot stand alone because it begins with a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">subordinating conjunction</strong> (because, although, when, if, since, while, etc.). Examples: "Because the dog barked." "Although she studied all night." "When they won the championship." These leave you hanging—you need more information to complete the thought.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Common Subordinating Conjunctions
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Memorize these <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">subordinating conjunctions</strong> that create dependent clauses: after, although, as, because, before, even though, if, since, though, unless, until, when, whenever, where, whereas, wherever, while. If a clause starts with one of these words, it''s dependent and CANNOT stand alone as a complete sentence.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Combining Clauses Correctly
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A complete sentence needs at least one independent clause. You can combine independent and dependent clauses: "She passed the test because she studied." (independent + dependent). You can also have two independent clauses joined properly: "She studied, and she passed the test." Understanding these combinations is crucial for avoiding fragments and run-ons.
</p>

<!-- Example 1 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Sentence Fragments and How to Fix Them
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">sentence fragment</strong> is an incomplete sentence—it''s missing either a subject, a verb, or a complete thought. Fragments are one of the most common errors on the ACT English test. Learning to spot and fix them will significantly improve your score.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Missing Subject Fragments
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Some fragments lack a subject. Example: "Ran to the store." Who ran? The subject is missing. Fix: "She ran to the store." or "The children ran to the store." Always ask: Who or what is performing the action? If there''s no answer, you have a fragment.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Missing Verb Fragments
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Other fragments lack a complete verb. Example: "The student studying all night." This has a subject (student) but "studying" is a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">participle</strong>, not a complete verb. Fix: "The student was studying all night." or "The student studied all night." Watch for -ing words without helping verbs (is, was, has been, etc.).
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Dependent Clause Fragments
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The most common fragment is a dependent clause standing alone. Example: "Because she was tired." This has a subject (she) and verb (was) but it''s incomplete because of "because." Fix option 1: Attach it to an independent clause—"Because she was tired, she went to bed early." Fix option 2: Remove the subordinating conjunction—"She was tired."
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Phrase Fragments
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Phrases</strong> (groups of words without subject-verb combinations) cannot stand alone. Examples: "In the morning." "Running through the park." "To win the game." These are fragments. Fix them by attaching to a complete sentence: "In the morning, we ate breakfast." "Running through the park, she felt free." "To win the game, they practiced daily."
</p>

<!-- Example 2 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Run-On Sentences and Comma Splices
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">run-on sentence</strong> occurs when two independent clauses are joined incorrectly without proper punctuation or conjunctions. A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">comma splice</strong> is a specific type of run-on where two independent clauses are joined with only a comma. Both are serious errors that the ACT tests frequently.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Identifying Run-On Sentences
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Run-on example: "The concert was amazing the band played for three hours." This has two independent clauses ("The concert was amazing" and "the band played for three hours") jammed together with no separation. Comma splice example: "The concert was amazing, the band played for three hours." The comma alone is insufficient to join two independent clauses.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Fix #1: Period (Two Sentences)
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The simplest fix is to split the run-on into two separate sentences. "The concert was amazing. The band played for three hours." This works when the ideas are distinct. Use this fix when the clauses aren''t closely related or when you want to add emphasis by creating a shorter, punchier sentence.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Fix #2: Semicolon
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">semicolon</strong> can join closely related independent clauses. "The concert was amazing; the band played for three hours." Semicolons work best when the two clauses are closely connected in meaning. Think of the semicolon as saying "and here''s more related information."
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Fix #3: Comma + Coordinating Conjunction
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Use a comma plus a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">coordinating conjunction</strong> (FANBOYS: for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so). "The concert was amazing, and the band played for three hours." This is probably the most common fix. Remember: you need BOTH the comma AND the conjunction. Just a comma alone is a comma splice!
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Fix #4: Make One Clause Dependent
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Turn one independent clause into a dependent clause by adding a subordinating conjunction. "The concert was amazing because the band played for three hours." or "Although the band played for three hours, the concert was amazing." This fix works when one idea is the main point and the other provides supporting information.
</p>

<!-- Example 3 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Advanced Sentence Structures and Variety
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Beyond avoiding errors, effective writing uses varied sentence structures. The ACT tests your ability to recognize <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">simple</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">compound</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">complex</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">compound-complex</strong> sentences. Understanding these patterns helps you choose the most effective sentence structure.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Simple Sentences
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">simple sentence</strong> contains one independent clause. Examples: "The dog barked." "Maria and Jose studied chemistry and physics." Even with multiple subjects or verbs, it''s still simple if there''s only one clause. Simple sentences are direct and powerful—use them for emphasis or to state clear facts.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Compound Sentences
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">compound sentence</strong> contains two or more independent clauses joined by a coordinating conjunction (FANBOYS) or semicolon. Example: "She loves reading, but he prefers movies." Both clauses could stand alone. Compound sentences show equal relationships between ideas.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Complex Sentences
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">complex sentence</strong> contains one independent clause and at least one dependent clause. Example: "Because it was raining, we stayed inside." The dependent clause provides context or conditions. Complex sentences show how ideas relate in terms of cause, condition, time, or contrast.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Compound-Complex Sentences
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">compound-complex sentence</strong> contains two or more independent clauses AND at least one dependent clause. Example: "Although it was raining, we went to the park, and we had a great time." This structure combines multiple ideas with varying relationships. Use it when you need to express complex, interconnected thoughts.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Strategic Sentence Variety
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Good writing mixes sentence types for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">rhythm</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">emphasis</strong>. A string of only simple sentences sounds choppy. All compound-complex sentences feel dense. The ACT sometimes asks you to choose revisions that improve sentence variety. Balance is key: use simple sentences for impact, compound for equal ideas, complex for showing relationships, and compound-complex sparingly when truly needed.
</p>

<!-- Example 4 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Independent clauses can stand alone; dependent clauses cannot (they start with subordinating conjunctions)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Fragments are missing subjects, verbs, or complete thoughts—fix by adding missing parts or attaching to complete sentences
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Run-ons join two independent clauses incorrectly—fix with period, semicolon, comma+FANBOYS, or subordination
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Comma splices (comma alone between independent clauses) are always wrong—you need a conjunction too
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Simple = 1 independent; Compound = 2+ independent; Complex = 1 independent + 1+ dependent
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Vary sentence types for better rhythm—mix simple, compound, and complex sentences strategically
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T19:05:23.471367+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (e320c237-310b-4255-9a97-c3052adcca49, f7167bcc-2b4d-497a-9f9a-7e83750e7dc6, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: English
Topic: Word Choice and Precision
Lesson Key: word-choice
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Word choice questions</strong> test whether you can select the most <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">precise</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">appropriate</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">contextually accurate</strong> word for the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ACT English Test</strong>. These questions require you to distinguish between commonly confused words (affect/effect, accept/except), choose words that match the passage''s tone and style, and select the most specific and vivid vocabulary. Appearing 5-8 times per test, word choice questions reward students who read carefully and understand subtle differences in meaning and connotation.
</p>


<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: MAIN CONTENT (4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Commonly Confused Words
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The ACT frequently tests pairs or groups of words that sound similar but have different meanings. Knowing these distinctions is essential for quick, accurate answers.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Affect vs. Effect
</h4>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">affect</strong> (verb) = to influence or change
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → The weather <strong>affected</strong> our travel plans.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">effect</strong> (noun) = a result or consequence
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → The <strong>effect</strong> of the storm was devastating.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Accept vs. Except
</h4>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #16a34a;">accept</strong> (verb) = to receive or agree to
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #064e3b; font-style: italic;">
    → She <strong>accepted</strong> the award graciously.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #16a34a;">except</strong> (preposition) = excluding, but not
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #064e3b; font-style: italic;">
    → Everyone came <strong>except</strong> John.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Then vs. Than
</h4>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fffbeb;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #92400e;">then</strong> = at that time, next
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #78350f; font-style: italic;">
    → We ate dinner, <strong>then</strong> watched a movie.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #92400e;">than</strong> = comparison word
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #78350f; font-style: italic;">
    → She is taller <strong>than</strong> her brother.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
More Commonly Confused Pairs
</h4>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong>allusion</strong> (reference) vs. <strong>illusion</strong> (false impression)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong>complement</strong> (complete) vs. <strong>compliment</strong> (praise)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong>elicit</strong> (draw out) vs. <strong>illicit</strong> (illegal)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong>emigrate</strong> (leave a country) vs. <strong>immigrate</strong> (enter a country)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong>ensure</strong> (make certain) vs. <strong>insure</strong> (protect financially)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong>farther</strong> (physical distance) vs. <strong>further</strong> (metaphorical extent)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong>imply</strong> (suggest) vs. <strong>infer</strong> (conclude)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong>lose</strong> (misplace) vs. <strong>loose</strong> (not tight)
  </p>
</div>


<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Precision and Specificity
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The ACT prefers specific, precise words over vague, general ones. When choosing between words with similar meanings, select the one that most accurately conveys the intended idea.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Vague vs. Precise Verbs
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Specific action verbs create clearer, more vivid sentences than generic verbs.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Vague:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">The scientist <strong>did</strong> an experiment.</span>
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Precise:</span> The scientist <strong>conducted</strong> an experiment.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Choosing the Most Accurate Word
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Context determines which word is most appropriate. Consider subtle differences in meaning.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong>Example context:</strong> "The policy will _____ everyone equally."
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    • <span style="color: #dc2626;">✗</span> <strong>effect</strong> (noun, doesn''t fit)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    • <span style="color: #16a34a;">✓</span> <strong>affect</strong> (verb, influences everyone)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    • <span style="color: #dc2626;">✗</span> <strong>impact</strong> (possible but less precise for policy)
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Avoiding Overly Casual or Formal Language
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Match your word choice to the passage''s tone. Academic passages require formal vocabulary; personal narratives allow more casual language—but never slang.
</p>


<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Tone and Connotation
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Words with similar definitions can have different connotations—emotional associations or implied judgments. The ACT tests whether you can choose words that match the passage''s intended tone.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Positive, Negative, and Neutral Connotations
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Consider whether the passage requires a positive, negative, or neutral word.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Describing someone who spends little money:</strong>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #064e3b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a;">✓ Positive:</span> <strong>thrifty</strong>, <strong>economical</strong>, <strong>frugal</strong>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b;">
    → Neutral: <strong>careful</strong> with money
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #7f1d1d;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626;">✗ Negative:</span> <strong>cheap</strong>, <strong>stingy</strong>, <strong>miserly</strong>
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Matching Passage Tone
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Read surrounding sentences to determine the passage''s overall tone before selecting a word.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #16a34a;">If the passage is celebratory:</strong> Choose positive words like "triumphant," "remarkable," "outstanding"
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #16a34a;">If the passage is critical:</strong> Choose words like "problematic," "flawed," "insufficient"
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #16a34a;">If the passage is objective/academic:</strong> Choose neutral words like "significant," "notable," "substantial"
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Intensity and Degree
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Some words convey stronger or weaker degrees of the same quality. Choose the intensity that fits the context.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fffbeb;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #92400e;">Describing anger (weak → strong):</strong>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #78350f;">
    annoyed → frustrated → angry → furious → enraged
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #92400e;">Describing size (small → large):</strong>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #78350f;">
    tiny → small → moderate → large → enormous → gigantic
  </p>
</div>


<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Context Clues and Strategic Reading
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When unsure about word choice, use context clues from surrounding sentences to determine which word fits best. The passage itself often provides hints about the correct answer.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Reading Before and After
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Always read at least one sentence before and after the underlined word to understand context.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Strategy:</strong>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b;">
    1. Read the sentence with the underlined word
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b;">
    2. Read the sentence before it
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b;">
    3. Read the sentence after it
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b;">
    4. Determine the overall tone and meaning
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b;">
    5. Eliminate words that don''t fit the context
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Looking for Parallel Structure Clues
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Sometimes nearby words provide clues about the appropriate word choice through parallelism or contrast.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #16a34a;">Example:</strong> "The new policy was both innovative and _____."
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #064e3b;">
    → Look for another positive adjective to match "innovative"
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #064e3b;">
    → Choose: "effective," "successful," "practical" (not "controversial" or "risky")
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Eliminating Obviously Wrong Answers
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Use process of elimination to narrow choices before making a final decision.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #dc2626;">Eliminate answers that:</strong>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #7f1d1d;">
    • Are the wrong part of speech (noun when you need a verb)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #7f1d1d;">
    • Have completely wrong meanings
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #7f1d1d;">
    • Don''t match the passage''s tone (too formal/informal)
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #7f1d1d;">
    • Create illogical or contradictory meaning
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
When Multiple Answers Seem Correct
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
If several options seem grammatically correct and contextually appropriate, choose the most precise and specific word.
</p>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background-color: #fef3c7; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b;">
<strong style="color: #92400e;">Final Tip:</strong> Trust your reading instincts. If a word "sounds wrong" in context, it probably is. Read the sentence aloud mentally with each answer choice to hear which flows best.
</p>


<!-- ========================================
     HIDDEN H3 SEPARATOR
     (Creates visual space before Key Takeaways)
     ======================================== -->
<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 4rem 0 0 0; padding: 0; height: 0; overflow: hidden;">Hidden Separator</h3>


<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Commonly confused words: Know the differences—affect (verb, influence) vs. effect (noun, result); accept (receive) vs. except (excluding); then (time) vs. than (comparison); imply (suggest) vs. infer (conclude)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Precision: Choose specific, accurate words over vague, general ones; prefer "conducted an experiment" over "did an experiment"; select words that most precisely convey the intended meaning in context
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Tone and connotation: Match word choice to passage tone; distinguish between positive (thrifty), neutral (careful), and negative (cheap) connotations; consider intensity and degree (annoyed vs. furious)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Context clues: Read sentences before and after the underlined word; look for parallel structure clues in nearby words; eliminate answers that are wrong part of speech or have wrong meanings
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Strategy: Trust your reading instincts—if a word sounds wrong in context, it probably is; when multiple answers seem correct, choose the most precise and specific option; read sentence mentally with each choice to hear which flows best
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-13T19:21:09.623307+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (82ee78bb-566c-4096-a331-6df376cbcbea, fc066500-ce4b-4270-8580-0a2533e4cb32, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: Math
Topic: Vectors
Lesson Key: 7.4
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Understanding <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">vectors</strong> provides powerful tools for representing quantities with both <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">magnitude</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">direction</strong>. Unlike <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">scalars</strong> (numbers with only magnitude), vectors are essential for describing displacement, velocity, and force. This lesson covers <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">vector operations</strong> (addition, subtraction, scalar multiplication), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">component form</strong>, and the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">dot product</strong>. While vectors appear infrequently on the ACT (0-1 questions), mastering them demonstrates advanced mathematical thinking and prepares you for college-level physics and engineering.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Vector Basics and Notation
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">vector</strong> is a quantity with both magnitude (size) and direction. Vectors are typically represented by arrows, where the length represents magnitude and the arrow direction represents the direction. In <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">component form</strong>, a 2D vector is written as ⟨a, b⟩ or as ai + bj, where a is the horizontal component and b is the vertical component. The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">magnitude</strong> (or length) of vector v is denoted |v| or ||v||.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Vector Notation and Representation
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Common notations for vectors:</strong>
<br><br>
• Bold lowercase: <strong>v</strong>, <strong>u</strong>, <strong>w</strong>
<br>
• Arrow notation: v⃗, u⃗, w⃗
<br>
• Component form: ⟨3, 4⟩ or 3i + 4j
<br>
• Column matrix: [3]
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[4]
<br><br>
<strong>Position vector:</strong> Vector from origin to point (a, b)
<br>
Position vector to (3, 4) is ⟨3, 4⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Zero vector:</strong> ⟨0, 0⟩ has magnitude 0 and no specific direction
<br><br>
<strong>Unit vector:</strong> Vector with magnitude 1
<br>
Standard unit vectors: i = ⟨1, 0⟩ (horizontal), j = ⟨0, 1⟩ (vertical)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Finding Vector Components
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Given initial point A(x₁, y₁) and terminal point B(x₂, y₂):</strong>
<br>
Vector AB⃗ = ⟨x₂ - x₁, y₂ - y₁⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Example 1:</strong> Find vector from A(1, 2) to B(5, 7)
<br>
AB⃗ = ⟨5 - 1, 7 - 2⟩ = ⟨4, 5⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Example 2:</strong> Find vector from C(-3, 4) to D(2, -1)
<br>
CD⃗ = ⟨2 - (-3), -1 - 4⟩ = ⟨5, -5⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Example 3:</strong> Find vector from origin to P(6, -8)
<br>
OP⃗ = ⟨6 - 0, -8 - 0⟩ = ⟨6, -8⟩
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Magnitude (Length) of a Vector
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> For v = ⟨a, b⟩, magnitude |v| = √(a² + b²)
<br>
This is the distance formula/Pythagorean theorem
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example 1:</strong> Find |⟨3, 4⟩|
<br>
|v| = √(3² + 4²) = √(9 + 16) = √25 = 5
<br><br>
<strong>Example 2:</strong> Find |⟨-5, 12⟩|
<br>
|v| = √((-5)² + 12²) = √(25 + 144) = √169 = 13
<br><br>
<strong>Example 3:</strong> Find |⟨6, -8⟩|
<br>
|v| = √(6² + (-8)²) = √(36 + 64) = √100 = 10
<br><br>
<strong>Note:</strong> These are the 3-4-5, 5-12-13, and 6-8-10 Pythagorean triples!
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Direction Angle of a Vector
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Direction angle θ:</strong> Angle measured counterclockwise from positive x-axis
<br><br>
<strong>Formula:</strong> tan(θ) = b/a for vector ⟨a, b⟩
<br>
So θ = tan⁻¹(b/a)
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Find direction angle of ⟨3, 3⟩
<br>
tan(θ) = 3/3 = 1
<br>
θ = tan⁻¹(1) = 45°
<br><br>
<strong>Important:</strong> Must consider quadrant!
<br>
• Quadrant I: θ as calculated
<br>
• Quadrant II: θ = 180° - |calculated angle|
<br>
• Quadrant III: θ = 180° + |calculated angle|
<br>
• Quadrant IV: θ = 360° - |calculated angle|
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 1: Vector Components
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    What is the magnitude of the vector from point (2, -3) to point (8, 5)?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> 6</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> 8</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> 10</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> 14</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> 100</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Find vector components</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">v = ⟨8 - 2, 5 - (-3)⟩ = ⟨6, 8⟩</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Find magnitude</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">|v| = √(6² + 8²) = √(36 + 64) = √100 = 10</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: C</strong> — Use distance formula for magnitude!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Vector Operations
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Vectors can be <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">added</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">subtracted</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">multiplied by scalars</strong>. Vector addition follows the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">parallelogram rule</strong> or <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">tip-to-tail method</strong> geometrically, and component-wise algebraically. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Scalar multiplication</strong> changes the magnitude and potentially reverses the direction (if scalar is negative) without changing the orientation. Understanding these operations is essential for physics applications and geometric transformations.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Vector Addition
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Component-wise addition:</strong> ⟨a₁, b₁⟩ + ⟨a₂, b₂⟩ = ⟨a₁ + a₂, b₁ + b₂⟩
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example 1:</strong> ⟨3, 4⟩ + ⟨2, -1⟩
<br>
= ⟨3 + 2, 4 + (-1)⟩
<br>
= ⟨5, 3⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Example 2:</strong> ⟨-2, 5⟩ + ⟨7, -3⟩
<br>
= ⟨-2 + 7, 5 + (-3)⟩
<br>
= ⟨5, 2⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Geometric interpretation (tip-to-tail):</strong>
<br>
Place tail of second vector at tip of first vector
<br>
The sum vector goes from tail of first to tip of second
<br><br>
<strong>Properties:</strong>
<br>
• Commutative: u + v = v + u
<br>
• Associative: (u + v) + w = u + (v + w)
<br>
• Identity: v + 0 = v
<br>
• Inverse: v + (-v) = 0
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Vector Subtraction
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Component-wise subtraction:</strong> ⟨a₁, b₁⟩ - ⟨a₂, b₂⟩ = ⟨a₁ - a₂, b₁ - b₂⟩
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example 1:</strong> ⟨7, 8⟩ - ⟨3, 2⟩
<br>
= ⟨7 - 3, 8 - 2⟩
<br>
= ⟨4, 6⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Example 2:</strong> ⟨-1, 4⟩ - ⟨5, -2⟩
<br>
= ⟨-1 - 5, 4 - (-2)⟩
<br>
= ⟨-6, 6⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Alternative:</strong> u - v = u + (-v)
<br>
Subtract by adding the opposite vector
<br><br>
<strong>Geometric interpretation:</strong>
<br>
u - v is the vector from tip of v to tip of u
<br>
(When both start at same point)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Scalar Multiplication
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Multiply each component by scalar:</strong> k⟨a, b⟩ = ⟨ka, kb⟩
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example 1:</strong> 3⟨2, -4⟩
<br>
= ⟨3·2, 3·(-4)⟩
<br>
= ⟨6, -12⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Example 2:</strong> -2⟨5, 3⟩
<br>
= ⟨-2·5, -2·3⟩
<br>
= ⟨-10, -6⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Effect on magnitude:</strong>
<br>
|kv| = |k| · |v|
<br>
Scalar multiplication scales the magnitude by |k|
<br><br>
<strong>Effect on direction:</strong>
<br>
• k > 0: Same direction as original
<br>
• k < 0: Opposite direction
<br>
• k = 0: Zero vector (no direction)
<br><br>
<strong>Properties:</strong>
<br>
• k(u + v) = ku + kv
<br>
• (k + m)v = kv + mv
<br>
• k(mv) = (km)v
<br>
• 1v = v
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Unit Vectors
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Unit vector:</strong> Vector with magnitude 1
<br><br>
<strong>To find unit vector in direction of v:</strong>
<br>
u = v / |v| = (1/|v|) · v
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> Find unit vector in direction of ⟨3, 4⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Find magnitude
<br>
|v| = √(3² + 4²) = √25 = 5
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Divide by magnitude
<br>
u = (1/5)⟨3, 4⟩ = ⟨3/5, 4/5⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Verify:</strong> |u| = √((3/5)² + (4/5)²) = √(9/25 + 16/25) = √(25/25) = 1 ✓
<br><br>
<strong>Standard unit vectors:</strong>
<br>
i = ⟨1, 0⟩ (points right)
<br>
j = ⟨0, 1⟩ (points up)
<br>
Any vector ⟨a, b⟩ = ai + bj
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 2: Vector Operations
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    If u = ⟨4, -3⟩ and v = ⟨-1, 5⟩, what is 2u - v?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> ⟨7, -11⟩</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> ⟨9, -11⟩</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> ⟨7, -1⟩</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> ⟨9, -1⟩</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> ⟨3, 2⟩</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Calculate 2u</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">2u = 2⟨4, -3⟩ = ⟨8, -6⟩</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Subtract v</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">2u - v = ⟨8, -6⟩ - ⟨-1, 5⟩ = ⟨8-(-1), -6-5⟩ = ⟨9, -11⟩</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: G</strong> — Scalar multiply first, then subtract components!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Dot Product and Angles
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">dot product</strong> (or scalar product) of two vectors produces a scalar (number) rather than another vector. Written as u · v, it equals the sum of products of corresponding components. The dot product has important geometric interpretations: it equals |u||v|cos(θ) where θ is the angle between vectors. This allows us to find <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">angles between vectors</strong>, test for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">perpendicularity</strong> (dot product = 0), and find <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">projections</strong>.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Calculating the Dot Product
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Formula:</strong> ⟨a₁, b₁⟩ · ⟨a₂, b₂⟩ = a₁a₂ + b₁b₂
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example 1:</strong> ⟨3, 4⟩ · ⟨2, 5⟩
<br>
= (3)(2) + (4)(5)
<br>
= 6 + 20
<br>
= 26
<br><br>
<strong>Example 2:</strong> ⟨-1, 6⟩ · ⟨4, 2⟩
<br>
= (-1)(4) + (6)(2)
<br>
= -4 + 12
<br>
= 8
<br><br>
<strong>Example 3:</strong> ⟨5, -3⟩ · ⟨2, -7⟩
<br>
= (5)(2) + (-3)(-7)
<br>
= 10 + 21
<br>
= 31
<br><br>
<strong>Note:</strong> The dot product is a scalar, not a vector!
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Properties of the Dot Product
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Key properties:</strong>
<br><br>
1. <strong>Commutative:</strong> u · v = v · u
<br>
2. <strong>Distributive:</strong> u · (v + w) = u · v + u · w
<br>
3. <strong>Scalar multiplication:</strong> (ku) · v = k(u · v) = u · (kv)
<br>
4. <strong>With itself:</strong> v · v = |v|²
<br>
5. <strong>Zero vector:</strong> 0 · v = 0
<br>
6. <strong>Unit vectors:</strong> i · i = 1, j · j = 1, i · j = 0
<br><br>
<strong>Example using property 4:</strong>
<br>
v = ⟨3, 4⟩
<br>
v · v = (3)(3) + (4)(4) = 9 + 16 = 25 = |v|²
<br>
So |v| = √25 = 5 ✓
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Geometric Interpretation and Angles
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0;">
<strong>Angle formula:</strong> u · v = |u||v|cos(θ)
<br>
Therefore: cos(θ) = (u · v) / (|u||v|)
</p>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Example:</strong> Find angle between u = ⟨3, 4⟩ and v = ⟨0, 5⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Calculate dot product
<br>
u · v = (3)(0) + (4)(5) = 0 + 20 = 20
<br><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Find magnitudes
<br>
|u| = √(9 + 16) = 5
<br>
|v| = √(0 + 25) = 5
<br><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Apply formula
<br>
cos(θ) = 20 / (5 · 5) = 20/25 = 4/5 = 0.8
<br>
θ = cos⁻¹(0.8) ≈ 36.87°
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Perpendicular (Orthogonal) Vectors
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Perpendicular vectors have dot product = 0</strong>
<br>
(Because cos(90°) = 0)
<br><br>
<strong>Test:</strong> u ⊥ v if and only if u · v = 0
<br><br>
<strong>Example 1:</strong> Are ⟨2, 3⟩ and ⟨-6, 4⟩ perpendicular?
<br>
Dot product: (2)(-6) + (3)(4) = -12 + 12 = 0 ✓
<br>
Yes, they are perpendicular!
<br><br>
<strong>Example 2:</strong> Are ⟨1, 2⟩ and ⟨3, -1⟩ perpendicular?
<br>
Dot product: (1)(3) + (2)(-1) = 3 - 2 = 1 ≠ 0
<br>
No, they are not perpendicular
<br><br>
<strong>Finding perpendicular vector:</strong>
<br>
If v = ⟨a, b⟩, then ⟨-b, a⟩ and ⟨b, -a⟩ are perpendicular to v
<br>
Example: ⟨3, 4⟩ ⊥ ⟨-4, 3⟩ (verify: 3(-4) + 4(3) = -12 + 12 = 0 ✓)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 3: Dot Product
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    Vectors u = ⟨6, 8⟩ and v = ⟨-4, 3⟩. Are these vectors perpendicular?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>A)</strong> Yes, because their dot product is 0</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>B)</strong> Yes, because their dot product is 1</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>C)</strong> No, because their dot product is 0</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>D)</strong> No, because their dot product is not 0</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>E)</strong> Cannot be determined</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Calculate dot product:</strong></p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">u · v = (6)(-4) + (8)(3) = -24 + 24 = 0</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Since dot product = 0, vectors are perpendicular</strong></p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: A</strong> — Dot product = 0 means perpendicular!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Applications of Vectors
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Vectors have numerous practical applications in physics, engineering, and computer graphics. <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Force vectors</strong> combine to produce net force, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">velocity vectors</strong> describe motion with both speed and direction, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">displacement vectors</strong> represent changes in position. Understanding how to resolve vectors into components, combine multiple vectors, and use vectors to model real-world situations demonstrates deep mathematical understanding and prepares you for STEM fields.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Resolving Vectors into Components
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Given magnitude |v| and direction angle θ:</strong>
<br>
Horizontal component: vₓ = |v| cos(θ)
<br>
Vertical component: vᵧ = |v| sin(θ)
<br>
Vector: v = ⟨|v| cos(θ), |v| sin(θ)⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Example:</strong> A force of 50 N acts at 30° above horizontal. Find components.
<br><br>
<strong>Horizontal component:</strong>
<br>
Fₓ = 50 cos(30°) = 50 · (√3/2) ≈ 43.3 N
<br><br>
<strong>Vertical component:</strong>
<br>
Fᵧ = 50 sin(30°) = 50 · (1/2) = 25 N
<br><br>
<strong>Vector form:</strong> F ≈ ⟨43.3, 25⟩ N
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Combining Multiple Vectors
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Problem:</strong> Three forces act on an object:
<br>
F₁ = 10 N east
<br>
F₂ = 15 N north
<br>
F₃ = 5 N west
<br>
Find the net (resultant) force.
<br><br>
<strong>Solution using components:</strong>
<br>
Use east as positive x, north as positive y
<br><br>
F₁ = ⟨10, 0⟩
<br>
F₂ = ⟨0, 15⟩
<br>
F₃ = ⟨-5, 0⟩
<br><br>
<strong>Net force:</strong>
<br>
F_net = F₁ + F₂ + F₃
<br>
= ⟨10, 0⟩ + ⟨0, 15⟩ + ⟨-5, 0⟩
<br>
= ⟨5, 15⟩ N
<br><br>
<strong>Magnitude:</strong> |F_net| = √(5² + 15²) = √(25 + 225) = √250 ≈ 15.8 N
<br>
<strong>Direction:</strong> tan(θ) = 15/5 = 3, so θ = tan⁻¹(3) ≈ 71.6° north of east
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Navigation and Displacement
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Problem:</strong> A ship sails 30 km east, then 40 km north. What is the ship''s displacement from its starting point?
<br><br>
<strong>First leg:</strong> d₁ = ⟨30, 0⟩ km
<br>
<strong>Second leg:</strong> d₂ = ⟨0, 40⟩ km
<br><br>
<strong>Total displacement:</strong>
<br>
d = d₁ + d₂ = ⟨30, 0⟩ + ⟨0, 40⟩ = ⟨30, 40⟩ km
<br><br>
<strong>Distance from start:</strong>
<br>
|d| = √(30² + 40²) = √(900 + 1600) = √2500 = 50 km
<br><br>
<strong>Direction:</strong>
<br>
tan(θ) = 40/30 = 4/3
<br>
θ = tan⁻¹(4/3) ≈ 53.1° north of east
<br><br>
<strong>Note:</strong> This is a 3-4-5 Pythagorean triple scaled by 10!
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Velocity and Relative Motion
</h4>

<div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0;">
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0;">
<strong>Problem:</strong> A plane flies at 200 mph heading due north. A wind blows from the west at 50 mph. What is the plane''s actual velocity?
<br><br>
<strong>Plane velocity (in still air):</strong> v_plane = ⟨0, 200⟩ mph
<br>
<strong>Wind velocity:</strong> v_wind = ⟨50, 0⟩ mph (from west means toward east)
<br><br>
<strong>Actual velocity:</strong>
<br>
v_actual = v_plane + v_wind = ⟨0, 200⟩ + ⟨50, 0⟩ = ⟨50, 200⟩ mph
<br><br>
<strong>Ground speed:</strong>
<br>
|v_actual| = √(50² + 200²) = √(2500 + 40000) = √42500 ≈ 206.2 mph
<br><br>
<strong>Actual heading:</strong>
<br>
tan(θ) = 200/50 = 4
<br>
θ = tan⁻¹(4) ≈ 76.0° from east (or 14.0° east of north)
</p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Example 4: Vector Applications
</h4>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 12px; box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1); margin: 1rem 0 2rem 0; border: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
  <p style="font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 1rem 0; font-weight: 500;">
    A person walks 12 meters north, then 5 meters east. How far is the person from the starting point?
  </p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>F)</strong> 7 meters</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>G)</strong> 13 meters</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>H)</strong> 17 meters</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>J)</strong> 119 meters</p>
  <p style="font-family: ''Times New Roman'', Times, serif; font-size: 15px; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>K)</strong> 144 meters</p>
  <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1.25rem; border-top: 2px solid #f59e0b;">
    <p style="font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0; font-weight: 600; color: #92400e;">Solution:</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Displacement vector:</strong> d = ⟨5, 12⟩ meters</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;"><strong>Distance from start:</strong></p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.5rem 0; color: #000000;">|d| = √(5² + 12²) = √(25 + 144) = √169 = 13 meters</p>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; color: #000000;"><strong style="color: #15803d;">Answer: G</strong> — Use Pythagorean theorem (5-12-13 triple)!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Vectors have both magnitude and direction; scalars have only magnitude
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Component form: v = ⟨a, b⟩ or ai + bj where a is horizontal, b is vertical
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Magnitude: |⟨a, b⟩| = √(a² + b²) using Pythagorean theorem
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Add/subtract vectors component-wise: ⟨a₁, b₁⟩ ± ⟨a₂, b₂⟩ = ⟨a₁ ± a₂, b₁ ± b₂⟩
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Scalar multiplication: k⟨a, b⟩ = ⟨ka, kb⟩ scales magnitude by |k|
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Unit vector in direction of v: u = v/|v| has magnitude 1
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Dot product: ⟨a₁, b₁⟩ · ⟨a₂, b₂⟩ = a₁a₂ + b₁b₂ (produces a scalar)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Perpendicular vectors: u ⊥ v if and only if u · v = 0
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Angle between vectors: cos(θ) = (u · v) / (|u||v|)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Applications: combine forces/velocities by adding vectors; find resultant magnitude using Pythagorean theorem
  </li>
</ul>
', 0, '2025-10-16T01:11:48.689902+00:00', NOW());
INSERT INTO section_content (id, section_id, content, order_index, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (08fab3ed-d203-40a3-b447-8fb09ffcef0e, fcdcada8-a521-40d2-9c3d-a4d1a737bbb5, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v3.0
Subject: English
Topic: Misplaced and Dangling Modifiers
Lesson Key: modifiers
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING PARAGRAPH
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
<strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Modifier questions</strong> test one of the most logical concepts on the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ACT English Test</strong>: modifying phrases and clauses must be placed next to the words they describe. When modifiers are misplaced or dangling, sentences become illogical or unintentionally humorous. The ACT tests three main modifier issues: <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">misplaced modifiers</strong> (placed too far from what they modify), <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">dangling modifiers</strong> (missing the word they should modify), and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">squinting modifiers</strong> (unclear which word they modify). Once you learn to identify what each modifier describes and place it correctly, these questions become straightforward.
</p>


<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: MAIN CONTENT (4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Understanding Modifiers
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A modifier is a word, phrase, or clause that describes, limits, or adds detail to another word. Modifiers include adjectives, adverbs, prepositional phrases, participial phrases, and various clause types. The fundamental rule: place modifiers as close as possible to the words they modify.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Types of Modifiers
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Understanding the different types of modifiers helps you spot modifier errors on the ACT.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Adjective:</strong> The <strong style="color: #2563eb;">red</strong> car is fast. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(modifies "car")</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Adverb:</strong> She ran <strong style="color: #2563eb;">quickly</strong>. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(modifies "ran")</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Prepositional phrase:</strong> The book <strong style="color: #2563eb;">on the table</strong> is mine. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(modifies "book")</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Participial phrase:</strong> <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Running down the street</strong>, John tripped. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(modifies "John")</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Relative clause:</strong> The student <strong style="color: #2563eb;">who studied hard</strong> passed. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(modifies "student")</span>
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
The Proximity Principle
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Place modifiers next to what they modify. The farther away a modifier is from its target, the more likely confusion will occur.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Clear:</span> I <strong style="color: #16a34a;">nearly</strong> read the entire book yesterday.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #064e3b; font-style: italic;">
    → "Nearly" modifies "read" (almost read it)
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Confusing:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">I read nearly the entire book yesterday.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → "Nearly" incorrectly seems to modify "entire" (almost entire?)
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Introductory Modifying Phrases
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When a phrase begins a sentence and modifies the subject, the subject must immediately follow the comma. This is the most common modifier pattern tested on the ACT.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Correct:</span> <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Exhausted from the long hike</strong>, <strong style="text-decoration: underline;">Maria</strong> went straight to bed.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → "Exhausted from the long hike" correctly modifies "Maria"
  </p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background-color: #fef3c7; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b;">
<strong style="color: #92400e;">Golden Rule:</strong> Whatever comes immediately after the comma must be what the opening phrase describes.
</p>


<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Misplaced Modifiers
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A misplaced modifier is positioned too far from the word it modifies, creating confusion or unintentional meaning. The modifier exists and has a logical target in the sentence, but poor placement makes the sentence unclear or illogical.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Misplaced Adjective Phrases
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Adjective phrases should be placed immediately after the nouns they modify.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Misplaced:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">The dog caught the frisbee running across the yard.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → This says the frisbee was running across the yard
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Correct:</span> <strong style="color: #16a34a;">Running across the yard</strong>, the dog caught the frisbee.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Correct:</span> The dog, <strong style="color: #16a34a;">running across the yard</strong>, caught the frisbee.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Misplaced Adverb Modifiers
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Words like "only," "almost," "nearly," "just," "even," and "merely" should be placed immediately before the word they modify. Moving these words changes the sentence meaning.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    I <strong style="color: #2563eb;">only</strong> told Maria the secret. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(I didn''t tell anyone else)</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    I told <strong style="color: #2563eb;">only</strong> Maria the secret. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(Maria was the only person)</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    I told Maria <strong style="color: #2563eb;">only</strong> the secret. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(the secret and nothing else)</span>
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Misplaced:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">She nearly spent $500 on textbooks.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → Did she nearly spend it, or spend nearly $500?
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Correct:</span> She spent <strong style="color: #16a34a;">nearly</strong> $500 on textbooks.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Limiting Modifiers and Placement
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Limiting modifiers (only, just, merely, simply, even, almost, nearly) are precise. Their position dramatically affects meaning.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Only</strong> John passed the test. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(no one else passed)</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    John <strong style="color: #2563eb;">only</strong> passed the test. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(he passed but didn''t excel)</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    John passed <strong style="color: #2563eb;">only</strong> the test. <span style="color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">(he passed the test but nothing else)</span>
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Squinting Modifiers
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A squinting modifier is positioned between two words and could logically modify either one, creating ambiguity.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Squinting:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">Students who practice regularly often improve their scores.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → Does "often" modify "practice" or "improve"?
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Clear:</span> Students who practice <strong style="color: #16a34a;">often</strong> regularly improve their scores.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Clear:</span> Students who regularly practice <strong style="color: #16a34a;">often</strong> improve their scores.
  </p>
</div>


<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Dangling Modifiers
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
A dangling modifier occurs when the word it''s supposed to modify is missing from the sentence entirely. This is the most serious modifier error and appears frequently on the ACT. Dangling modifiers often create illogical or humorous meanings.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Identifying Dangling Modifiers
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
When an introductory phrase modifies a subject, that subject must appear immediately after the comma. If a different noun appears, the modifier dangles.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Dangling:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">Walking to school, the rain started pouring.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → This says the rain was walking to school; who was walking?
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Correct:</span> <strong style="color: #16a34a;">Walking to school</strong>, <strong style="text-decoration: underline;">I</strong> got caught in the pouring rain.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Correct:</span> <strong style="color: #16a34a;">While I was walking to school</strong>, the rain started pouring.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Dangling Participial Phrases
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Participial phrases (-ing or -ed verb forms) at the beginning of sentences must modify the subject that follows.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Dangling:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">Excited about the concert, my ticket was in my hand.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → The ticket was excited? Who was excited?
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Correct:</span> <strong style="color: #16a34a;">Excited about the concert</strong>, <strong style="text-decoration: underline;">I</strong> held my ticket in my hand.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Dangling Infinitive Phrases
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Infinitive phrases (to + verb) that begin sentences must have a clear actor in the main clause.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Dangling:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">To improve her grade, extra credit was completed by Maria.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → Who wanted to improve the grade? The passive voice hides the actor
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Correct:</span> <strong style="color: #16a34a;">To improve her grade</strong>, <strong style="text-decoration: underline;">Maria</strong> completed extra credit.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Fixing Dangling Modifiers: Two Strategies
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
You can fix dangling modifiers in two ways: add the missing subject after the comma, or convert the modifier into a full clause with its own subject.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Original (dangling):</strong> After studying for hours, the test seemed easy.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Fix #1 (add subject):</span> After studying for hours, <strong style="color: #16a34a;">I found</strong> the test seemed easy.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Fix #2 (add clause):</span> After <strong style="color: #16a34a;">I studied</strong> for hours, the test seemed easy.
  </p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background-color: #fef3c7; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b;">
<strong style="color: #92400e;">ACT Strategy:</strong> When you see an introductory phrase, immediately check what comes after the comma. If it''s not the word being described, you''ve found a dangling modifier error.
</p>


<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Advanced Modifier Issues
</h3>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Beyond basic misplaced and dangling modifiers, the ACT tests more subtle issues including relative clause placement, modifier overload, and logical modification. Mastering these advanced concepts helps you catch errors that many students miss.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Misplaced Relative Clauses
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Relative clauses (starting with who, which, that) should immediately follow the noun they modify.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Misplaced:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">The car was found by police that had been stolen.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → This suggests the police had been stolen
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Correct:</span> The car <strong style="color: #16a34a;">that had been stolen</strong> was found by police.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Split Infinitives
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
While split infinitives (placing a word between "to" and the verb) are increasingly accepted in modern English, the ACT may test your awareness of them. Generally, avoid splitting infinitives when an alternative sounds natural.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Split infinitive:</strong> She decided to <strong style="color: #2563eb;">quickly</strong> finish her homework.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Preferred:</span> She decided to finish her homework <strong style="color: #16a34a;">quickly</strong>.
  </p>
</div>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Note: Sometimes split infinitives are the clearest option ("to boldly go"). On the ACT, if moving the modifier creates awkwardness, the split infinitive may be acceptable.
</p>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Modifier Overload and Clarity
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Too many modifiers, especially when stacked together, create confusion. Sometimes the best fix is restructuring the sentence.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Confusing:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">The extremely highly successfully performing students received awards.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → Too many modifiers create awkwardness
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Clear:</span> The students who performed <strong style="color: #16a34a;">extremely well</strong> received awards.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
Logical Modification
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Beyond grammar rules, modifiers must make logical sense. Ask: Can this modifier actually describe this noun?
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fef2f2;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;">✗ Illogical:</span> <span style="color: #64748b;">As a young child, my mother told me stories.</span>
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1rem; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; color: #64748b; font-style: italic;">
    → Grammatically this says "mother" was the young child
  </p>
</div>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Logical:</span> When <strong style="color: #16a34a;">I was</strong> a young child, my mother told me stories.
  </p>
  <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓ Logical:</strong> As a young <strong style="color: #16a34a;">parent</strong>, my mother told me stories.
  </p>
</div>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;">
ACT Modifier Question Pattern
</h4>

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
On the ACT, modifier questions typically offer four answer choices that reposition the modifier or restructure the sentence. The correct answer will place the modifier logically next to what it describes.
</p>

<div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;">
  <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: #1e293b;">
    <strong style="color: #2563eb;">Strategy:</strong> For each answer choice, ask: "What does the opening phrase describe?" Then check if that word comes immediately after the comma.
  </p>
</div>


