<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Proximity principle: Place modifiers as close as possible to the words they modify; introductory phrases must be followed immediately by the word they describe
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Misplaced modifiers: Modifiers positioned too far from their target create confusion; limiting modifiers (only, nearly, almost, just) must be placed immediately before what they modify; squinting modifiers appear between two words and could modify either
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Dangling modifiers: Occur when the word being modified is missing from the sentence entirely; fix by adding the missing subject after the comma or converting the modifier to a full clause with its own subject
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Participial and infinitive phrases: When these begin sentences, the subject they describe must immediately follow the comma; passive voice often creates dangling modifiers by hiding the actor
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>ACT strategy: When you see an introductory phrase, immediately check what follows the comma—if it''s not the word being described, you''ve found a modifier error; relative clauses (who, which, that) must directly follow the nouns they modify
  </li>
</ul>
